<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Money Recovered,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money-Filled Suitcase Recovered From Crash Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suitcase reportedly containing
$30,000 has been recovered from a plane that crashed in the woods
here, killing three people, authorities said.
   The suitcase of Simon Siegel, 66, of Brookline, Mass., was found
Saturday, said police Lt. Frank Lentz.
   He would not discuss the contents, saying only that it contained
personal belongings. The Press of Atlantic City on Tuesday quoted
sources as saying it contained $30,000.
   Siegel, owner of Siegel's Egg Company in Roxbury, Mass., was
flying to an Atlantic City casino Friday when the plane crashed,
killing him, the pilot and co-pilot.
   The Siegel family attorney is expected to arrive later this week
to reclaim the bag, Lentz said.
</TEXT>
