<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbsenteeAdventists     02-24 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Absentee Adventists,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Adventists, Others Can Cast Absentee Ballots In Saturday
Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who observe the Sabbath on
Saturdays have the right to cast absentee ballots in elections held
on Saturdays, a federal judge ruled.
   In a case arising from West Virginia's March 5 constitutional
amendment election, U.S. District Judge William M. Kidd issued a
preliminary injunction Tuesday in favor of two Seventh-day
Adventists who had been told they could not submit absentee ballots
for the Saturday voting.
   The ruling also affects Jews, Seventh-day Baptists, and members
of other religious groups who believe that they should not
participate in any civic, business, governmental or non-essential
work on Saturdays.
   Karen and Howard Conner, school bus drivers in Barbour County,
contended that because of their religious beliefs, they were being
deprived of their right to vote on a proposed amendment that would
establish a statewide property tax for education.
   West Virginia usually holds elections on Tuesdays, but moved
this one to Saturday in hopes of boosting turnout. The election was
set after a state court ruled that the state must equalize spending
among school systems.
   The Conners were told by the secretary of state's office that
they did not qualify for absentee voting under state law. They then
filed suit in state court against Secretary of State Ken Hechler
and Barbour County Circuit Clerk Jean Green.
   The state Supreme Court earlier this month refused to hear the
case, so the Conners took it to the federal court.
   Kidd ordered Hechler to submit by Friday a plan ``outlining
measures to be taken to ensure that plaintiffs and members of this
class are permitted to vote in the forthcoming election.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
