<NOTE>Eds: Version of the following item moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Basketball star Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson told
1,200 teen-agers that he never should have dropped out of college
and still intends to get his degree.
   Johnson, who led the Los Angeles Lakers to four National
Basketball Association championships in his eight years with the
club, spoke to a cheering throng Monday at Westchester High School,
which has a 30 percent dropout rate.
   ``I am 40 hours short of my degree in telecommunications, but I
intend to get it,'' he said.
   ``My first year of high school, I was hoopin' good,'' recalled
Johnson of his childhood in Lansing, Mich. ``But my grades were
real low. My counselor pulled on my coattails and told me, `You are
getting Ds and Cs and Es. You won't go to college and play ball if
you don't pull 'em up.''
   There were a few gasps from the audience.
   ``If she didn't get to me I might not be standing here rapping
to you. I might be somewhere else. It's never too late to get
yourself together.''
   Asked about his future, Johnson said he hoped to play five or
six more years with the Lakers, ``then I'd like to get into my
businesses. Hopefully, I will own a building 18-20 stories high and
maybe hire a few of you.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jazz pianist-composer Billy Taylor says money
spent sending American artists to festivals abroad is money well
spent.
   ``In traveling to places like a jazz festival in India, I've
seen Russia, Japan, France, Australia, sent their best,'' Taylor
said Tuesday. Other nations know about American music through
records, but ``that knowledge is flawed if they don't get some of
our very best. We have to find measures to at least be competitive
in this way.''
   Taylor was attending an announcement by the Rockefeller
Foundation, U.S. Information Agency and National Endowment for the
Arts of a fund to support the sending of U.S. artists to
international festivals and exhibitions.
   ``One of the things I find, traveling around the world, is that
I become intensely patriotic,'' said Taylor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aston Martin, the U.S.-owned purveyor of expensive
sports cars, kept up its ties with the British royal family by
giving scaled-down cars to the young sons of Prince Charles and
Princess Diana.
   Company chairman and chief executive Victor Gauntlett made the
presentation Tuesday. But 5-year-old Prince William and 3-year-old
Prince Harry may have to wait a while before getting behind the
wheels. Asked if his children are ready to drive, the Prince of
Wales said, ``Gracious, no.''
   The 8.5-foot-long, 4@7-scale Aston Martins each cost about
$17,500. They are equipped with stereo radios and cassette players,
electrically powered aerials, five-speed gearboxes, leather
upholstery, headlights and turn signals.
   Aston Martin, which is controlled by the American manufacturer
Ford, said the junior cars are like the Aston Martin V-8 Volante
that Charles drives in virtually every detail. Instead of a V-8
British-built engine capable of a maximum speed of 153 mph,
however, they are powered by a Honda engine made in Japan and tuned
to reach 25 mph.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norman Loyd, who plays the grandfatherly
Dr. Auschlander in television's ``St. Elsewhere,'' has joined a
hospital's drive to recruit nurses.
   ``I must say this is a little nicer than St. Elsewhere,'' the
fictional inner-city Boston hospital featured in the NBC-TV series,
Loyd observed Tuesday as he walked down the corridor at Heartland
Hospital East. ``I think I'll ask them to change the set.''
   Loyd will star in a 10-minute video to be distributed nationwide
in Heartland's search for nursing personnel. He took time between
takes to shake hands with Heartland employees.
   ``Having him in it will be an attention getter _ something we
hope will catch the eye of nurses who might be looking for a
position,'' said Debi Yancer, associate director of patient care
services.
   The video will be shown at career days, placement fairs and at
recruitment dinners that have been spurred by the nationwide
shortage of nurses.
</TEXT>
