<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HijackingSuspect     02-24 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijacking Suspect,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Criticizes FBI Inattention To Due Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents illegally interrogated a suspected
Lebanese terrorist about a 1985 airplane hijacking when they kept
him aboard a Navy ship four days after his arrest in the
Mediterranean, a federal judge says.
   Sharply critical of the FBI's arrest and interrogation of Fawaz
Younis, U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker on Tuesday ruled
that oral and written confessions were obtained illegally from the
defendant.
   The judge suppressed the statements as evidence against Younis,
who is charged with leading five armed men who hijacked a Royal
Jordanian airliner on June 11, 1985, at Beirut International
Airport. The trial is scheduled to begin March 22 before Parker.
   The operation occurred after former FBI Director William H.
Webster had moved on to head the CIA and before William Sessions,
the bureau's current head, took office last fall.
   Defense lawyer Francis D. Carter said he was pleased with the
decision but conceded it won't necessarily help Younis' case.
Prosecutors have a variety of other evidence, including a videotape
of Younis delivering a statement to reporters before the plane was
blown up in the background.
   Oliver Revell, the bureau's executive assistant director,
participated in the arrest of Younis last Sept. 13 in waters off
Cyprus.
   Parker concluded that fractures Younis suffered on both wrists
were sustained when he was grabbed by two agents and slammed onto
the deck of an FBI-chartered yacht, to which he had been lured by
the prospect of a drug deal.
   Throbbing pain from the fractured wrists, sea sickness and the
lack of proper medical treatment ``placed him at a distinct
disadvantage where he could scarcely understand intelligently his
rights as explained and translated to him, much less be able to
voluntarily waive them.''
   The FBI agents gave Younis the only warning of his
constitutional right to remain silent shortly after he arrived
seasick on the USS Butte, a munitions boat that steamed four days
before meeting with the aircraft carrier USS Saratoga, Parker noted.
   ``They saw and knew that he was in a weakened state and
susceptible to persuasion,'' Parker said.
   Younis was kept in a windowless overheated room during the
voyage, which Parker called ``a clear abuse of the obligation to
bring the defendant before a judicial officer immediately following
his arrest.''
   The ship's ``slow voyage across the Mediterranean appeared to
serve only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a
confession,'' Parker said in his 47-page opinion.
   Only after his arrival in Washington were Younis' fractured
wrists ``correctly diagnosed and appropriately treated,'' the judge
said.
   ``We are reviewing the decision carefully,'' Timothy J. Reardon
III, principal assistant U.S. attorney, said in a statement. FBI
officials declined to comment on the decision, said spokeswoman
Susan Schnitzer.
   The judge said he was also ``extremely troubled'' by the FBI's
failure to provide Younis with a lawyer during the interrogation,
particularly since the operation to arrest him had been carefully
planned.
   ``The government was not just bringing another defendant into
the station house for questioning,'' he said, also criticizing the
FBI for not using a video camera to record the interrogations.
   In addition to the videotape of Younis at the scene, the
government also plans to present testimony from two Americans who
were among the passengers and crew taken off the plane before its
destruction.
   The FBI also can rely on the testimony of Jamal Hamdan, a
one-time friend of Younis who lured him onto the yacht. Hamdan, who
lived in Cyprus, secretly taped conversations he had with Younis
about the hijacking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0346EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Women'sStatue     02-24 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women's Statue,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What Next After a Women's Statue at Vietnam Memorial?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that a sculpture of three battle-weary
infantrymen stands near the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, some
senators want to place a bronze statue of an Army nurse nearby to
honor the 10,000 women who served in the Southeast Asia conflict.
   Several leading veterans' organizations applaud the proposal by
Sens. David Durenberger, R-Minn., and Alan Cranston, D-Calif. But
Maya Lin, the young woman architect who designed the memorial,
isn't happy.
   ``I cannot see where it will all end,'' she said at a Senate
hearing Tuesday. ``What is to stop someone from trying to add a
female statue to the Iwo Jima Memorial?''
   Ms. Lin was supported by others who warned that unless officials
stop caving in to pressure for more additions, the Vietnam memorial
will turn into a ``sculpture garden'' of special interests ranging
from native Americans to scout dogs.
   J. Carter Brown, chairman of the Commission of Fine Arts which
rejected the women's statue proposal last October, said the
original memorial _ now bearing the names of 58,156 war dead
including eight nurses on its black granite walls _ symbolically
includes all Vietnam veterans.
   He said the addition of the sculpture of three infantrymen
triggered envy among other groups who felt left out. His commission
believed that ``including a white, Army nurse would only continue
and exacerbate that process of exclusion,'' he said.
   At a crowded hearing by a Senate Energy and Natural Resources
subcommittee, Robert W. Doubek, former executive director of the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, said a woman's sculpture would
``destroy the symbolism and aesthetics of the memorial.''
   But John P. Wheeler III, chairman of the private fund which
raised $11 million to build the memorial, supported the nurse's
statue and discounted ``the threat of a sculpture garden'' cited by
critics.
   Donna-Marie Boulay, a Minneapolis lawyer who served in Vietnam
as an Army nurse, testified that the statue should be erected
because nurses shared ``the intensity, the trauma, the carnage of
war'' with infantrymen.
   She is chairman and co-founder of the Vietnam Women's Memorial
Project, a non-profit organization founded in 1984.
   Durenberger's bill, which has 56 Senate co-sponsors, specifies
that after a woman's statue is placed at the 2.2-acre site near the
Lincoln Memorial, ``the Vietnam Veterans Memorial will be complete
and no further additions to the site should be authorized or
undertaken.''
   The bill, if enacted, would require the three agencies whose
approval is required _ the Interior Department, the fine arts
commission and the National Capital Planning Commission _ to
reconsider the proposal within 90 days. The statue has been
approved by the Interior Department but rejected by the other two
agencies.
   The memorial, which is administered by the National Park
Service, has become the most popular tourist attraction among all
the federal monuments in the capital. An estimated 20 million
people have visited the memorial since it was dedicated in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PublicWorks Bjt   02-24 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Public Works, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 10:30 a.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S. Falling Down on the Public Works Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's commitment to necessities such as
transportation, water supply and waste disposal is barely adequate
and will fall far short of future needs without sharply increased
spending on public works, a federal council warned today.
   The report to the president and Congress calls for twice as much
annual capital spending for public works projects over the next
dozen years and suggests a broad range of possible money sources
from higher federal fuel taxes to local ``impact fees'' on
developers.
   ``In most cases we cannot rely simply on wiser spending. We also
must generate additional sources of funding,'' declared the report
by the National Council on Public Works Improvement.
   The council was established by Congress four years ago to take a
close look at the nation's problems with its ``infrastructure,'' a
bureaucratic term covering a variety of public projects from
highway and airport construction to water management and disposal
of toxic wastes.
   ``The quality of America's infrastructure today is barely
adequate to meet current requirements and insufficient to meet the
demands of future economic growth,'' the report concludes.
   The group acknowledged that major increases in spending for
public works may be difficult amid growing federal budget
pressures, and perhaps even impossible until the federal budget
deficit is reduced. But it said such spending ``must rank high
among our priorities.''
   In a report card on each major type of public works, the council
gave no failing grades but suggested that a far better job needs to
be done in all areas. The country's battle to deal with toxic
wastes was given a D, and a C or C-minus was awarded for coping
with mass transit, solid waste disposal and waste water treatment
needs.
   Managing water resources was given a B, the best grade, followed
by B-minuses for aviation and water supply management.
   ``In general the aviation system has handled rapid increases in
demand safely and effectively. ... Congestion is the system's
primary problem,'' said the council.
   Discussing hazardous wastes, the council said that while
spending to clean up contaminated sites has increased fivefold in
the last two years, ``only a small fraction of the 2 tons of waste
per capita produced in America each year is being treated safely.''
   On water quality, the council suggested that governments at all
levels have been fighting a losing battle.
   ``Despite (a) $44 billion federal investment in sewage treatment
since 1972, water quality has not improved significantly. ... due
in part to uncontrolled sources of pollution such as run-off from
farmland and roadways,'' said the report.
   Overall capital spending for public works projects totaled $45
billion in 1985, the latest year for which figures were available.
The council said the amount of spending by all levels of government
and the private sector will have to double by the end of this
century if future needs are to be met.
   The report said overall spending on public works has declined
from 3.6 percent of gross national product in 1960 to 2.6 percent
in 1985. While spending on operations and maintenance has kept pace
with economic growth, capital spending has fallen from 2.3 percent
of GNP to 1.1 percent.
   Government spending for public works at all levels has declined
from 20 percent of total government spending in 1950 to 7 percent
in 1984, the report continued.
   ``In effect we're drawing down past investments without making
commensurate investments of our own,'' said the report. ``Failure
to reverse this decline will exact a high price for the nation in
the future both in the cost of deferred investment and in reduced
economic competitiveness.''
   The council endorsed the ``general principle'' that users and
beneficiaries of public works projects, including developers, be
required to pay a greater share of the cost of such projects.
   It also criticized the hoarding of money in various federal
public works trust funds so that the federal budget deficit will
appear smaller. In 1987 the unspent balances in the federal
highway, transit, aviation and waterway trust funds totaled nearly
$24 billion, the council said.
   ``Federal user fees paid in good faith by beneficiaries to
preserve and protect public works systems (should) be spent for
that purpose,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
