<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Panama'sPresident Bjt   02-24 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama's President, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle May Be Ready to Break with Noriega, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say they are receiving signs
that Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle may be ready to
disassociate himself from military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Any such move would further weaken Noriega and possibly hasten
his demise as the dominant force in Panamanian politics, the
officials said.
   The Reagan administration looks upon Noriega as the principal
obstacle blocking its goal of an eventual transition to elected,
civilian-led rule in Panama.
   The officials, who asked not to be identified, said Delvalle has
privately expressed his intention for many weeks to distance
himself from Noriega but they recognize that such a step would
require considerable courage.
   ``We get information from all sorts of sources, including
friends and relatives, that he is about to do something along these
lines,'' one official said. Congressional sources, also insisting
on anonymity, said they have heard the same reports.
   Since last summer, the administration has been publicly
encouraging Panama's military officers to withdraw from politics as
a means of promoting a return to rule by civilians. In the
meantime, much of the U.S. aid program to Panama has been suspended
and Panama has expelled all U.S. aid personnel.
   Two federal indictments against Noriega on drug trafficking
charges added a new dimension to the already strained relationship.
The indictments, handed down in Florida earlier this month,
portrayed Noriega as a key member of an international drug
smuggling conspiracy. In the Congress, opposition to Noriega spans
the political spectrum.
   Delvalle assumed the presidency in 1985 under circumstances
which strongly suggested that Noriega had forced his predecessor,
Nicolas Ardito Barletta, from office.
   It was a constitutional succession but Delvalle has been widely
perceived as no more than Panama's titular head.
   Noriega has maintained that executive authority rests with
Delvalle and that Panama has achieved a full transition to
democracy. Noriega says his U.S. critics are campaigning against
him for the purpose of annulling the Panama Canal treaties, under
which the waterway reverts to Panamanian control at the end of 1999.
   Attempts to obtain comment from the Panamanian Embassy on
Delvalle's purported intentions were not successful.
   For the United States, the stakes in Panama are extraordinarily
high. The administration believes that a democratic, politically
stable Panama offers the best assurance for the continued efficient
operation of the canal.
   The U.S. officials noted that challenging Noriega would not be
an easy step for Delvalle. They said Delvalle's extensive business
interests and his family could be threatened if he breaks with
Noriega. In addition, Delvalle's health is said to be tenuous
because of a heart operation.
   However, the officials said Delvalle has become increasingly
disturbed by his ties to Noriega and that some of his friends have
rebuffed him because of that association.
   Delvalle also may be tempted to act because of Panama's growing
financial crisis. ``The country is falling apart all around him,''
said one source.
   Lawrence Chewning Fabrega, a Panamanian diplomat who resigned
recently in protest over Noriega's rule, said in an interview this
week that the country's financial problems are so severe the
government may not be able to meet its payroll next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0320EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBIInfiltration Bjt   02-24 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI Infiltration, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Stung by Complaints of Vietnam-Era Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stung by complaints that it revived
Vietnam-era spying on political protesters, the FBI has initiated
top-level reviews of terrorism investigations that could interfere
with legitimate activity.
   FBI officials said Tuesday that the policy results from problems
with an increasingly controversial investigation of a group
opposing President Reagan's Central America policies.
   In that probe, some FBI field offices came ``very close'' to
conducting an improper political investigation of the Committee In
Solidarity with the People of El Salvador, despite warnings from
headquarters, said FBI Executive Assistant Director Oliver B.
Revell.
   While vigorously defending the legitimacy of the March 1983-June
1985 investigation, Revell told the Senate Intelligence Committee
that neither he nor former FBI Director William Webster _ now head
of the CIA _ closely supervised the probe.
   The investigation ended without filing of any charges, but
before it was completed FBI agents had collected information not
only on CISPES members but also more than a hundred other groups
and individuals opposed to Reagan policies. Targets of the
surveillance included Roman Catholic nuns, college professors and
labor union officials.
   FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer acknowledged to a reporter that
the new reviews were ``related to'' the First Amendment concerns
arising from the CISPES investigation.
   In addition, FBI Director William Sessions has ordered an
internal investigation of the bureau's conduct specifically in the
CISPES case.
   CISPES has accused the FBI of investigating its members solely
because of its political stance, recalling FBI surveillance of
opponents of the Vietnam War.
   The Vietnam-era surveillance came under intense congressional
criticism in the 1970s and led to attorney general's guidelines
intended to govern the bureau's investigative conduct.
   Tuesday, several members of the Senate Intelligence Committee
told Revell they believe the bureau acted on flimsy evidence to
keep the CISPES investigation alive.
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, complained that CISPES was targeted
for ``a nationwide dragnet-type operation'' while investigations of
Reagan's Central America supporters were ``much more limited, more
surgical.''
   Revell said ``we have taken interim steps to increase the level
of review'' of sensitive investigations conducted under the largely
classified guidelines for international terrorism probes.
   Under the new policy, Ms. Schnitzer said, the conduct of
international terrorism investigations will be reviewed by a deputy
assistant director who reports to Revell _ who has responsibility
for all criminal investigations.
   Revell told the senators that Webster was ``aware of several
cables sent to him for informational purposes'' in the CISPES
probe, but ``he did not authorize, nor did I authorize any
supervisory activity. That occurred at the sectional level'' three
steps below Revell.
   Ms. Schnitzer said Webster and Revell ``had a limited amount of
knowledge'' of the CISPES investigation.
   International terrorism investigations _ such as the CISPES
probe _ are conducted under guidelines which do not require the FBI
to have evidence of a specific crime.
   In the CISPES investigation, the FBI said it had information
that some CISPES members were planning violent activities in the
United States, possibly in conjunction with the FMLN _ the
coalition fighting the U.S.-backed government of El Salvador. The
bureau characterizes the FMLN as a ``terrorist'' organization.
   The bureau also said CISPES members were investigated after
bombings at the U.S. Capitol and the Army National War College at
Fort McNair in Washington in 1983, although no evidence against
them was found.
   Revell said much of the information that started and fueled the
investigation came from Frank Varelli, a former informant in Dallas
whose information proved to be a ``mixed bag ... some blatantly
false, some concocted in his own mind.''
   ``That did result in the investigation being misled in certain
material facts,'' said Revell, adding the bureau only discovered
the problem ``after the fact.''
   Varelli is now suing the FBI, saying it still owes him money for
his informant work.
   Revell also said the FBI made a mistake when it disseminated _
under a ``secret'' classification _ derogatory information received
about CISPES from a conservative group. The information from the
Young America's Foundation was sent to 33 field offices.
   ``I did not approve it or sign it,'' Revell said. ``I would not
have. ... It was inappropriate to indicate that the views of
another organization should be considered by our investigators.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
