<DOCNO> AP880224-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Senegal-Election Bjt   02-24 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senegal-Election, Bjt,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War Of Words Escalates In Final Days of Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This West African nation votes for
president and National Assembly on Sunday in a multiparty election,
a rarity on a continent dominated by one-party and military
governments.
   With only five days left until national elections, the war of
words escalated Tuesday as four presidential candidates and six
political parties wound up campaigning.
   Opposition politicians accused the Socialist Party, which has
ruled since independence from France in 1960, of rigging Sunday's
elections in advance and sending armed militias to break up
opposition party gatherings.
   The president and Socialist leader, Abdou Diouf, 52, a tall,
angular technocrat, is widely expected to retain his seat and
legislative majority.
   But young voters in some urban areas may back Abdoulaye Wade, a
61-year-old lawyer who leads the Senegalese Democratic Party, the
country's largest opposition group. Wade has called for change in
the government's generally conservative, pro-Western policies.
   Tensions were high in the cities, where there have been sporadic
student strikes and stone-throwing incidents between young
supporters of the different parties.
   Wade's party has formed its own ``people's resistance
committees'' to safeguard its meetings.
   ``We will mobilize our supporters to go to the polling
stations,'' said Ousmane Ngom, a party spokesman. ``If we see
fraud, we will occupy the Interior and Communications ministries to
prevent them from announcing their fraudulent results. If we think
we have the majority, we will declare victory and declare a new
government.''
   Diouf said Monday the government was ``prepared to deal with all
excesses,'' and there will be ``no liberty for the enemies of
liberty.'' He has insisted the elections will be free, fair and
democratic.
   Diouf has governed the country since 1981, when he took over
from retiring leader Leopold Sedar Senghor.
   Other candidates in the presidential race are Babacar Niang, 59,
of the People's Liberation Party, and Landing Savane, 43, of the
Revolutionary Movement for a New Democracy.
   Niang and Savane, a Maoist, have both said they have little
chance of winning and are participating to show there is an
alternative to the Socialists.
   Serigne Diop, former Wade supporter and leader of the Senegalese
Democratic Party for Renovation, backed Diouf's candidacy but hoped
to win legislative seats for his own party.
   The Marxist-oriented Democratic League-Labor Movement, led by
Abdoulaye Bathily, 43, also offered only legislative candidates.
   In 1983, Diouf retained the presidency and his party took 111 of
the 120 seats in the National Assembly in the country's first
multiparty elections. Wade and other opposition politicians claimed
that election was marred by fraud.
   Wade has again accused the government of distributing voter
registration cards through Diouf's party rather than through
independent registration committees. He also said the government
radio, television and semi-official Le Soleil newspaper have given
preferential coverage to Socialist candidates.
   Opposition politicians have criticized the country's austerity
program, which is backed by the International Monetary Fund and
World Bank, but which has brought a reduction on civil service
openings for university graduates and other belt-tightening
measures.
   Earlier this month, four Senegalese gendarmes, two
non-commissioned officers and three police sergeants were arrested
on charges of plotting the secession of the Casamance, Senegal's
southernmost province.
   Violent separatist demonstrations led by ethnic Diola agitators
in the Casamance capital, Ziguinchor, in December 1983, caused more
than 100 deaths. Scores of ringleaders were later sentenced to long
prison terms and the main secessionist association was outlawed.
   Senegal has a population of 7 million. The largely agricultural
nation has suffered from recurring droughts and the southern
advance of the Sahara desert. Its chief export is groundnuts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
