<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Prostitute-AIDSBill     02-24 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Prostitute-AIDS Bill,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prostitute Lobbies Legislators Against AIDS Testing Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An admitted prostitute led a protest
at the Capitol against a bill that would require AIDS tests for
convicted prostitutes and their customers.
   ``Prostitutes are not spreading AIDS,'' Carol Leigh said Tuesday
at a rally outside the capitol. She and about a dozen demonstrators
accused lawmakers of making prostitutes the scapegoats in political
battles over AIDS.
   ``Prostitutes use safe sex,'' said Leigh. ``Do ordinary people
use safe sex? No.''
   ``We want (AIDS) education. We want to be able to do a good
job,'' said Leigh, a member of the prostitutes' rights group, Cast
Off Your Old Tired Ethics (COYOTE).
   The bill would require prostitutes and their customers to
complete an education course and undergo screening for acquired
immune deficiency syndrome after their first conviction.
   A vote on the bill is scheduled for next week.
</TEXT>
