<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UMW-OCAW 1stLd-Writethru a0771 02-24 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UMW-OCAW, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0771,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede CHARLESTON, W.Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miners, OCAW Reject Merger of Energy Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with merger talks collapsing,
comments from both unions. Picks up 10th graf pvs `Before a ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers on Tuesday
rejected a proposed merger with the United Mine Workers, just hours
before the two unions were poised to announce the deal, officials
said.
   ``There's a decision from OCAW not to go forward,'' that union's
spokesman, Rod Rogers, said late Tuesday. ``I don't know that that
sets everything in concrete. But that's where it stands for now.''
   A news conference had been tentatively set for Wednesday to
announce the merger, but the OCAW backed out after meeting with UMW
leaders most of Tuesday afternoon.
   The merger was intended to bolster the strength of the two
energy workers' unions, whose memberships have been shrinking
throughout the last decade.
   The OCAW's rejection sent UMW President Richard Trumka and his
executive board members into a late-night meeting at a Denver hotel.
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said only that ``a snag'' had come
``from the OCAW side, not the UMW.''
   The UMW board had voted Sunday in Denver to approve the merger,
a union source said. It was not clear Tuesday night whether UMW
officials would make any further offers to the OCAW.
   Rogers said earlier Tuesday that a merger between the unions,
which each claim about 100,000 active members, would be logical for
several reasons, including ``consolidation of resources.''
   ``Nowadays we (the two unions) are kind of in the posture of
negotiating with the same companies, and that's because the major
oil companies own the lion's share of the energy and coal reserves
in the United States,'' he said.
   A cooperative negotiating effort between the two unions was
announced in 1986 at a special UMW constitutional convention
attended by OCAW President Joseph Misbrener.
   At that convention, the miners' union also gave Trumka and the
union's 24-member governing board the power to approve affiliations
or mergers with other unions.
   Before a merger could take effect, however, it would have to be
approved by OCAW's rank-and-file at a constitutional convention.
The union's next regularly scheduled convention is in August.
   At the UMW's 1986 convention, Trumka told delegates that the two
unions would work to compile information on their common employers
leading to their coincidental contract expiration date, Jan. 31,
1988.
   ``The two titans of the energy union movement, the Mine Workers
and the OCAW, have agreed to link themselves with computer and to
share information about the multinationals where we both represent
our members,'' Trumka said.
   The UMW and the Bituminous Coal Operators Association have
ratified a new national wage agreement, but the UMW is continuing
negotiations with the Pittston Coal Group Inc., a major producer
that dropped out of the association.
   OCAW has reached contract agreements with all the major oil
companies. However, strikes are in progress at four refineries
owned by Mobil Oil or British Petroleum, which also owns Standard
Oil of Ohio.
   About one-third of the OCAW membership is covered by new
contracts, with negotations for the rest continuing at the district
level, Rogers said.
</TEXT>
