<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-NewsConference     02-24 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-News Conference,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Holds First News Conference In Four Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain; news conference at 8 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After four months without a news conference,
President Reagan faces questions tonight on hostage-taking in
Lebanon, Israel's crackdown in the occupied territories, and the
bitter fight by Republicans wanting to succeed him.
   Reagan also may be asked about his embattled attorney general,
Edwin Meese III, the target of an investigation by an independent
counsel, and the separate felony convictions of former White House
aides and presidential confidants Lyn Nofziger and Michael K.
Deaver.
   Also still awaited is Reagan's reaction to a plan by House
Democrats for $25 million in ``humanitarian'' aid for Nicaragua's
Contras, a package that was put together after rejection of the
president's proposal to give the rebels new weapons.
   On the political front, Reagan has doggedly steered clear of
involvement in the GOP presidential race. However, he may be
tempted to comment on the increasingly sharp words between
Republicans, given that he is the author of the so-called 11th
commandment forbidding Republicans to speak ill of each other.
   The 8 p.m. EST session in the East Room will be Reagan's first
news conference since last Oct. 22, which was dominated by
questions about the 508-point collapse of the stock market.
   A lot has happened since then, and Reagan has had little to say
except in prepared speeches. He has been largely isolated from the
press, commenting only occasionally in response to a shouted
question as he boards a helicopter or to a query during a
picture-taking ceremony in the Oval Office.
   Tonight's session comes amid intense diplomatic activity by
Secretary of State George Shultz in Moscow and the Middle East.
   Shultz, who arrived back in Washington on Tuesday evening, was
reporting to Reagan today on his talks in Moscow about arms
control, the timing of a superpower summit and the likelihood of a
Red Army pullout from Afghanistan.
   All of those issues pose possible questions for Reagan.
   With barely a day back in the capital, Shultz leaves again
tonight, this time to the Middle East where he will meet with Arab
and Israeli leaders about efforts to revive peace negotiations.
   White House officials say there is an urgency to Shultz' efforts
in the Middle East because of the violence in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza. The United Nations says 63 Palestinians have been
killed by Israeli gunfire since violence began Dec. 8.
   Shultz said Tuesday he has encountered ``intense skepticism''
about the chances of a breakthrough on Middle East negotiations,
but the United States has ``a few ideas'' that could help end the
deadlock.
   Reagan likely will be asked about the kidnapping in Lebanon of
Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins and the eight other Americans
seized there.
   Higgins, onetime aide to former Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger, was serving with U.N. forces when he was taken in
southern Lebanon last Wednesday. Reagan raised some questions by
saying he wanted ``to rescue'' Higgins, but aides later clarified
that he was referring to diplomatic efforts, not a military
maneuver.
   A group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth claims to have abducted Higgins. The group is demanding
Israeli withdrawal from the ``security zone'' it maintains in south
Lebanon, release of Palestinian and Lebanese prisoners held by
Israel and suspension of U.S. diplomatic activity in the Middle
East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0518EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BidenHealth     02-24 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biden Health,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Senator Released From Hospital, But Faces More Brain
Surgery</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. wore a blue baseball
cap to hide his scar as he left Walter Reed Army Medical Center 12
days after undergoing brain surgery that will have to be repeated
in a few months.
   Doctors said they were ``delighted'' with Biden's recovery from
surgery Feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm in an artery supplying blood
to the senator's brain.
   But a hospital statement said that a second aneurysm has been
found and will have to be corrected later.
   Biden, 45, left the hospital Tuesday by car with his wife, Jill,
and his brother, Jim Biden of Washington.
   A family spokesman, Larry Rasky, said the Democrat from Delaware
was under orders to rest at home and was to have no visitors nor be
given office work.
   Biden, said Rasky, is ``in great shape and great spirits. He's
full of vigor. I think if the doctors hadn't told him to rest, he
could have gone to the office.''
   Rasky said the family purposely avoided announcing the senator's
plan to leave the hospital in order to avoid the stress of any
media interest.
   But Biden and his wife paused briefly beside their car to pose
for a photographer. Biden's blue cap covered the scar on his left
temple where the surgical incision was made. He smiled broadly as
the camera shutter clicked.
   The hospital statement said neurosurgeons earlier had found the
additional aneurysm on the opposite side of the brain from the
aneurysm that was repaired.
   ``The second aneurysm is smaller and could not be approached
during the earlier surgery,'' the statement said. ``There were no
signs of leakage, but the second aneurysm will require surgical
repair.''
   No date has been set for the new operation, the statement said.
It added: ``Procedures of this type are usually done after the
patient has fully recovered from any earlier surgery, usually
within two to three months.''
   Rasky said doctors told Biden the second surgery could come in
less than three months, if his recovery went well, and that
recovery from the new operation would take less time. But the
spokesman said the senator will not return to his Washington office
until he has recovered from the second surgery.
   A doctor associated with the case, who asked not to be
identified, said that about 15 percent of all patients with one
cerebral aneurysm will develop another. If the aneurysm is small,
stable and not bleeding, he said, it can be left and repaired later.
   Biden's release just 12 days after surgery, said the doctor,
shows ``he is doing very well.''
   An aneurysm is a weakened area in an artery. The pressure of
blood flow causes the area to balloon, forming a blister-like flaw
on the artery side.
   Aneurysms are dangerous because they can rupture suddenly and
hemorrhage, or they can leak. Such bleeding from a cerebral
aneurysm can quickly cause brain damage or death.
   Biden was admitted to Walter Reed on Feb. 12 after a
middle-of-the-night, emergency transfer from a Delaware hospital.
He had been taken to the Delaware hospital the day before after
experiencing severe neck pain and nausea.
   An X-ray test located the aneursym within his skull and he
underwent surgery within hours.
   The doctor associated with the case said then that about
one-third of all patients with cerebral aneurysms die.
   Typically, the doctor said, surgery for a brain aneurysm
requires an incision in the temple area. Surgeons then cut a small
window in the skull to enable them to lift the brain slightly and
locate the flawed artery.
   The aneurysm is corrected by permanently attaching a clip, a
small metal device with locking jaws, at the base of the
blister-like flaw and parallel to the blood flow. Eventually, the
artery will heal itself.
   Biden had been treated for a neck pain that started two weeks
before his surgery. A doctor diagnosed the ailment as a pinched
nerve and possibly a viral infection of neck muscles. The senator
wore a neck brace as treatment.
   When the pain left after several days, Biden abandoned the brace
and went on a speaking tour. But the pain, along with nausea,
recurred. The senator was admitted to a hospital near his
Wilmington, Del., home and then transferred by ambulance to Walter
Reed.
   A doctor said an aneurysm leaking into the brain cavity can
cause neck pain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0509EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Pipeline     02-24 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Pipeline,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Quid Pro Quo Latin For `Planned Payoff'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``quid pro quo'' in a memo to Attorney
General Edwin Meese III may be a planned payoff to the Israeli
Labor Party, say government sources familiar with a criminal
investigation of Meese.
   The Sept. 25, 1985, memo from longtime Meese friend E. Robert
Wallach discusses an Israeli commitment not to bomb a proposed $1
billion Iraqi oil pipeline.
   ``We all recognize that there would be no progress to this
point'' had Israeli-born Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport ``not been
able to obtain the security package which involves the
never-to-be-stated but fully understood quid pro quo which helped
to produce that commitment,'' said Wallach's memo. The memo doesn't
elaborate.
   Meese's attorneys say the ``quid pro quo'' is a reference to an
agreement that Rappaport, a partner in the proposed pipeline, would
make available to Israel substantial amounts of oil generated from
the project. Wallach was Rappaport's lawyer.
   However, investigators for independent counsel James McKay
question the explanation of Meese's lawyers and are seeking to
determine whether the language may be a reference to planned
payments to the Labor Party, said the government sources, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Wallach gave Meese the ``quid pro quo'' memo, along with a
handwritten letter from then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in
which Peres said he ``would go a long way to help'' the pipeline.
   One of Meese's lawyers, James Rocap, said the attorney general
doesn't recall any discussion of the memo with Wallach, who
hand-delivered the documents to the attorney general. Rocap said
Meese did not read the memo closely.
   Wallach's memo urged Meese to enlist support for the pipeline
project from top U.S. officials, hinting that he might talk to
Secretary of State George Shultz about it and then proposing a
discussion with President Reagan.
   Meese's lawyers say he took none of the initiatives suggested by
Wallach, but only referred Peres to the office of then-National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane.
   A separate Wallach-to-Meese memo also dated Sept. 25, 1985,
spells out Rappaport's close ties to Peres, saying the businessman
described an arrangement in which Israel will receive up to $700
million over 10 years from the pipeline.
   ``What was also indicated to me, and which would be denied
everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to
Labor,'' says the second memo, the focal point of McKay's criminal
investigation. Meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of
the document relating to Labor Party payments.
   The independent counsel is investigating whether Meese knew of a
possibly improper payment plan involving the Israeli political
party and, if so, why he did not do something about it.
   The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act makes it illegal for U.S.
citizens, companies or their agents to offer foreign officials
anything of value to influence them to provide help in business
matters.
   The law states that the attorney general may file a civil suit
if it appears the person or company is about to engage in an act
that would violate the law.
   Both memos were publicly released Monday, along with an exchange
of notes between Peres and Meese.
   Peres, now Israel's foreign minister, on Tuesday defended his
communications with Meese, saying: ``We all agree that we favor the
laying of the pipeline. So why would anyone need to use bribes?
Nobody said he (Meese) gave the Labor Party anything or proposed
anything to the Labor Party.''
   However, Peres acknowledged Tuesday through a spokesman in
Jerusalem that the Israeli government had been offered a discount
on oil purchases amounting to $65 million to $70 million a year in
return for approving the pipeline, The Washington Post reported in
today's editions.
   But the aide said that Peres did not take the offer seriously
and failed to pass it on to colleagues, the newspaper said.
   In another development, Arthur L. Liman, the chief counsel for
the Senate committee that investigated the Iran-Contra affair, says
the Justice Department should have turned over Wallach's memos when
the committee subpoenaed material.
   One of the memos refers to Israeli help in efforts to free
American hostages held in Lebanon, and quotes Rappaport as saying,
``There is a feeling the United States `owes' and that the
accomplishment of this (pipeline) project ... is appropriate.''
   ``I would like to have questioned Meese about this,'' Liman was
quoted as saying in today's editions of The New York Times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
