<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-24 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Against Yen; Stocks Continue Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly higher against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo today after a sharp decline the previous day,
while share prices gained for the 10th consecutive day.
   The dollar closed at 128.75, up 0.25 yen from its closing figure
of 128.50 yen Tuesday, when it lost 1.45 yen. It had opened at
128.90 yen today but never went higher, changing hands between
128.57 and 128.90 yen.
   The dollar came under selling pressure after a statement by
Satoshi Sumita, head of the Japan's central bank, who told
reporters today that the U.S. currency's sharp decline has hit
bottom, but that unstable factors remained, such as large external
imbalances among major economic countries.
   The dollar rebounded somewhat as life insurance and securities
firms went on buying the currency just before the end of trading,
Abe said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei average of 225 selected
shares, a 102.74-point winner Tuesday, took on an additional 19.20
points, or 0.07 percent, to close today's session at 24,968.65
points.
   ``The small gain shows investors are becoming careful,'' said an
analyst with Sanyo Securities, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   But he noted that the volume of trading was a hefty 1.1 billion
shares, the heaviest this year, and said: ``If the volume stays at
the current level, the stock average will easily top the
27,000-point level.''
   Large-size issues, such as shipbuildings and steels, were
bought, and chemicals, papers, brokerages and real estate issues
were firm.
</TEXT>
