<1ST_LINE>u p PM-BacktoNewEngland Bjt   02-24 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Back to New England, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once More To The Nation's Northeast Corner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 presidential campaign is making a
quick side trip to the nation's northeast corner this week for
lobster, maple syrup and votes, with Michael Dukakis and George
Bush nervously hoping for neighborly victories in Maine and Vermont.
   With their strong regional ties, Dukakis and Bush need to win
their parties' caucuses in Maine this weekend and the Vermont
primaries Tuesday to build momentum for Super Tuesday.
   But former television evangelist Pat Robertson and Senate GOP
leader Bob Dole would like to embarrass Bush in his home territory
_ especially in the wake of Bush's weak showings in Tuesday's South
Dakota primary and Minnesota caucuses.
   In both Maine and Vermont, strong Bush and Dukakis organizations
will carry the burden, for all the candidates will be spending most
of the next seven days campaigning in the South, focus of the Super
Tuesday's primaries on March 8.
   The Republican vice president will touch down for airport news
conferences today in Portland, Me., and Burlington, Vt. _ his last
scheduled visits for the week. Dukakis may be back in Maine by the
weekend.
   Bush has a home in Maine and is widely expected to be the winner
in the town caucuses in the state scattered over the weekend.
   But his campaign is worried about Robertson in Maine.
   With a usual turnout of only about 5,000 Republicans, the
caucuses are a good opportunity for success using Robertson's
tactics from other states _ flooding caucuses with new participants
and winning surprising victories.
   The Dukakis campaign, which has a strong organization on the
ground as it did in New Hampshire, faces less opposition among
Democrats, who have mostly left the states to the governor from
neighboring Massachusetts
   ``It doesn't appear that the other campaigns are taking these
states seriously,'' said Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach.
   The one possible exception to the rest of the Democratic field's
bypassing of the states is Jesse Jackson in Vermont. The Rainbow
Coalition _ formed during Jackson's 1984 presidential bid _
actually has remained active in the state and Burlington's
Socialist mayor, Bernie Sanders, has endorsed him.
   ``The Rainbow Coalition has been working hard,'' said Vermont
Democratic chief Violet Coffin.
   But Dukakis, in contrast has had 12-15 paid staffers working the
state, she said.
   Neither of the states' events has drawn a great deal of
candidate's attention for several reason.
   First, Maine and Vermont together will send 41 delegates to the
Democratic National Convention and 39 delegates to the Republican
meeting this summer. The Super Tuesday events decide which
candidates have the allegiance of 1,307 Democratic delegates and
712 GOP delegates.
   Only the Maine caucuses actually begin the delegate selection
processes; the Vermont primary on Tuesday is simply a beauty
contest expression of preference. Vermont's delegates will be
picked in the late spring in a separate caucus process.
   But the close ties that Bush has with Maine make it an excellent
chance for Robertson to stun the front-runner in his home turf.
   ``It will be a battle,'' said Ron Kaufman, Bush's Northeastern
coordinator. ``Dole has had a lot of people on the ground in Maine.
... But my concern is the Rev. Robertson.''
   It is the potential of Robertson's ``invisible army'' of
supporters to take over the GOP caucuses that worries the Bush
staff.
   Maine GOP state chairwoman Karen Stram of Dresden sees the
caucuses this way:
   ``The Bush campaign has the broadest organization. Robertson has
organized a lot of new voters. ... The Dole people have an
organization that has been working here.''
   On the Democratic side in Maine, state party chief Rick Barton
acknowledges that Dukakis has a home-field advantage, but he says
another candidate could have an impact. ``The question is whether
anybody is making an effort here'' besides Dukakis, Barton said.
   And he pointed out that there is a seventh candidate contending
in the Maine caucuses _ uncommitted. Led by Maine House leader John
Diamond, party activists have been pushing for uncommitted
delegates to be elected at the city and town meetings.
   In Vermont, Dole has the potential for a good showing, although
the vice president is credited with a broader organization. Dole
has the backing of several GOP leaders, including former Gov.
Richard Snelling.
   Vermont Republican party chief Ralph Howe said Dole _ from the
farm state of Kansas _ has also won points with the state's dairy
farmers by supporting changes in the milk price support program
that Bush has not endorsed.
   In Dukakis' home state of Massachusetts, which votes on Super
Tuesday, the governor enjoys a prohibitive lead among Democratic
presidential candidates, while Bush leads the GOP field, a new poll
indicates.
   The survey, commissioned by WCVB-TV in Boston, WEEI radio and
The Boston Globe, was conducted by the Gallup organization among
Massachusetts voters last weekend. It said Dukakis led with 61
percent support, with Gephardt trailing with 13 percent. The other
Democrats finished in single digits.
   In the Republican race, Bush _ a Massachusetts native _ led with
49 percent, compared to 29 percent saying they support Dole. Those
others were in single digits, with 8 percent undecided.
   The telephone survey of presidential preference involved 639
registered Democrats with a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percent. The poll also reached 331 Republicans, with a margin of
error of plus or minus 6 percent.
</TEXT>
