<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ElectionsAnalysis Bjt   02-24 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elections Analysis, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good Thing for Bush: All Caucuses are Not Created Equal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some elections are more equal than others, fortunately for
George Bush. He was trounced twice in Republican presidential
contests, but he'd left the scene of the landslides.
   Sen. Bob Dole, who won a runaway in South Dakota and a
comfortable victory in Minnesota, said he had gained major headway
as the GOP race moved toward the South.
   ``It pays to come to South Dakota,'' he said Tuesday night in
Sioux Falls.
   But the pay wasn't very high.
   Dole apparently swept the delegates at stake in South Dakota _
all 18 of them. Pat Robertson was second, just below the 20 percent
it took to share in the delegation. Bush lagged narrowly behind him.
   But compare that delegate payoff to Texas. Republicans there
will choose 111 nominating delegates on March 8, and Bush ranks as
the favorite. His role and Dole's are reversed in Texas _ the vice
president leads and the senator from Kansas has virtually written
off the state.
   In Democratic competition Tuesday, Rep. Richard Gephardt
captured South Dakota, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis won in
Minnesota, and nobody got any nominating delegates. The results
were purely advisory; the real prizes come later.
   Those results, especially the defeats Bush absorbed by running
third in South Dakota and fourth in Minnesota, were muted for lack
of the attention concentrated on the leadoff presidential contests
in Iowa and New Hampshire.
   Dole and Gephardt won in Iowa, Bush and Dukakis in New
Hampshire, in contests played to national television audiences,
with anchormen on location. The states were comparable, the stakes
were comparable, but Tuesday's contests were not magnified by being
first.
   So Bush, campaigning in London, Ky., absorbed the twin defeats
without a word of comment. It's time for targeting, and the next
one on his list comes this weekend in Maine, where he maintains a
home and where he expects to win in GOP caucuses.
   That's also a Robertson target, and the Bush camp says the
former television evangelist could pose a significant challenge in
caucuses, the kind of competition that best fits his organization.
   Robertson said Bush should pay in the national public opinion
polls for the defeats on Tuesday. ``I don't see how he's going to
continue to ride so high,'' Robertson said. ``The vice president is
definitely wounded.''
   But it is nothing Maine, and the just-for-show Vermont primary
on March 1, can't heal.
   Those contests, and the South Carolina primary on March 5, with
Robertson formidable and claiming he can win, all preface Super
Tuesday, March 8. That's a 20-state primary and caucus day, with
1,307 Democratic delegates and 712 Republicans at stake.
   That competition is concentrated in the South, but it includes a
half-dozen contests in other regions, Massachusetts to Washington.
   With candidates picking their spots and with delegates to be won
through proportional representation among the Democrats, Super
Tuesday isn't likely to be any more conclusive than what has gone
before.
   Republican rules make it more likely that one candidate can pile
up a significant delegate lead on March 8.
   Ironically, for all the efforts at calendar rigging and
early-season decisions, the pivotal primaries may still be weeks
away, in populous industrial states like Pennsylvania, New York,
Ohio, and, finally, California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Trade     02-24 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Payments and Lamb Quotas Would Get Ax Under House Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House lawmakers are hoping to melt some of the
ice around their sweeping trade bill with proposals to drop
Senate-sponsored curbs on lamb imports and $400 million in payments
to sugar refiners.
   ``I think there is a need for trade legislation,'' House Ways
and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said Tuesday
after the plan was sent to senators on a conference committee
drafting the trade bill. ``If we don't get it this year it could
very well mean that we won't get it for some time in the future.''
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas,
promised early consideration of the offer proposed by Ways and
Means Committee members who are also part of the conference
committee.
   Bentsen said there could be a reply as early as the weekend from
Finance Committee members on the conference committee. The
so-called ``subconference'' of Ways and Means and Finance members
is one of 17 such bodies that have been formed to draw up portions
of the 1,000-page bill.
   The lamb provision would limit imports of fresh chilled or
frozen lamb meat. It was attached to the Senate version of the
trade bill at the urging of Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.
   The sugar provision would let some refining companies that claim
tney are being hurt by high tariffs recover some $400 million in
duties they paid a number of years ago on imported sugar that was
refined and re-exported.
   The Reagan administration was fiercely opposed to it, saying
insufficient documents existed to administer the plan properly.
   At a news conference, Rostenkowski again expressed hope the
House would pass an overall compromise ``before the Easter recess''
but said that might not be possible.
   One issue remaining is Democratic presidential aspirant Richard
Gephardt's amendment to require 10 percent annual rollbacks in
Japanese trade surpluses with the United States.
   The measure, approved by the House, does not appear in the
Senate version and it seems likely to be changed in the final
product.
   Gephardt, a member of the Ways and Means Committee, has been
basing part of his campaign on his trade proposal and other
Democrats on the panel have been reluctant to do anything that
might be interpreted as undercutting him.
   Rostenkowski indicated that no reshaping of provisions dealing
with unfair foreign trade barriers is likely before the ``Super
Tuesday'' primaries in the South on March 8. The chairman was an
opponent of Gephardt's plan when it was debated in the House last
year.
   He indicated, however, that he would present the case for
Gephardt's plan.
   ``I've been commissioned by the House of Representatives to do
as much as I can to keep as much of it in as I can, and I'm going
to do that,'' he said.
   After a report on Monday that lawmakers would ``dump'' the
Gephardt provision following the Super Tuesday voting, Rostenkowski
issued a statement saying that ``Mr. Gephardt's amendment has not
been scuttled or jettisoned.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ACMNominations     02-24 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ACM Nominations,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daddy Would be Proud, Says Hank Williams Jr.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Repeating</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music's reigning top entertainer Hank
Williams Jr. says his Academy of Country Music Awards nominations
would have made his legendary father, and his mama, proud.
   ``I keep thinking in Ernest Tubbs' last song `Leave Them Boys
Alone,' it says, `His daddy would be proud if he could see Bocephus
now,''' Williams, whose nickname is Bocephus, said after receiving
six nominations Tuesday.
   ``I think of mama, too, she would have said, `I told you honey,
he was going to do it all the time,''' the 38-year-old son of Hank
Williams said from his home in Paris, Tenn.
   Gentleman ex-frycook Randy Travis also got nominations in the
same categories: Entertainer of the Year, vocalist, single, song,
album and video categories.
   Williams, current Country Music Association and academy
Entertainer of the Year, and Travis, who dominated the awards last
year with four trophies, are also up for Grammy Awards next month.
   ``We're very happy to be nominated and to be in such good
company,'' said Travis, 28, who fried catfish and burgers at the
Nashville Palace before getting his break.
   ``It's a great feeling to know that the industry enjoys our
music.''
   George Strait got four nominations _ top vocalist, single, song
and album. Nominees with three each were perennial favorite
Alabama, shut out on last year's show, and newcomers K.T. Oslin and
Ricky Van Shelton.
   The Bellamy Brothers, Crystal Gayle, The Judds, Reba McEntire
and Restless Heart got two apiece.
   Nominees for the 23rd annual ACM awards were announced by
country entertainers Dwight Yoakam, the group Restless Heart,
Charlie Pride and Lacy J. Dalton.
   Ballots go in the mail this week to the 2,500 academy members.
The winners will be announced March 21 during a two-hour NBC-TV
special with Williams and Miss McEntire hosts.
   In addition to Williams and Travis in the Entertainer of the
Year category are Alabama, Miss McEntire and Willie Nelson.
   The only major surprise was the poor showing of the multiple
Grammy nominee ``Trio'' album, which got the Academy's best album
nomination but no other mention for singers Dolly Parton, Linda
Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
