<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0441EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SDPolls     02-24 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SD Polls,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole's Support Broad in South Dakota, Except for Strong
Conservatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans across the ideological spectrum
helped Bob Dole win the South Dakota primary, with the exception of
strong conservatives, whose support could prove important in later
contests, exit polls said.
   Those Republicans, one fifth of the total, favored Pat
Robertson, helping the former television minister challenge Vice
President George Bush for second place in the state primary
Tuesday, an NBC News exit poll found.
   Among Democrats, many voters chose a candidate in the final days
of the South Dakota campaign, and they went strongly for Rep.
Richard Gephardt, who employed aggressive television advertising in
his winning effort, polls said.
   A third of the Democratic voters told CBS News they made up
their minds in the last three days of the race, and 45 percent of
them backed Gephardt, to 23 percent for Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, who finished second.
   The television networks based their analyses of the voting on
random surveys of South Dakotans as they left polling places. The
networks did not conduct surveys in Minnesota, which held party
caucuses Tuesday.
   Dole, the Senate minority leader from Kansas, campaigned
determinedly in South Dakota. Bush, sensing his disadvantage,
steered clear of the state. The polls said Dole prevailed in nearly
all categories; ABC News, for example, said he won more than seven
in 10 liberals and moderates and four in 10 conservatives.
   NBC separated out another category, ``very conservative''
voters, and said 42 percent went for Robertson to 32 percent for
Dole and 17 percent for Bush. Dole did poorly among very
conservative voters in New Hampshire, where Bush won last week's
primary, and NBC noted that more such voters may turn out in the
Super Tuesday southern state primaries March 8.
   When considering Dole's overall strong showing, ``The caveat is
that Bush didn't contest it,'' and that Republican turnout was
light, said Doug Muzzio, an ABC poll analyst. Still, he said,
``Bush lost almost every group he won in New Hampshire,'' including
Republicans who support President Reagan and those who are
concerned about foreign policy.
   One important outcome was ``a narrowing of the margins,'' Muzzio
said: Sen. Paul Simon, a liberal Democrat, fared poorly, as did
Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, a conservative Republican.
   ABC said Kemp got just 8 percent of the conservative Republican
vote, to Robertson's 27 percent. Robertson also won more than half
the evangelical or fundamentalist Christians, about a fifth of all
GOP voters, ABC and CBS said.
   Among the Democrats, Gephardt and Dukakis split the liberal
vote, but Gephardt won moderate and conservative Democrats, won the
male vote while splitting the female vote with Dukakis, and won
among the less wealthy and the less educated, again splitting the
others with Dukakis.
   Gephardt ``went upscale'' by doing better among the
better-educated and wealthier Democrats than he had in the past,
Muzzio said. ``The good news for Dukakis is that he did well in a
downscale state,'' he added.
   Surprisingly, the NBC News poll found that a plurality of South
Dakota Democrats, 46 percent, said they believed Dukakis eventually
will win the presidential nomination, though not all voted for him.
   Even 28 percent of those who voted for Gephardt said they
expected Dukakis to be the nominee.
   CBS reported that 40 percent of the Democrats chose farm policy
as a key issue, more than the number that selected any other
subject.
   ``Gephardt was definitely strong among people who cared about
farm policy,'' with 55 percent support to 18 percent for Dukakis,
said CBS surveys manager Pam Mitchell.
   Among the losing Democrats, NBC found that former Sen. Gary Hart
of Colorado was viewed unfavorably by twice as many South Dakotans
as viewed him favorably, and 55 percent were not pleased that Hart
re-entered the race after withdrawing last summer amid questions
about his marital fidelity.
   NBC's poll had a margin of sampling error of 3 percent. The CBS
poll's margin of error was 4 percent, and ABC's was 5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
