<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-NATO     02-24 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-NATO,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Gives Televised Assurances To NATO Allies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 4,000 nuclear weapons that would remain in
Western Europe after elimination of intermediate-range nuclear
weapons should stay there until its conventional forces are better
balanced with the Warsaw Pact, President Reagan told a European
television audience.
   ``Ensuring the peace requires that these nuclear weapons stay
where they are until we can achieve a better balance of
conventional forces on the continent,'' Reagan said Tuesday.
``Because of them and the Soviet knowledge that we have them, we
can maintain the balance that maintains the peace.''
   Reagan spoke in a televised address broadcast by satellite to
Europe by the ``Worldnet'' facilities of the U.S. Information
Agency. The address came a week before leaders of the 16 NATO
countries gather at the alliance's headquarters in Brussels for
their first full-scale summit in six years.
   Reagan said the recently signed U.S.-Soviet treaty to abolish
intermediate-range nuclear forces _ missiles with a range of about
300 miles to 3,000 miles _ was ``a victory for NATO.''
   Nevertheless, he said, NATO must continue to have battlefield
nuclear weapons, those with a range of under 300 miles.
   ``The alliance's adversaries must not believe that our only
possible response to a limited attack is to begin an
intercontinental nuclear exchange,'' Reagan said. ``If they do,
they may doubt that we would risk such a response and be tempted to
test us.''
   West Germany has expressed opposition to upgrading short-range
missiles until NATO develops an overall arms control strategy and
the Soviet Union reduces it conventional force strength.
   Reagan said NATO must insure that it maintains ``all the modern
forces, both conventional and nuclear,'' to uphold a strategy of
flexible response to Soviet aggression.
   ``After all, our goal is not a nuclear-free or a tank-free or an
army-free Europe but a war-free Europe,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
