<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief, 500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Park Service Dedicates Black History Trail In Nation's Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eagle Scout's project that began in 1979
has been realized as a National Park Service trail illustrating the
rich history of blacks in the nation's capital.
   The scout, Willard Andre Hutt, now 27, was present Tuesday at
the dedication of the Black History National Recreation trail. The
trail winds from a 179-year-old cemetery in the exclusive
Georgetown neighborhood to the home of 19th century black leader
Frederick Douglass in the city's poor Anacostia section.
   Other landmarks on the 7.5-mile trail include the downtown home
of educator and presidential advisor Mary McLeod Bethune; the
Metropolitan African Methodist Episcopal Church, created in 1822;
and Howard University, founded after the Civil War to provide
higher education to blacks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Monitors Should Hit Big Overpayments in State Assistance Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal oversignt of state-run family
assistance programs should pay closer attention to the social
purposes of programs instead of just looking at financial
accountability, a new study says.
   The report by the National Research Council, an arm of the
National Academy of Sciences, also said federal monitors should
penalize only those states with excessive rates of overpayments.
   The recommendations were based on an 18-month study ordered by
Congress and released Tuesday. It said federal officials should
measure the states against each other and penalize only those with
``excessively large'' error rates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Republicans Say Their Child Care Bill Has Better Chance of
Becoming Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $375 million child care improvement bill
introduced by Republicans to counter the multibillion-dollar
Democratic version would rely on state grants, liability pools and
capital improvements, the two sponsors say.
   It would also give tax credits to employers with on-site child
care and offer a double tax exemption to families in which a parent
stayed home for six months to care for a newborn. The break would
be worth about $500 to $600 to the average family.
   ``It's closer to what the president is going to sign than
anything else on the table or under discussion,'' Rep. Nancy
Johnson, R-Conn., House sponsor of the GOP bill. said Tuesday, the
day the bill was introduced. The cosponsor is Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Armed Forces Size Down 12,000 Over Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force had
2.17 million men and women on active duty as of Jan. 31, the
Pentagon says.
   The active-duty strength of the nation's military services in
January was more than 12,000 below the same period last year, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   According to the latest ``Military Strength'' assessment, two of
the four armed services reported declines in personnel in January
from December.
   The Marine Corps reported 198,243 men and women on active duty,
down 194 from December. The Air Force reported 604,574, down 755.
   The Army had an active-duty strength of 778,835 as of Jan. 31,
up 1,155 from December. And the Navy reported 585,726 on active
duty last month, up 561 from December.
</TEXT>
