<HEAD>Shares Open Fractionally Higher, Then Fall Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices opened fractionally higher on the
London stock exchange today but then fell slightly in early trading.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 Index was down 1.6 points
at 1,756.3 at 9:45 a.m. When the market officially opened at 9
a.m., the index was up 0.9 points at 1,758.8.
   Dealers said share prices had moved ahead strongly on bullish
sentiment about the British economy, but the market didn't find a
direction and major shares were narrowly mixed.
   The largest fall among the index of 100 shares was Consolidated
Goldfields, which dropped 12 pence to 818 pence because of weakness
in the gold price.
   Banks showed some of the largest gains, with Barclays up 6 at
480 and National Westminster up 8 at 558. Barclays increase was due
to release its 1987 earnings later today following National
Westminster which released its results on Tuesday.
   The early trend followed a small drop Tuesday in New York, where
the Dow Jones industrial average fell 1.17 to 2,039.12, and a small
gain in Tokyo overnight, where the Nikkei index rose 19.20 to
24,968.65.
