<DOCNO> AP880224-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0531EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CampaignAbroad     02-24 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Abroad,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How the U.S. Presidential Campaign is Viewed Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election process is viewed in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   As the U.S. presidential election campaign picks up pace, it is
coming more and more under scrutiny in other nations. Here is what
some newspapers and commentators said recently about the election
process in general and about Super Tuesday in particular.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Unimaginable' Process</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Sueddeutsche Zeitung of Munich (liberal): ``In a nation like
the Federal Republic (of Germany), where the parties have extended
their power into every corner of society, the drama par excellence
now occurring on the American stage would be unimaginable.
   ``Not the party, but the primary determines who will enter the
`final match' on Nov. 8. And the primary is close to the ideal
democracy imagined by Jean-Jacques Rousseau.
   ``The contenders must meet the voters face to face _ from
Alabama to Wyoming, in living rooms, schools and shopping centers.
And a candidate can climb into the ring with or without the
blessing of his party.
   ``Surprises are guaranteed.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Political Olympics'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Japan Times of Tokyo (English-language, independent): ``The
strong belief remains that none of the Democratic candidates will
emerge as an unbeatable front-runner after Super Tuesday or later.
In this case, brokering will choose the candidate at the
convention, and waiting on the sidelines for just such a
development is New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   ``What may be understandable but nevertheless regrettable is
that campaigning so far resembles a `political Olympics' with a
concentration on percentage points in pre-ballotting polls and in
the results. This tends to obscure the issues, particularly in the
reporting by the media.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH AFRICA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Roughhouse Election</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Neil Lurrssen, Washington correspondent, The Sunday Star of
Johannesburg (English-language, independent: ``The United States is
in for a roughhouse 1988 election season.
   ``It is going to be quite a spectacle. ... And the campaigning
shows every indication of deteriorating into a bare-knuckle brawl,
especially among the Republicans where the two leading candidates .
.. have already started slugging away at each other.''
   ``None of the other candidates is likely to shake the Bush-Dole
lead, though there could be a rude surprise for both of the leaders
in some parts of the South where former television evangelist Pat
Robertson has enthusiastic supporters. ... This could make Mr.
Robertson _ who has sympathy for the South African government _ a
significant factor at the party convention if there has to be
horsetrading of delegates to find a presidential nominee.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Silly Season' is Past</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ The Independent of London (independent): ``It looked on
occasion last year as if America's ... method of selecting
presidential candidates was finally coming to pieces. There was
speculation that nobody of any ability or self-respect would
subject himself and his family to the intense strain and
scrutinizing involved in the race for nomination.
   ``Such questions no longer dominate the political agenda;
suggestions that the system is unable to throw up a credible slate
are rarely heard. The political silly season is, mercifully, past.
...
   ``The main problem for the United States has turned out not to
be the caliber of the leading candidates. It is, increasingly, the
quality of government in the final months of a lame-duck
administration.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`Disappointing Comment'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ The Times of London (independent): ``Questioned on his defeat
by Vice President George Bush (in New Hampshire), Sen. Robert
Dole's first response was to rebut the `lies' put about by Mr. Bush
that he wanted to raise taxes. Evidently the last thing Mr. Dole
wanted to be associated with was a responsible fiscal policy which
he believed had cost him a significant number of votes at a crucial
stage in the presidential race.
   ``For the rest of the world this is a disappointing comment on
the nature of U.S. politics. But it hardly comes as a surprise. The
shadow of the presidential election has for months hung over the
struggle to rein back America's budget deficit. Its influence can
only increase as President Reagan's term draws to a close.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>`A Matter of Manners'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Susan Crosland, wife of the former Labor Party Cabinet minister
Tony Crosland, the Sunday Times of London (independent). Writing in
her weekly column on what she perceived as a backlash against Dole
because he accused Bush of lying, she said raised the question with
a Washingtonian living in London:
   Q. ``Why is Bush's insincerity preferred to Dole's frankness?''
   A. ``If you speak from the heart and say that someone should
have lost, you're seen as a dirty player. It's a matter of manners.
As an example of American mores, when I say `How are you?' I don't
really care how you are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
