<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JacksonTour     02-24 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson Tour,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Jackson Kicks Off Tour In KC</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KX9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As thousands roared approval, Michael
Jackson moonwalked across the stage and declared, ``I'm bad,'' to
open his first solo U.S. tour.
   Jackson kicked off the 13-city tour Tuesday at 16,900-seat
Kemper Arena, where smoke machines, lasers, and 72 speakers
highlighted the performance.
   Ku Klux Klan leaflets were placed on numerous car in the parking
lot, but the only arrest was of a person suspected of being under
the influence of alcohol, police said.
   After another show here tonight, the pop singer moves to New
York City's Madison Square Garden in March.
   Jackson sang 17 songs Tuesday in a two-hour concert that opened
with smoke machines churning and the audience bathed in brilliant
white lights. An overhead video screen showed the image of
Jackson's legs moonwalking across it.
   Flanked by four dancers, and backed by four singers and a
seven-member band, Jackson appeared and slid into non-stop
gyrations to the throbbing beat of ``Wanna Be Startin' Somethin',''
one of the hits from ``Thriller,'' the 1983 blockbuster album that
sold 40 million copies.
   Many traveled for hours to get to the concert, but perhaps none
farther than Ivan Herman, 32, and Carla Vanparys, 27, who came from
their home in Brussels, Belgium. Herman said he also attended the
opening of the 1984 Victory Tour by Jackson and members of his
musical family.
   ``I've seen him six times,'' Herman said. ``He's gotten more
mature. He's more of a real person.''
   Some said they liked the idea of a solo tour.
   ``This time we get to focus on Michael, just his talents,'' said
Alonzo Washington, 20, of Kansas City, Kan. ``He's trying to prove
he's a talent, and not just hype.''
   During his rendition of ``Bad,'' Jackson was lifted on a
platform over the heads of the audience. While suspended there, his
coat and hair flapped in an artificial breeze as he sang, ``I'm
bad, I'm bad.''
   During ``Thriller'' he was enveloped in smoke and threw a white
hat to the crowd.
   Tickets were $30 when the Victory tour opened with a concert at
Arrowhead Stadium, home of the Kansas City Chiefs football team.
This tour, tickets at the much-smaller Kemper Arena were priced at
$23, but scalpers reportedly were getting up to $200.
   A fan from Tulsa, Okla., who won a free ticket to tonight's show
but can't ride a bus with other winners because of a disability was
given an airline flight, limousine service and hotel accomodations
by the tour's sponsor, Pepsi-Cola Co.
   Alan Stephens, 18, won promotional tickets from Tulsa radio
station KMOD, but cannot travel by bus because he suffers from
Lesch-Nyhan Sydrome, which causes him to strike himself and limits
the use of his limbs.
   Other stops on the tour are St. Louis; Pittsburgh; Minneapolis;
Cleveland; Denver; Chapel Hill, N.C.; Indianapolis; Cincinnati;
Houston; Louisville, Ky.; and Birmingham, Ala. Other dates may be
added, tour officials have said.
</TEXT>
