<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp Qualifies For Hoosier Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., has joined the field
for Indiana's May 3 Republican presidential primary.
   Kemp campaign officials Tuesday filed the required ballot
petitions in the office of the secretary of state. Bob Poor of
Greencastle, Kemp's Indiana campaign chairman, said the petitions
contained 6,300 signatures.
   Indiana law requires a candidate to have 500 petitioners from
each of the state's 10 congressional districts.
   Kemp and Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas are the only GOP candidates to
file so far. The filing period ends March 4.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Some Democrats Miss Statewide Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and Democratic Party officials say
at least three Democratic presidential contenders will not be
running statewide on Ohio's May 3 primary ballot because they
failed to file slates of delegates in one or two of the state's 21
congressional districts.
   The secretary of state's office said Tuesday that while official
lists will be compiled by March 1, it appears former Sen. Gary Hart
of Colorado, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Jesse Jackson
will not run statewide.
   All of the other major presidential candidates in both parties
apparently fielded slates in all districts, although Democrat Bruce
Babbitt and Republican Pete DuPont have abandoned their campaigns
and their names apparently will be withdrawn.
   Democrats whose statewide candidacies appeared assured include
Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon and
Sen. Albert Gore, Tennessee. The Republicans are Sen. Robert Dole
of Kansas, Vice President George Bush, Congressman Jack Kemp of New
York and Pat Robertson.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson, Uncommitteed File For New York Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Jesse Jackson have become the
first of the six announced Democratic presidential candidates to
file petitions for a spot on the crucial April 19 New York primary
ballot.
   While the Jackson camp showed up Tuesday at the state Board of
Election with more than six times the required number of
signatures, state board spokesman Steven LaFever said they had been
beaten to the ballot by ``uncommitted.''
   LaFever said supporters of uncommitted slates of delegates, put
together by a group of elected Democratic county clerks from across
upstate New York, had filed petitions containing 18,816 signatures
on Monday.
   Democratic candidates have until midnight tomorrow to file
petitions containing at least 10,000 signatures with at least 100
coming from each of 17 of the state's 34 congressional districts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Far Ahead, Bush Leading in Poll of Massachusetss Primary
Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis enjoys a prohibitive lead
among Democratic presidential candidates in his home state and Vice
President George Bush leads the Republican field in the
Massachusetts primary on March 8, according to a new poll.
   The survey, commissioned by WCVB-TV in Boston, WEEI radio and
The Boston Globe, was conducted by the Gallup organization among
Massachusetts voters last weekend.
   The survey said Dukakis led the Democratic field with 61 percent
support, followed distantly by Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt with
13 percent.
   In the Republican race, Bush _ a Massachusetts native _ led with
49 percent, compared to 29 percent saying they support Kansas Sen.
Bob Dole.
   The telephone survey of presidential preference involved 639
registered Democrats with a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percent. The poll also reached 331 Republicans, with a margin of
error of plus or minus 6 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Disabled Follow Politics But Have Trouble Voting, Poll Suggests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disabled Americans express greater interest in
politics than other citizens, but they register and vote at a rate
considerably lower than the general public, according to a recently
released survey.
   ``Our findings suggest that barriers, either external or
internal or both, prevent many disabled Americans from converting
their exceptionally high political interest into actual electoral
activity,'' said Humphrey Taylor, president of Louis Harris and
Associates, which conducted the poll.
   The most common barrier cited for disabled people was lack of
transportation and difficulty in getting to the polls, problems
noted by 29 percent of the respondents. Twenty-one percent said it
was difficult to stand or walk.
   The telephone poll of 536 disabled people nationwide, conducted
in June and July 1987, found that 53 percent said they follow
government and public affairs most of the time.
   In comparison, only 26 percent of all U.S. adults pay attention
to politics much of the time, according to a 1984 National Election
Study by the University of Michigan.
   The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent.
</TEXT>
