<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RacialPunishment     02-24 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Racial Punishment,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences White Man To NAACP Work After Attack on Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white man who admitted chasing two blacks with
a baseball bat was ordered to perform 200 hours of community
service for the NAACP by a judge trying to help him overcome racial
hatred.
   ``He has been taught to hate black people for some reason,''
said Cook County Circuit Judge Stuart Nudelman. ``I'm trying to put
him in an environment where he can perhaps do some good and learn
something about the people he thinks he hates and perhaps learn
that his feelings are misguided.''
   James Kalafut, a 21-year-old plumbing company laborer, pleaded
guilty to aggravated assault and ethnic intimidation and could have
been sentenced to a year in prison, the judge said after sentencing
him Tuesday.
   Kalafut was charged in August after he and a group of other
whites _ brandishing baseball bats, throwing bottles and shouting
racial slurs _ chased two blacks from a transit stop in Gage Park,
a predominantly white neighborhood on the Southwest Side.
   Nudelman placed Kalafut under his supervision for one year and
ordered him to perform 200 hours of community service work for the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Details of when Kalafut will serve the sentence are to be worked
out in the next few days by his attorney, Barry Silver, the NAACP
and the judge.
   Silver said before the sentencing that Kalafut would accept the
agreement to perform community service and no appeal would be
attempted.
   ``I think it's a good sentence given the fact that he's
basically pleaded guilty to hating a minority group,'' Silver said.
   ``By being with black people, he will have a chance to learn
they are no different than he is except that the color of their
skin is different.
   ``I think that is an important lesson for anyone to learn,
especially someone who has been involved in this kind of
activity,'' Silver said.
   The attorney said Kalafut, who declined to be interviewed, was
``concerned about his own personal safety when he is in the
neighborhood of the NAACP,'' located on the South Side.
   Silver said Kalafut also was concerned about being rejected by
NAACP officials and being ``made the scapegoat in a sort of reverse
discrimination.''
   But the civil rights organization plans to make sure that
doesn't happen, said Edward McClellan, president of the South Side
branch.
   ``Certainly we don't presume there are only white racists or
what have you,'' said McClellan, who wasn't sure what type of work
Kalafut would perform. ``Racism can be engendered by anyone
inclined to that sort of prejudice.''
   Nudelman said that trying to help Kalafut overcome his prejudice
against blacks made more sense than sentencing him to jail, ``where
he won't learn anything except more hatred.''
   But the judge warned, ``If he ... doesn't do what he's supposed
to, he'll come back before me and I'll sentence him to jail.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
