<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0558EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-FarmScene     02-24 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETTRANSMITTING for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wheat To Have First Year-To-Year Increase In Four Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook for U.S. wheat farmers has
improved significantly, aided in part by huge subsidized sales to
the Soviet Union.
   An additional sale of 700,000 metric tons to the Soviets was
announced Tuesday by the Agriculture Department. Overall, exports
are expected to rise more than 50 percent from last year, reducing
the U.S. wheat stockpile to the lowest level in six years.
   In a related analysis, the department's Economic Research
Service said the rising demand and shrinking inventories have
boosted wheat prices well above last year's harvest lows of about
$2.28 per bushel.
   Over the entire wheat marketing year, which began last June 1,
the national average farm price is expected to be in the range of
$2.55 to $2.65 per bushel, up from $2.42 in 1986-87, the report
said. That will be the first year-to-year increase since 1983-84.
   Looking briefly at 1988 harvest prospects, the report noted that
plantings of winter wheat last fall for this summer's harvest were
the smallest in 10 years. Spring wheat plantings may be up slightly
if strong prices entice farmers away from the USDA's 1988 acreage
program.
   ``However, weather remains the leading determinate of 1988's
wheat crop,'' the report said.
   The latest sale, equal to about 25.7 million bushels, was
handled by Continental Grain Co., 150,000 tons; Tradigrain Inc.,
50,000; Louis Dreyfus Corp., 250,000; Cargill Inc., 100,000; and
Peavey Co., 150,000.
   At recent prices averaging $2.76 per bushel, the wheat would
have a farm value of about $71 million. That is a five-day average
price through Feb. 19, adjusted to reflect prices received by
farmers.
   More than 6.3 million tons of subsidized wheat have been sold to
the Soviet Union under the department's Export Enhancement Program,
or EEP, for delivery in the year that began last Oct. 1.
   William L. Davis, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said an additional
500,200 tons of wheat are still available to the Soviet Union under
current EEP authorization.
   Under EEP, private exporters are given surplus commodities owned
by the department's Commodity Credit Corp. so they can sell a
foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive
world prices.
   The sales also are part of the grain the Soviet Union is
committed to buy during the fifth and final year of a long-term
agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9
million tons of U.S. grain. The pact expires Sept. 30.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat or soybeans, or 39.4 bushels of corn.
   In addition, 1.67 million tons of U.S. corn, 800,000 tons of
soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal have been bought by
the Soviets for delivery this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department economists say
consumers soon will see lower prices for lettuce.
   ``Lettuce shipments and prices should return to normal this
spring as harvesting moves north from California's Imperial Valley
and spring brings improved weather,'' according to a report by the
department's Economic Research Service. ``Both grower and retail
lettuce prices likely will decline to more typical levels.''
   Last fall prices soared because ``unusual heat and pest problems
reduced yields,'' the report said. In November and December,
lettuce sold for $20 to $25 per carton at California shipping
points, compared with $4 to $7 a year earlier. As of early
February, prices were ranging between $3 and $12.
   ``Prices remained higher than usual during the winter because
cold weather and plant disease transmitted by the whitefly reduced
midwinter shipments from the Imperial Valley,'' the report said.
``The valley usually supplies most of the domestic lettuce supply
during midwinter.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent death of Donald L. Houston, one of
the Agriculture Department's senior career officials, was a tragic
loss to the department and to the nation, Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng said.
   Houston, 53, died Feb. 19 of cancer. He was named head of the
department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service last fall
and previously was administrator of the Food Safety and Inspection
Service for seven years.
   Lyng said Tuesday in a statement that he had known Houston, a
veterinarian, for more than 15 years. ``He truly epitomized what
the American people want and expect in a public servant,'' Lyng
said.
   Houston was born in East St. Louis, Ill., where he joined USDA
as a veterinary meat inspector in 1961. He moved to Washington in
1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
