<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0558EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Ireland     02-24 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Ireland,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Comments On Aid To Ireland Cause Dustup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's second-ranking official
caused a diplomatic and political dustup last week with his
explanation, later partially disavowed, of why the administration
wants to shut down its aid program for Ireland.
   The remarks by Deputy Secretary John Whitehead generated a stir
in Dublin, sent Irish diplomats scurrying to find explanations, and
produced expressions of dismay from the ``Shamrock caucus'' in
Congress.
   In the end, the State Department took the unusual step of
issuing a clarification that effectively repudiated part of what
Whitehead said.
   At issue is U.S. participation in the International Fund for
Ireland. American contributions have totaled $85 million over the
past two years, and $35 million is slated for the current year.
Most of the money is aimed at promoting economic and social
progress in Northern Ireland, now approaching two decades of
sectarian strife.
   Last Thursday, Whitehead went before reporters to explain the
administration's foreign aid proposals for 1989, and he was asked
why no money was programmed for Ireland.
   He said Ireland ``ranks down the list'' of foreign aid
priorities, adding that the United States does not get a ``real
return'' on its investment despite the emotional and ``maybe
political appeal'' of aid to Ireland.
   ``Other needs appear to us to be more urgent,'' Whitehead said.
   Both the cutoff decision and the tone of Whitehead's remarks
were the talk of Dublin late last week. And there were expressions
of concern from two of the best known Irish-Americans in Congress _
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and his nephew, Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II,
both Massachusetts Democrats.
   The chairman of the congressional Friends of Ireland, Rep. Brian
Donnelly, D-Mass., said he was outraged.
   The State Department came under pressure to clarify Whitehead's
remarks, and did so over the weekend. Privately, one official said
that Whitehead misspoke but the problem was ``how to set the record
straight'' without upsetting him.
   After a day's contemplation, the State Department issued a
statement expressing strong support for the International Fund even
though Whitehead had said U.S. contributions to it had yielded few
benefits.
   Distancing itself still further from Whitehead, the statement
said, ``We have been very happy with the progress which the Fund
and its governing board have made.''
   Beyond that, it even implied that the administration would not
be displeased if Congress overrode the aid cutoff and earmarked
more money for the program.
   ``Of course, we will be ultimately guided by what Congress
authorizes and appropriates and what is signed into law by the
president,'' the statement said.
   There is some dispute as to whether U.S. participation in the
program was to be phased out. Whitehead made no reference to any
such limit, but the State Department clarification does allude to a
three-year time frame. Irish diplomatic sources, meanwhile, said
funding for additional years had never been ruled out.
   In any case, the statement appears to have calmed Dublin, where
there is a feeling that the Congress won't cut the aid program
adrift.
   Contributing to the more relaxed mood was the statement by Rep.
Kennedy: ``The Fund has done good work and continues to do so,'' he
said. ``I for one will be encouraging my colleagues to consider the
economic and symbolic importance of continued American support for
the International Fund.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
