<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dole     02-24 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole, With Two Wins To His Credit, Heads South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, proclaiming ``we're
winning again,'' was heading South hopeful his victories in
Minnesota and South Dakota would help his Republican presidential
campaign in a region where Vice President George Bush is the
front-runner.
   ``I've got a big hill to climb in the South,'' Dole said Tuesday
night while celebrating his latest victories.
   Dole scheduled four stops in South Carolina, one in North
Carolina and then planned to head for Florida.
   The Kansas senator got some help in South Carolina on Monday
when he was endorsed by Sen. Strom Thurmond, the state's senior
officeholder. But Bush has the backing of Gov. Carroll Campbell.
   With a Republican primary on March 5, South Carolina opens the
Southern phase of the 1988 campaign. Three days later is Super
Tuesday, when 20 states, the majority of them in the South, will
hold primaries or caucuses.
   For the second time this busy campaign month, Dole was heading
out of the Midwest with a decisive show of support.
   Two weeks ago, he won the Iowa caucuses and flew to New
Hampshire hoping to deliver a killing blow to Bush. But New England
proved to be Bush territory and the vice president won the New
Hampshire primary and revived his status as GOP front-runner.
   Dole was in a black mood after his New Hampshire defeat, but
upon getting strong backing from voters in South Dakota and
Minnesota, the senator said, ``It's a lot more fun winning.''
   As for Bush's showing _ second in South Dakota and fourth in
Minnesota _ Dole said, ``I really believe when the vice president
of the United States gets 10 percent, or around that area _ the
sitting vice president _ and only about 15 percent in South Dakota,
it's going to send a strong signal to small towns, to farmers, to
businessmen and businesswomen.''
   ``We're winning again,'' he said. ``We probably had our
expectations too high in New Hampshire and it probably hurt us some
around the country. But now we're winning again.''
   Dole said he hoped the results ``send a message that Bob Dole
has a message. That's what the election is all about. I haven't
changed my message. I've talked about the future, I've talked about
leadership, I've talked about party responsibilities, I've talked
about the left out and the down-and-out in America, I've talked
about the future of our young people.''
</TEXT>
