<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-24 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired lawyer who reads dictionaries for
fun says too many people are put off by big words.
   Because so many people suffer from sesquipedalophobia, a fear or
hatred of big words, 80-year-old Norman Schur has written eight
books on the subject.
   ``This has gone from a hobby with me to a vocation and finally
to a matter of sociological and political concern,'' Schur said
Tuesday.
   Schur has just published his latest book, ``1000 Most
Challenging Words.'' In the next one, ``1000 Most Obscure Words,''
he plans brief essays on each word's origins and meaning. He
believes if a person becomes familiar with a word, he or she will
use it.
   Schur, who received his high school diploma at age 11 and
graduated from Harvard University at age 17, does not blame weak
vocabularies on the educational system.
   ``There are some well-educated people who do not like you to use
big words,'' he said. ``If you use a word that's unfamiliar to them
they resent it and this intimidates a lot of people.''
   For people who want to improve their vocabulary, Schur suggests
they jot down every new word in a notebook, master it and then use
it.
   ``I find reading dictionaries fascinating, but that's not the
menu for most people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy Goose met Granny Goose in
court, but the legal fight is not a family feud.
   Granny Goose Foods Inc., the nation's third largest potato chip
manufacturer, has accused Grammy Goose Baby Boutique in nearby
Petaluma of creating confusion over the food firm's name and logo
by using a similar name.
   Granny has asked for a preliminary injunction against Grammy.
   The name and logo ``represent the most valuable asset my client
owns,'' Granny attorney Kate Spellman told Sonoma County Superior
Court Judge Lloyd von der Mehden on Tuesday. ``Where there is
confusion, dilution has occurred.''
   Sandy Gotelli, the Petaluma grandmother who owns the baby shop,
said she'll be forced out of business if the injunction is granted.
She said she picked the name by combining her liking for geese with
her granddaughter's nickname for her.
   Ms. Spellman said the company offered to help Grammy Goose
design a new sign, phase out printed paper goods and find a new
name that retains part of the current name.
   ``We understand she is a small business and we would like to
mitigate the harm to her,'' Ms. Spellman said. ``We mean her no
harm; she is so inflexible.''
   Mrs. Gotelli's attorney said the shop owner had made a counter
offer to the chip maker: to promise the Grammy Goose name would
never be sold to anyone else and would never be used outside of
Sonoma County.
   The judge gave Mrs. Gotelli one week to respond in writing to
the Granny Goose offer. Granny Goose's attorneys then will have
five days to respond.
   The judge said he would then issue a ruling.

</TEXT>
