<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Bowl,0131</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>18th Century Tea Bowl Sold For More Than $34,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny porcelain tea bowl painted by a French
artist in 1749 was bought for $34,850 at Sotheby's, the auction
house said.
   The artist, Louis Denis Armand the elder, who worked at the
Vincennes factory near Paris, painted 46 patches of enamel colors
on the bowl to guide him in selecting colors, which often changed
drastically in the firing process.
   Some colors were also very expensive. One pound of one color
cost nine times Armand's annual salary.
   The bowl, 1} inches high, was bought and sold anonymously on
Tuesday. Only one similar tea bowl from Vincennes is known to
exist, and it is in a museum at Sevres, the other famous French
porcelain center.
</TEXT>
