<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WitchKillers     02-24 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Witch Killers,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Sentenced in `Witch' Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who claimed they were waging a
holy war have been sentenced in the latest of three slayings in
which they regarded the victims as witches or vampires.
   Michael Carson was sentenced to prison for 27 years to life in
the 1982 slaying of Clark Stephens near Garberville. His wife,
Suzan, was sentenced to 25 years to life.
   The sentences will follow earlier terms, Deputy District
Attorney Max Cardoza said Tuesday. The Carsons were convicted in
May of shooting Stephens, 26, and burning his body before burying
it.
   Carson, 36, was given an additional two years for using a
firearm. The two were sentenced Monday by Humboldt County Superior
Court Judge William Ferroggiaro.
   The Carsons previously were given consecutive sentences of 25
years to life for two other slayings.
   They were convicted in the 1981 murder in San Francisco of a
woman Mrs. Carson told investigators was a ``psychic vampire'' who
was draining her of her beauty.
   They also were convicted of the 1983 killing of a man in Sonoma
County who picked up the hitchhiking couple, only to be declared a
witch by the wife.
   In a lengthy statement taped by police, the two said they were
on a holy war ordered by Allah.
   Defense attorneys contended Carson shot Stephens to death
because he had sexually attacked Mrs. Carson, an action that
amounted to self-defense in keeping with the couple's beliefs as
fundamentalist Moslems.
</TEXT>
