<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Sevareid     02-24 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Sevareid,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says TV News Being Made Into Entertainment for the Bored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Sevareid says news on television ``has
become part of the daily entertainment of a rather bored society.''
   The former chief Washington correspondent of CBS News, at a
seminar Tuesday at the Museum of Broadcasting, expressed misgivings
about the rise of features-oriented TV magazine shows.
   ``Underlying this whole development in the way news is presented
now is ... the nature and psychology of American society at this
moment in history (after) years of essential peace and essential
prosperity for most people.
   ``We have news about entertainment now; you're going to have a
news magazine on the business side of sports; you have a game
called `Trivial Pursuit.'''
   Audiences don't get very excited about policy issues and don't
want to follow what appears to be 30 years of the same pictures
coming from the Middle East, he said.
   ``If you had another great war or great depression, that would
change matters, but that would be too high a price,'' Sevareid said.
   Sevareid also said he watched ``with some astonishment'' the
on-air battle between CBS anchorman Dan Rather and Vice President
George Bush.
   ``I'd never seen brother Dan lose his cool before,'' Sevareid
said. ``I'm sorry it happened. I don't think a CBS hard news show
should become controverted. ... Neutrality should be preserved.
   ``I don't think Mr. Bush answered much,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
