<HEAD>Contempt Hearing for Capasso Wednesday; Myerson Subpoenaed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hearing scheduled for 9:30 a.m. EST. Spelling of Fredman is
cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Bess Myerson, who was
indicted last year for conspiring to influence the judge in the
divorce settlement of her boyfriend, has been called to testify in
a hearing today over a property dispute between the estranged
couple.
   Nancy Capasso sought the hearing after her ex-husband, Carl
``Andy'' Capasso, allegedly removed property from the house she had
won as part of the divorce settlement, said Raoul Felder, Mrs.
Capasso's attorney.
   Felder said that he had subpoenaed the 63-year-old Miss Myerson,
a former city cultural affairs commissioner, and characterized her
as ``a key witness'' in the proceeding in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan.
   Miss Myerson stayed in the Long Island house last summer after
Capasso went to jail in June after being convicted of tax evasion
in an unrelated case.
   Mrs. Capasso, who won the house as part of her $6.4 million
divorce settlement, seeks to have Capasso held in contempt, Felder
said.
   Felder said he could not elaborate on details because a gag
order was in effect.
   Mrs. Capasso has said all the living room furniture was taken,
some artwork, a collection of antique quilts, some decoy ducks and
sets of china and flatware.
   Miss Myerson was indicted last October for allegedly attempting
to influence the rulings of former state Supreme Court Justice
Hortense Gabel in the Capassos' divorce by giving the judge's
daughter, Sukreet Gabel, a city job.
   Miss Myerson, Capasso and Mrs. Gabel have pleaded innocent to
five counts each of federal conspiracy, mail fraud and
bribe-related charges. They each face up to five years in prison,
if convicted. Miss Myerson faces an additional five years if
convicted of obstruction of justice.
</TEXT>
