<2ND_LINE>PM-Fare Fight,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Questioned in Assault on Changeless Rider</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus driver was arrested after allegedly beating
a passenger who boarded his bus without exact change, police said.
   The name of the driver, a 43-year-old Detroit man, was withheld
pending issuance of a warrant on a charge of felonious assault,
city police Lt. Philip Foster said Tuesday.
   Jonathan Perkins, 30, of Detroit boarded the Detroit Department
of Transportation bus about 9:15 a.m. Monday without the proper
change, police said.
   ``The driver was absolutely belligerent,'' an unidentified bus
rider told the Detroit Free Press.
   Perkins placed some coins in the fare box, then asked other
passengers for change for a $20 bill to pay the balance of the $1
fare, the rider said.
   The driver yelled at Perkins for about a mile, then shoved him
off the bus, the passenger said.
   ``He literally threw him on the ground, pulled a knife on him
and the next thing I know, he's on the guy's face,'' the passenger
said. ``He started kicking him in the head and then shoved him into
the intersection and left the scene.''
   Perkins was treated at Detroit Receiving Hospital for minor
bruises and cuts, police said.
   A woman who answered the phone at the Department of
Transportation office said Robert Polk, director of the agency, was
not available for comment Tuesday.
</TEXT>
