<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-US     02-24 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-US,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 U.S. Servicemen Detained After Noriega's Son-In-Law Stopped For
Speeding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian police detained more than
two dozen U.S. servicemen without charges after the son-in-law of
Panama's military strongman was held for speeding at a U.S.
military installation.
   Two U.S. military personnel were stopped and briefly held
Tuesday, a Pentagon official said in Washington. On Monday,
Panamanian police detained 25 U.S. servicemen for two hours before
releasing them without filing charges, said a U.S. Embassy
spokesman in Panama City.
   The servicemen were picked up while driving to U.S. military
installations inside the former Panama Canal Zone.
   The State Department planned to protest the detentions, said the
Pentagon official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The official said the detentions came a day after Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega's son-in-law was stopped in the canal zone. He
declined to give the son-in-law's name, but said Noriega's daughter
and two other passengers were in the car when it was stopped Sunday
night for speeding and passing in a no-passing zone at the Albrook
Air Force Station, outside of Panama City.
   The son-in-law allegedly became abusive with the Air Force
security policeman who stopped him. He could not produce
identification, the source said. At that point, the policeman
``restrained'' him, put him in handcuffs and took him to the Air
Force police station for processing, the source said. The
son-in-law was released about an hour after being stopped, he said.
   On Monday, the U.S. Embassy spokesman told The Associated Press
police stopped 25 servicemen. The spokesman, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said most were driving motorcycles to installations
inside the former canal zone, but two were driving cars and one was
walking.
   Col. Leonidas Macias, chief of police for the Panamanian Defense
Forces, denied police detained the servicemen. He said officers
merely stopped them to check for drivers' licenses and remind them
that U.S. personnel are forbidden to wear uniforms outside of the
former canal zone.
   The detentions marked the latest sign of deteriorating relations
between the United States and Panama since last June, when
demonstrations broke out in Panama demanding the resignation of
Noriega, the armed forces chief.
   The Reagan administration has publicly called for Noriega to
step down following his indictment on drug trafficking charges this
month by a federal grand jury in Miami.
</TEXT>
