<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amnesty-Honduras     02-24 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Honduras,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rights Group: Death Squad Activity Increasing In Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduran death squads linked to the military have
stepped up their campaign of terror, targeting opposition leaders,
human rights activists, students and peasants, Amnesty
International said today.
   ``Serious human rights violations, including arbitrary arrests,
torture and ill-treatment are widespread in Honduras and show no
signs of diminishing,'' the London-based human rights organization
said in a report.
   The group said many of the abuses arose during strikes, disputes
over farm land or army operations against leftist guerrillas. The
group also said it remains concerned about the government's failure
to investigate reports of more than 100 people who disappeared
between 1980 and 1984.
   In the report, titled ``Honduras: Civilian Authority, Military
Power,'' Amnesty based its findings on interviews with senior
government and military officials and non-government sources during
two visits to Honduras last year.
   The group said recent abuses include bombings, arbitrary
detentions, death threats and harassment of critics of the
government of President Jose Azcona Hoyo. Despite a civilian
government, the 17,500-man army wields great power.
   Victims include human rights figures, opposition leaders,
members of labor organizations, students and peasants, Amnesty
said. The victims described severe beatings, electric shocks and
sexual abuse.
   The group said patterns of abuse changed since the early 1980s,
when it said abductions and executions were carried out
systematically by order of the armed forces.
   The alleged abuses fell off after 1984, but the death squads
have apparently begun a new campaign of intimidation in the last
two years, the report said. Death squads were believed to have been
involved in three killings last month, it said.
   Two people shot to death in January were to have testified
against the government in a human rights case before the
Inter-American Court of Human Rights in Costa Rica.
   Amnesty blamed most of the recent alleged human rights abuses on
the National Investigations Division, which Amnesty said is part of
the police but actually is controlled by the military.
   The report quoted a former member of Battalion 3-16, which it
said was a secret military intelligence unit, as saying he and
other members of the group were secretly trained by the U.S.
military in 1981.
   The unidentified man was quoted as saying that the U.S.
officials discouraged torture but had trained the unit in methods
of physical coercion.
   Since 1981, the Reagan administration has made Honduras a key
ally for policy aimed at containing the leftist Sandinista
government in neighboring Nicaragua.
   A series of joint military exercises have been held, almost
continously, for the past five years. A permanent American military
presence is maintained at Palmerola Air Base near Tegucigalpa and
at other facilities, totaling more than 1,000 U.S. troops.
   The U.S. military aid program grew from $8.9 million in 1981 to
$88.8 million for 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0087 </DOCNO>
