<HEAD>Tugboat Captain Wounded in Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tugboat captain was wounded early today when
shots fired from the Brooklyn shoreline shattered the cabin's glass
windshield, police said.
   More than a dozen such shootings have occurred since 2,800 union
tugboat and barge workers went on strike over wage cuts Feb. 16,
said an officer from the Police Department's Harbor Unit who
declined to give his name.
   Early today, the tugboat Odin was headed south in the East
River, just off Newtown Creek, when a gunman fired four shots.
Newton Creek divides Brooklyn and Queens.
   Capt. Les Wallin suffered cuts on the left side of his face and
glass in his eye when the windshield broke, but refused medical aid
when the tugboat docked at Staten Island, the officer said.
   The captain and non-union crew members declined to discuss the
shooting, police said.
   No other details were immediately available.
</TEXT>
