<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MechamRecall     02-24 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Recall,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford Could Be Drafted in Recall Without Resigning, Corbin Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Gov. Rose Mofford may be able to
run for governor in a May 17 recall election without giving up her
position as secretary of state, the state's attorney general said.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin, in a non-binding opinion issued
Tuesday, said that if Mrs. Mofford is drafted instead of declaring
herself a candidate, she would not have to resign as secretary of
state.
   Mrs. Mofford, who became acting governor following the
impeachment of Gov. Evan Mecham on Feb. 5, has not said whether she
is interested in running, and had no comment Tuesday on the
possibility of a draft.
   As governor, Mecham would automatically be on the recall ballot,
but his status is clouded by his impeachment and impending trial
before the Senate, and a criminal trial scheduled for March.
   Democrat Carolyn Warner, who lost to Mecham in a three-way race
in 1968, and Republican John Rhodes have indicated they will be
candidates in the recall election.
   Mecham, a Republican, faces a Senate trial Monday on charges
that he hid a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership, and
tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a
state official.
   A criminal trial is scheduled for March 22 on felony charges of
concealing the $350,000 loan.
   Arizona's resign-to-run law requires officeholders who run for
another position to resign unless they are in the last year of
their current term.
   Rep. Cindy Resnick, a Democrat, had asked Corbin whether a draft
of an officeholder as a gubernatorial candidate would require that
person to resign.
   Ms. Resnick said she expects a draft-Mofford movement to be
started, but said she did not plan to be involved.
   Meanwhile, Rhodes announced Tuesday that former Sen. Barry
Goldwater would be his honorary campaign chairman. Goldwater
endorsed Mecham in the 1986 campaign, but now says that was a
mistake.
   In accepting the position, Goldwater said: ``You look back over
all the governors that we've had in this state. We've had some darn
good ones and we've had some mediocre ones, but it took us a long
time to get a really bad one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
