<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-AppleLeak     02-24 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Apple Leak,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Reveals Details of Long-Awaited Apple Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. is developing a
laptop computer which it hopes to introduce next year, according to
a computer magazine which printed details of the secret project.
   The article in this week's edition of Macintosh Today details
the size, appearance and technical specifications of Apple's Laguna
laptop model. The San Francisco Examiner reported Tuesday that the
article was based on a confidential document given to a free-lance
writer by an Apple employee.
   ``We don't comment on rumors of products which may or may not
come to market,'' said Barbara Krause, spokeswoman for Apple
Computer Inc.
   The magazine article describes a 12-pound laptop with a
flat-panel monitor called an active matrix screen and a central
processor that can run Macintosh software using only a fraction of
the power used by most desktop models.
   The magazine said the system will come with 1 megabyte of
internal memory, the same as the Macintosh SE. It will be powered
by a five-pound lead-acid battery that will last up to 10 hours
before recharging.
   The Laguna is not expected to join the $1 billion laptop market
until next year.
</TEXT>
