<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Tae-Woo To Be Sworn In As South Korea's 13th President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTs in 2nd graf beginning ``Roh will... '' to say he
will be 6th president sted 13th.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Roh Tae-woo will be
sworn in Thursday in the first peaceful transfer of power in South
Korea's turbulent history with a promise to end authoritarian rule
and usher in full democracy.
   Roh will take the oath of office as the 6th president at a
heavily-guarded ceremony at the National Assembly with no general
public participation. Outgoing President Chun Doo-hwan and other
leaders will attend the ceremony.
   The inauguration also will mark the start of the Sixth Republic
as the country adopts a new constitution that provides for greater
political and individiual freedoms. Roh has promised the republic
will be ``the great era of the common man.''
   The charismatic Roh, 55, is committed to ending the nation's
long tradition of authoritarian rule that strictly limited
political activity and ruthlessly cracked down on opposition. He
also has pledged to end the country's confrontational politics and
violent regional divisions and to redress social and economic
inequality.
   Roh on Monday called for a government that ``is loved by the
people and run in accordance with democratic principles to suit a
new era.''
   The new president faces the challenge of ending authoritarian
rule in a nation that has never had a peaceful transfer of power.
The nation has been dominated by civilian and military strongmen
since its creation in 1948 and its politics are turbulent and often
violent.
   Police were on alert in Seoul and other cities today after
reports that radical students and dissidents may attempt to stage
anti-Roh protests. Radical groups have refused to recognize Roh's
election and contend he is intent on continuing authoritarian rule.
   Radical groups called for anti-government protests in Seoul and
other cities today and Thursday. Detachments of riot police were
seen guarding key points in some areas of Seoul and police
officials said reserves were on alert.
   More than 200 student and dissident leaders were being watched
in case they attempted to organize protests, officials said. Police
also were guarding festive arches erected in Seoul for the
inauguration in case dissidents attempted to wreck them.
   Chun warned at a farewell dinner in Seoul tonight that political
stability and continued expansion were vital. He warned against
political unrest.
   ``I am convinced that there must not, and will not, be any
repeat of political chaos that imperils the country or social chaos
that threatens national survival,'' he said.
   Chun, who took power with military backing in 1980 when he and
Roh were senior generals, is to head a presidential advisory board.
He was to leave office in a separate ceremony Thursday.
   A low-key inaugural ceremony was planned for Thursday with Roh
scheduled to take the oath of office in the square in front of the
National Assembly building. But attendance was by invitation only
and there were no plans for celebrations or public attendance.
   Factory workers, street cleaners and other ordinary people were
invited to attend the ceremony along with officials, academics, and
other representatives of Korean society, officials said.
   Envoys from 88 nations, including Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita of Japan and the premiers of Sri Lanka and Fiji, were to
attend the inauguration. The United States was to be represented by
Treasury Secretary James Baker.
   Roh won the country's first democratic presidential election in
16 years on Dec. 16 with 36.6 percent of the vote. He defeated
rival opposition candidates Kim Young-sam and Kim Dae-jung, who
split the opposition vote.
   Roh, a former general, is identified with the military-backed
governments that have ruled the country since 1961 and many Koreans
are doubtful if he can achieve massive democratic change.
   Opposition parties contend Roh's inauguration will simply signal
a change of figurehead and the government will continue to be run
by the armed forces and an entrenched elite of government officials
and business leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
