<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Politics     02-24 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Politics,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Protesters Rally Against Aquino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIL C. SIONIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of leftist demonstrators
marched on a military camp today and accused the government of
betraying the revolution that swept President Corazon Aquino to
power two years ago.
   About 200 policemen blocked the road leading to Camp Crame as
helicopters patrolled overhead. But the crowd, estimated at 20,000
people by police, was peaceful.
   The rally was held on a boulevard between Camp Crame and Camp
Aguinaldo. Two years ago, hundreds of thousands of Filipinos
flocked there and prevented troops loyal to then-President
Ferdinand Marcos from attacking rebellious soldiers holed up in
Crame. The four-day standoff ended with Marcos' depature from the
Philippines.
   Today's marchers included students, workers, farmers, nuns and
priests. They chanted ``dismantle the U.S.-Aquino regime'' and
carried effigies of Mrs. Aquino and Uncle Sam.
   Red banners said, ``Advance the People's Genuine Revolution,''
and one poster read: ``Cory _ Closet Dictator.''
   The protesters denounced what they said was Mrs. Aquino's
failure to put in place the sweeping economic and political reforms
she had promised during the 1986 presidential election.
   ``We had high hopes when Cory Aquino said she would be the exact
opposite of Marcos. But after two years, we have no more hope that
she will fulfill her promises,'' Crispin Beltran, head of the
militant May 1st Movement labor organization, told the rally.
   Some of the protesters distributed leaflets of the outlawed
National Democratic Front, an umbrella organization of 12 Marxist
groups, including the Communist Party of the Philippines and its
armed wing, the New People's Army.
   ``The Aquino government has betrayed the Filipino people's hope
for fundamental changes in society after ousting Marcos...,'' a
leaflet said. It accused the government of incompetence and
``subservience to the U.S.''
   The crowd dispersed without incident after about three hours.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt, however, congratulated the
Aquino government today on molding a democratic government.
   ``What we have seen happen in this period is impressive,'' Platt
said in a statement. ``A constitution has been written and ratified
by an overwhelming margin... A new congress has been freely elected
and is vigorously functioning. Local elections have been held in
every province, city and town throughout the Philippine Archipelago.
   ``In these and mnay other ways democracy has been restored in
the Philippines,'' he said.
   In other developments, Mrs. Aquino defended her embattled
defense secretary, Gen. Fidel Ramos, and credited him with blocking
attempts by renegade military officers to topple her government.
   She said ``as far as I'm concerned, General (Fidel) Ramos has
proven himself not only now but in the past, especially in his
abiding by the constitution. He has not been any part of any coup
attempt.''
   Mrs. Aquino made the remark to reporters one day after the wife
of a Navy captain linked to at least two coup attempts and the
assassination of a leftist labor leader hinted that Ramos was
involved in a November 1986 conspiracy.
   Ramos said that he, in fact, exposed the coup attempt.
</TEXT>
