<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhaleFossils     02-24 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whale Fossils,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ancient Whale Surfaces After Millions Of Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusually well-preserved fossil
skull stumbled upon by a graduate student belongs to one of the
smallest baleen whales ever known, scientists said.
   The skull and other parts of the 15-foot whale, believed to be
12 million to 14 million years old and possibly related to modern
toothless whales, were found embedded in a sandstone bluff on Ano
Nuevo Island, about 19 miles northwest of Santa Cruz.
   The 35-pound skull is a ``beautiful specimen,'' said Kenneth S.
Norris, a professor of natural history at the University of
California-Santa Cruz.
   ``(It's) one of the best I know of,'' Norris, a world authority
on whales, said at a news conference Tuesday.
   Brian Fadley, 26, a UC-Santa Cruz graduate student, said he
spotted the skull as an irregularity in a rock formation last May
while visiting Ano Nuevo Island with a group studying elephant
seals. A closer look revealed that it was a whale skull.
   ``Since I didn't have the usual tools of a paleontologist, I
modified a rusty pipe to excavate the fossil,'' Fadley said.
   Norris said it was unusual to find a cetacean skull with the
delicate earbones intact. Those tiny bones could help researchers
learn how whales and other marine mammals developed their
exceptionally acute hearing, he said.
   The animal itself, 15 feet long and weighing 1,500 pounds,
apparently was an adult pygmy baleen whale ``with close linkage to
the modern California gray whale,'' Norris said. California grays
can be as long as 40 feet long and weigh 40 tons.
   Baleen whales, which include the 100-foot blue whale, have no
teeth but eat by filtering plankton and tiny crustaceans from
seawater with bristly baleen plates attached to their upper jaw.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0095 </DOCNO>
