<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ireland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0522,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>British Soldier Charged in Civilian's Death; Anglo-Irish Meeting
Convenes</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with British soldier charged,
Anglo-Irish meeting under way. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `O Fiaich
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old British soldier
was charged today with unlawfully killing an unarmed Roman Catholic
civilian in a case that has further strained tense Anglo-Irish
relations.
   The soldier, David Jonathan Holden, appeared at Cookstown
Magistrates Court, 25 miles west of Belfast, as British and Irish
leaders met across the border in Dublin to discuss the
deterioration in relations.
   In addition to the Holden case, tensions have increased because
of the disclosure Tuesday that another British soldier jailed for
murdering an unarmed Roman Catholic civilian was freed on parole
after serving three years.
   Magistrate Robert Porter ordered Holden held in police custody
until a court appearance in Belfast on March 9. The defense said it
would appeal to the High Court for bail to be set.
   Holden's attorney said the soldier will plead innocent to the
charge of unlawfully killing Aidan McAnespie, 23, an election
worker for Sinn Fein, the legal political arm of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army.
   The British Army said McAnespie was killed Sunday by a
ricocheting bullet after a machine gun was fired accidentally from
an army observation post at a checkpoint near Aughnacloy, half a
mile from the border in County Tyrone.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Tuesday rebuked Irish Prime
Minister Charles Haughey's government for ordering its own
investigation into the shooting. British officials said they
already were investigating.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King paid a courtesy call on
Haughey in Dublin before he joined Irish Foreign Minister Brian
Lenihan and Justice Minister Gerry Collins today for a meeting of
the Anglo-Irish conference.
   The main item on the agenda was proposed British legislation
aimed at guaranteeing a fair division of employment between Roman
Catholics and Protestants in Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland.
   Before entering the meeting, King said: ``We will be talking
about all matters of concern to us both and we shall be having very
frank and valuable discussions. This is the value of the
Anglo-Irish Agreement. It means we can meet to discuss very
difficult issues.''
   The Anglo-Irish Agreement, signed in November 1985, gives the
Irish government a consultative role in the running of Northern
Ireland.
   The conference was set up as a forum for Irish and British
ministers to discuss problems in the province, where the IRA is
fighting to end British rule.
   On Tuesday, security forces ringed Aughnacloy for McAnespie's
funeral.
   Cardinal Tomas O Fiaich, Roman Catholic primate of Ireland who
broke off a trip to San Francisco to attend the funeral, told the
congregation McAnespie had been murdered. McAnespie was buried
across the border in the Irish Republic.
   O Fiaich said he has never hesitated to condemn IRA killings as
murder, adding: ``How can I now avoid using this term `murder' to
describe the killing in broad daylight of one of the best known and
most highly respected men in this parish?''
   Anglo-Irish relations have been severely strained recently by a
series of disputes, principally Britain's refusal after a long
inquiry to prosecute Northern Ireland policemen who shot and killed
six unarmed Catholics in 1982.
   News that a British soldier sentenced to life in prison for
murdering an unarmed Roman Catholic civilian, Thomas Reilly, 22, in
Belfast in 1983 was freed on parole after serving only three years
has added to that tension.
   The British Army in a statement Tuesday confirmed Irish news
reports that Pvt. Ian Richard Thain, who was jailed for murdering
Reilly during rioting in Belfast on Aug. 9, 1983, had been freed on
parole in February 1987.
   Thain, 21, said at his trial he thought Reilly, road manager of
the pop group Bananarama, was reaching for a gun, but the judge
dismissed his claim.
   Upon hearing of Thain's release, Reilly's father, James Reilly,
said: ``It is unbelievable. People talk about British justice but
where is it today? Our son was never involved in anything. He was
murdered.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
