<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1020EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbuseTraining     02-24 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abuse Training,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Say Sexual Abuse Training Should Be Phased Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Pnina Tobin is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Programs aimed at helping California's
preschool children resist sexual abuse are ineffective and should
be phased out, a federally funded study said.
   The programs are beyond the understanding of such young
children, may frighten them away from normal affection and unjustly
make them responsible for the behavior of others, researchers said
Tuesday.
   ``The central idea of training the children bears rethinking,''
said Neil Gilbert, professor of social welfare at the University of
California at Berkeley.
   ``We should not make 4-year-olds responsible for defending
themselves,'' said Gilbert, who conducted the two-year study for
UC-Berkeley's Family Welfare Research Group.
   Programs that try to train preschool children to recognize and
resist sexual abuse reach 42,000 younsters throughout the state.
   The study of 118 preschoolers in seven counties found that
attempts to teach very young children the difference between a
``good touch'' and a ``bad touch'' may confuse them.
   Defining a ``bad touch'' as anything that ``feels bad'' results
in children resisting any contact they do not like at the moment,
such as Grandma's ``yucky'' kiss, Uncle Ed's scratchy cheek and the
tight hug from a well-meaning relative, Gilbert said.
   ``Thus, in the most inclusive view of `bad touch,' children are
taught that virtually a pat on the head could be cause for
reporting to the authorities,'' the report said.
   The report also said responsibility for protecting children lies
with adults and not with the youngsters themselves.
   Teaching 4-year-olds they must ``take charge to control the
outside world ... is an abdication of family and social
responsibility'' and a ``sorry message of these times,''
researchers said.
   However, teaching parents alone will not make children safe from
sexual abuse, said Pnina Tobin, executive director of the San
Francisco-based Children's Self-Help Project, one of the programs
studied.
   ``It does no good just to (educate) the adults around the
child,'' she said. ``What if that adult is the offender? The child
is not protected. They must know there are others they can talk
to.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
