<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LesbianSorority     02-24 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lesbian Sorority,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UCLA Recognizes Nation's First Avowed Lesbian Sorority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sorority formed by lesbians has been
officially recognized by UCLA, reportedly the first such
recognition extended by any U.S. university.
   The decision allows the nine-member Lambda Delta Lambda to meet
on campus and apply for student funds, but university rules forbid
exclusion of heterosexual members.
   ``It was very validating for us,'' sorority president Allison
Adler said of last week's recognition by the Office of Fraternity
and Sorority Relations at the University of California, Los Angeles.
   Although other social and political organizations for homosexual
students exist at UCLA and other campuses, gay activists said they
knew of no other gay-oriented sorority or fraternity that has
formal approval from an American college or university to be part
of a regulated Greek letter system.
   ``I think it's fantastic,'' said Vernon Strickland, a leader of
the Washington, D.C.-based gay fraternity Delta Lambda Phi. ``I
think that means the gentlemen will have no problems getting
recognition.''
   Delta Lambda Phi is trying to organize chapters at UCLA and four
other universities. Its Washington chapter isn't affiliated with
any school.
   ``I never felt any sentimental attachment to UCLA before. But I
now feel proud to be a student here,'' Lambda Delta Lambda member
Julie Leverence said this week. ``Lambda Delta Lambda gives me a
supportive atmosphere and a connection to the school.''
   All nine women members said they are lesbians and said they feel
excluded at existing sororities.
   ``We are not starting this sorority so we can meet new people to
sleep with,'' Marci Kay said. ``We are starting it because we feel
excluded from the Greek system now, and that is a network system
for friendship and professional careers.''
   Lambda Delta Lambda is planning ways to raise money and attract
new members, and it is also considering applying for membership in
the Panhellenic Council, which coordinates many inter-sorority
events.
   ``We don't just want to be separate but equal,'' Adler said.
``We want to be equal.''
</TEXT>
