<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cuba-HumanRights     02-24 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Human Rights,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Official Accuses U.S. Delegate Of Lying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief Cuban delegate to the U.N. Human Rights
Commission today accused the chief U.S. delegate, a former Cuban
political prisoner, of lying about his 22 years in custody.
   Raul Roa Kouri, Cuba's deputy foreign minister, called a news
conference to answer the allegations of Armando Valladares, who
said he was tortured and temporarily crippled while imprisoned in
Cuba.
   ``He was never beaten, he was never tortured,'' Roa said. ``This
doesn't happen in Cuba.'' He said he called the press conference
because ``the credibility of the commission is at stake.''
   Roa distributed copies of documents that included a purported
confidential U.S. State Department memo on Valladares and Cuban
arguments against points made in the memo.
   Valladares, named late last year to head the U.S. delegation to
the 43-nation Human Rights Commission, has been a U.S. citizen
since January 1987. In January 1961, Valladares was sentenced to 30
years in prison in Cuba. He was freed after 22 years following the
intervention of President Francois Mitterrand of France.
   Valladares gained international attention during his
incarceration by writing poetry that he managed to smuggle out of
prison.
   In a book he wrote about his prison years, titled ``Against All
Hope,'' Valladares says he was arrested and jailed because he
voiced his opposition to communism under Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
   Roa said, ``The book is full of lies, and it is boring.''
   Roa repeated Cuban allegations that Valladares was jailed
because he belonged to a group that was planning terrorist
activities to overthrow the government.
   He read from what he said was the record of Valladares' trial,
saying Valladares was convicted of ``planning to take up arms with
the purpose of overthrowing through violent means the powers of the
state.''
   The State Department says Valladares was not charged with
terrorism at his trial and that such allegations only arose later.
   Roa alleged that Valladares had been a police officer under the
government of dictator Fulgencio Batista, who was ousted in 1959 by
Castro loyalists, but he said Valladares was never penalized for
this. He denied that the Cubans had charged Valladares belonged to
Batista's secret police.
   However, a reproduction of an article in the French newspaper Le
Monde in 1983, included in the package of documents distributed by
the Cuban delegation, quotes Castro as saying Valladares was a
member of the ``Gestapo of Batista.'' A U.S. spokesman, Bill
Lawrence, said Roa was ``lying'' when he said Valladares had been a
policeman.
   ``They keep altering their story every year, trying to make it
more acceptable,'' he told The Associated Press. He said Cuba had
also at one time accused Valladares of being a torturer but that
the country now denies having said that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
