<HEAD>Southwestern Bell Receives Thousands of Requests for 976 Blocking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 20,000 customers have asked Southwestern Bell
Telephone to block access to 976 phone numbers, including 8,000 who
called Bell in one day requesting the free service.
   The 976 system has drawn criticism from parents and citizen
groups because some 976 lines offer sexually explicit messages. In
some cases, children have made numerous calls to the services,
racking up large phone bills for their parents. Businesses also
face problems with employees making calls and billing the company.
   Eight thousand calls were received Tuesday, the first day
Southwestern Bell offered to block access to Dial 976 for free,
company spokesman Dave Lopez said. The other calls were made before
Bell began running notices in local newspapers, he said.
   The 20,000 requests represent less than 1 percent of the 3.5
million phone lines in four cities where 976 service is availble _
Dallas, Fort Worth, Houston and San Antonio, Lopez said.
   The Public Service Commission authorized Bell to block the calls
for free last week following hearings in Austin.
