<2ND_LINE>PM-Racial Assault,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Employee of Prosecutor Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The theft of a transcript of grand jury
testimony won't compromise the investigation of the alleged rape
and kidnapping of a black teen-ager, state Attorney General Robert
Abrams said.
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said Tuesday that
a former employee of Abrams' office had been arrested and charged
with stealing and disclosing a transcript of testimony taken before
the Dutchess County grand jury investigating the attack on Tawana
Brawley.
   Abrams was appointed by Gov. Mario Cuomo as a special prosecutor
to investigate the case.
   Miss Brawley, 16, was found on Nov. 28 in Wappingers Falls after
having disappeared for four days. She was wrapped in a plastic
garbage bag and covered with feces, with ``KKK'' and ``nigger''
scrawled on her body.
   On the advice of her attorneys, she has not cooperated with
investigators since shortly after the attack.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, one of Miss Brawley's representatives,
said the alleged theft of the grand jury transcript ``underscores
the ineptness and incompetence that we've been talking about.''
Sharpton said he spoke for attorneys Alton Maddox Jr. and C. Vernon
Mason, who are advising the Brawley family.
   Abrams said the arrest will not affect the investigation, which
continues Monday when a special state grand jury is to be empaneled
in Poughkeepsie.
   Samuel Evans, 49, was employed as the senior printing machine
operator in Abrams' office until his resignation on Feb. 5. He
allegedly stole the Brawley transcript before he left the job.
   Evans, of New York City, surrendered to the district attorney's
office on Tuesday.
   According to Morgenthau, Evans gave the transcript to an
unidentified person on Feb. 18. That person notified the district
attorney's office.
   Evans is charged with fourth-degree grand larceny, which carries
a maximum penalty of four years in prison upon conviction.
   The material did not go beyond Evans and the informant, and no
other document relating to the case was stolen, Abrams said.
</TEXT>
