<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-Syria     02-24 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Syria,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Secretary of State To Visit Damascus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz
will visit Damascus for several hours Saturday as part of a tour of
Middle East capitals to promote Arab-Israeli peace, a Syrian source
said today.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Shultz
will fly to Damascus around noon and depart in the evening. Shultz
will be accompanied by Richard Murphy, his assistant on Middle
Eastern affairs, the source said. He gave no other details.
   U.S. officials said Friday in Washington that Shultz probably
would visit Syria, the Soviet Union's main Arab ally, during his
Middle East tour. Shultz was scheduled to leave Washington late
today for visits to Israel, Jordan and Egypt.
   The U.S. officials said the purpose of the Damascus visit would
be to discuss the U.S. drive for Arab-Israeli negotiations with
President Hafez Assad, whose support for any long-term settlement
in the Middle East is considered essential by specialists at the
State Department's Near East Bureau.
   A visit by Shultz would be a major boost to Syria and would mark
an improvement in its relations with the United States. Syria is
one of six countries on the State Department's list of states
supporting terrorism.
   President Reagan imposed sanctions against Syria in November
1986, after Britain severed diplomatic relations with Damascus
following Syria's implication in an attempt to blow up an Israeli
airliner in London.
   U.S.-Syrian relations began improving last year, when the United
States sent its ambassador back to Damascus.
   Last week, one of the U.S. sanctions against Syria was lifted.
State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that
security clearance requirements on Syrian applicants for U.S. visas
have been lifted. Under the sanctions, all such applicants were
subjected to lengthy checks to qualify for a visa.
</TEXT>
