<1ST_LINE>u p PM-ELN-Republicans 3rdLd-Writethru a0646 02-24 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ELN-Republicans, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0646,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Bush, Kemp comments; pick up 4th graf
pvs bgng ``Dole was...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A triumphant Bob Dole headed for Southern
campaign territory today with two Republican Midwest victories in
hand, proclaiming ``it's a lot more fun winning.'' George Bush
dismissed his losses, saying ``You can't win them all.''
   Dole racked up solid victories in Minnesota's presidential
caucuses and South Dakota's primary while Bush finished third in
South Dakota and last in Minnesota.
   In Portland, Maine, Bush said his poor showings were ``somewhat
anticipated.''
   ``You can't go everywhere,'' he told reporters. ``... You can't
win them all.''
   Jack Kemp, with dismal finishes in both states, took solace in
Bush's equally poor showings.
   ``I think last night proved the race is wide open. That's all I
really needed,'' Kemp said in Beaufort, S.C. ``I needed to break up
the idea that this is a Bush-Dole race.''
   Dole was campaigning today in South Carolina, which holds its
primary March 5, three days before the 20-state Super Tuesday
contest.
   A week ago, Dole lost the New Hampshire primary to Bush. A week
before that, Bush lost the Iowa caucuses to Dole, finishing behind
former television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Robertson, who ran second to Dole in Minnesota and South Dakota,
said he was ``simply delighted'' with his showing in South Dakota.
But he conceded he had hoped for a victory in Minnesota, where he
built a strong organization.
   ``This helps me enormously as I go into the Super Tuesday
states,'' Robertson said today in Atlanta. ``I am very pleased with
what I'm seeing. I believe that coming out of Super Tuesday I will
be the acknowledged front-runner of the Republican Party with
delegates.''
   Bush, who had bypassed campaigning in the two states, went to
bed in Kentucky without commenting to reporters on the returns.
Dole, for his part, was anything but silent.
   ``I hope we send a message that Bob Dole has a message,'' the
Kansas senator told cheering backers at a victory celebration in
Minneapolis. ``That's what the election is all about. I haven't
changed my message. I'm talking about the future, I've talked about
leadership, I've talked about party responsibility, I've talked
about the left-outs, the down-and-outs in America.''
   Returns from all but one precinct in South Dakota gave Dole 55
percent, Robertson 20 percent, Bush 19 percent and Kemp 5 percent.
   In Minnesota, with returns in from 80 percent of the precincts,
Dole had 42 percent, Robertson 28 percent, Kemp 15 and Bush 11.
   Kemp was in a do-or-die effort to make a competitive showing in
one of the Midwest states. On the last weekend of the campaign,
Kemp inundated South Dakota with biographical television
commercials that emphasized family values and he spent most of the
weekend campaigning in Minnesota. But he spent the election night
in South Carolina, unavailable to reporters.
   In Minnesota, the first order of business in the GOP caucuses
was a non-binding straw poll of presidential preference.
   Robertson startled party regulars in the Iowa caucuses with a
strong second-place finish, well ahead of Bush. The former
evangelist saw Minnesota as a similar situation and he hoped to
repeat his Iowa performance.
   Barb Sykora, chairman of the Minnesota Republican Party, had
predicted a lot of people would attend caucuses for the first time.
   ``I think there are going to be a lot of people coming for Pat
Robertson and for Bob Dole,'' she said.
   ``Where is George Bush?'' taunted Dole during campaign
appearances in South Dakota and Minnesota.
   ``Why vote for someone who doesn't come to the state?'' the
Kansas senator asked an audience in Minneapolis, on the final full
day of campaigning.
   As usual, party officials were unable to project the turnout for
Robertson because so many of his supporters were newcomers to
Republican politics.
   Kemp's best showing so far in the race going into Tuesday's
contests was third place in the New Hampshire primary, well behind
Bush and Dole. The New York congressman hoped a strong showing in
Minnesota would give his campaign renewed energy.
   Kemp was staging a bus tour in South Carolina today. On Tuesday,
he told students at the University of South Carolina in Columbia
that he expects to do well in the state.
</TEXT>
