<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Entrapment     02-24 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Entrapment,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Broadens Protection for Some Criminal Defendants in
Wisconsin Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today broadened protection
for criminal defendants who claim they were enticed by law
enforcement officials into committing a crime.
   By a 6-2 vote, the justices overturned a bribery conviction
against Frederick Mathews of Milwaukee, Wis., a former Small
Business Administraton official.
   The court said a criminal defendant should be allowed to
introduce the defense of entrapment at the trial even if he
inconsistently denies committing a criminal act.
   Mathews was sentenced to probation for three years for accepting
a $2,100 loan from James DeShazer, owner of Midwest Knitting Mills.
   Mathews was in charge of a program that provides help to
businesses owned by ``socially and economically disadvantaged''
firms.
   DeShazer, acting as an FBI informant, gave Mathews the money at
a hotel coffee shop on April 23, 1985, and Mathews was arrested as
he left the restaurant.
   Mathews said he needed the money because he had just been told
he was being fired by the SBA and was financially strapped.
   He said he regarded the money as a personal favor from DeShazer
and denied the loan was a bribe to get him to help DeShazer receive
advance payments from the government on a Pentagon contract for
Midwest Knitting Mills.
   A federal judge refused to allow Mathews to present evidence to
the jury to support his claim of entrapment unless he also admitted
that he intended to commit a crime.
   The Supreme Court today said Mathews should be allowed to claim
entrapment while denying he took the money with criminal intent.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, in his opinion for the
court, noted that an entrapment defense is based on a defendant's
claim that he was induced into comitting the crime and lacked a
predisposition to engage in criminal conduct.
   The government argued that a jury cannot logically conclude that
a defendant both failed to commit the elements of the alleged
offense and was entrapped.
   But Rehnquist said defendants are allowed to be inconsistent. He
rejected the government's claim that allowing inconsistent defenses
will encourage perjury, confuse jurors and subvert the
truth-finding purpose of a trial.
   ``We are simply not persuaded by the government's arguments that
we should make the availability of an instruction on entrapment
where the evidence justifies it subject to a requirement of
consistency to which no other such defense is subject,'' Rehnquist
said.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, in a separate concurring opinion, said
he voted with the majority, but only because he believes ``when
genuine inconsistency exists its effect in destroying the
defendant's credibility will suffice to protect the interests of
justice.''
   Dissenting were Justices Byron R. White and Harry A. Blackmun.
Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who joined the court last Thursday, did
not take part in the decision.
   The case is Mathews vs. U.S., 86-6109.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
