<2ND_LINE>PM-West Virginia Budget, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0544,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out W.Va. State Budget</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with treasurer backing down on
threat to halt state checks, quotes, possible safety valve for
governor, transition, DELETE outdated material; Pick up 10th graf
`Senate President....'
^By A.V. GALLAGHER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasurer A. James Manchin today backed
down on his threat to halt all state government checks because of a
state Supreme Court decision invalidating the budget.
   ``It's nothing more than hot air and a whimper of the wind,''
Manchin said of Tuesday's 3-2 ruling by the court, which said the
Legislature had appropriated $26 million more than Gov. Arch Moore
said would be available. The state Constitution requires a balanced
budget.
   Manchin released a number of checks for hospital workers today,
less than 24 hours after threatening to halt the processing of all
state bills. He said the decision allows for a 60-day grace period,
and for a petition for a rehearing, meaning the case won't be
resolved until after the June 30 end of the fiscal year by the time
the court issues a final ruling.
   He called the court decision a ``token action to appease the
West Virginia Education Association,'' and labeled it a ``charade.''
   Legislative leaders say they will ask the court for a rehearing
with the 60-day grace period. Moore has already scheduled a special
session of the Legislature for April 12 to look at education
matters, and the budget question presumably could be considered at
that time.
   Moore, a Republican, had called the treasurer's threat to stop
payments ridiculous. Manchin, a Democrat, had countered Tuesday by
calling the governor's criticism ``rubbish.''
   The governor was in Welch today and could not be reached
immediately for comment on Manchin's decision to release paychecks.
However, press secretary John Price said Moore had a possible
safety valve: a bill he received Tuesday would allow him to borrow
up to $50 million from the state consolidated investment fund of
pension and workers' compensation money.
   Moore is bickering with the Legislature, however, over a
provision that requires him to pay the money back by Sept. 30,
Price said.
   Amid the bitter verbal battle, all sides agreed that the state
was lurching toward a crisis Monday, when a bimonthly payroll of
$15 million is due to go out to 40,000 state employees.
   ``As of this moment, all of the checks are stopped,'' Manchin,
one of three state officials who must sign all checks, had said
Tuesday.
   The high court's ruling, written by Justice Darrell McGraw, did
not tell Moore and the Legislature what to do, saying simply, ``We
presume the governor and Legislature will do their duties.''
   Senate President Dan Tonkovich, a Democrat, said the Legislature
will petition the high court for a rehearing.
   Moore, who was named as a defendant in the court case, never
contested that the budget was unconstitutionally out of balance.
   The state is suffering from slumping tax collections, with
revenue $35.7 million behind projections as of the end of January.
   The New York-based investment firm Standard and Poor's Corp. on
Dec. 15 issued a national warning covering $900 million of West
Virginia's bonds, saying that neither the Legislature nor the
executive branch was addressing the state's ``deteriorating
financial picture.''
   The financial officer at West Virginia University, which employs
more than 8,000 state workers, criticized the court's overturning
of the state budget.
   ``I don't know how you can just shut down the whole world,''
said John Signorelli, associate vice president for finances at the
Morgantown campus.
   Others supported the ruling, including officials of the West
Virginia Education Association, which last year filed the lawsuit
leading to the decision. The suit challenged $13.5 million in cuts
for education funding.
   ``I think it's great. The financing of education is, among
mandated public services, the first constitutional priority,'' said
James Caruth, executive secretary of the 18,500-member association.
   State House parliamentarian Gregory Gray said it was the first
time he knew of that the state's budget was thrown out as
unconstitutional by the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
