<2ND_LINE>PM-Ant Victim,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tot in Critical Condition from Ant Bites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-month-old girl bitten by a horde of
ants was in critical condition today in the children's intensive
care unit of Sacred Heart Hospital, a spokeswoman said.
   Tiffany Cheatam of Navarre, a small Santa Rosa County community
about 20 miles east of this Florida Panhandle city, had stopped
breathing when rescuers arrived at her home shortly after noon
Tuesday, said James Chalmers, an emergency medical technician for
the Holley-Navarre Volunteer Fire Department.
   ``There were ants crawling all over the child,'' Chalmers said.
   Ann Papadelias, a Sacred Heart spokeswoman, said she suspected
the attack was by fire ants, known for their vicious sting, but she
was unable to confirm that with doctors, who were busy treating the
child. Rescuers also said they were unsure what kind of ants were
involved.
   A witness said a dog knocked the girl into a bed of ants in the
child's backyard, said Chief Don Van Derry of the Holley-Navarre
Fire and Rescue Association.
   She was revived through cardiopulminary resuscitation and then a
Life Flight helicopter initially transported her to Gulf Breeze
Hospital. The helicopter later transferred her to Sacred Heart
which has a children's unit.
</TEXT>
