<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CovertAction     02-24 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Covert Action,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Will Oppose Congressional Notification Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIA Director William Webster testified today
that President Reagan would reject legislation tying his hands on
covert activities, including any requirement that he tell Congress
of secret operations within 48 hours.
   Webster told a House panel he agreed with the lawmakers' goal of
preventing another Iran-Contra affair by tightening control of
covert operations, but said a presidentially approved national
security directive would do the job.
   The Reagan administration has already lost round one in its
battle to maintain greater discretion on when to notify Congress.
The Senate Intelligence Committee voted 13-2 for legislation that
includes the 48-hour requirement, and is similar in other respects
to a House bill Webster is now trying to derail.
   ``A bill which fails to preserve the flexibility and authority
the president needs to conduct intelligence activities effectively
will not be acceptable to the president,'' Webster warned, although
he did not use the word ``veto.''
   Members of both intelligence committees introduced the
legislation after Reagan failed for 10 months to notify Congress of
his February 1986 approval of U.S. arms sales to Iran. And he did
so only after a Lebanese publication exposed the U.S.-Iranian
negotiations to free American hostages.
   A number of lawmakers said quick notification would have given
them a chance to presuade Reagan that his policy was a mistake.
   The law now requires an administration to give Congress prior
notification of significant intelligence activities, but allows the
president to delay that in extraordinary circumstances. The
notification must then take place in a ``timely fashion,'' although
the word ``timely'' is left vague.
   In fact, Webster said, there have been only three times when
notification has taken more than two days: the Iran-Contra affair;
the rescue of Americans from Iran who were hidden by Canadian
diplomats, and the failed military attempt to rescue American
hostages in Iran.
   Testifying before a House Intelligence subcommittee, Webster
said many problems in the Iran-Contra affair resulted from
``officials failing to follow existing procedures and rules.'' He
said the secret operations to sell arms to Iran and to the
Nicaraguan Contras were run by National Security Council officials
who did not normally work with these procedures.
   ``Some allowance must be made for that rare case where a limited
delay in congressional notification is critical to preserve the
absolute security of an operation when, for example, lives are at
stake,'' Webster said.
   He added that the new presidential policy requires top
administration officials to re-evaluate at least every 10 days a
presidential decision to delay notification of a given finding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
