<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1255EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-CampaignMoney 4thLd-Writethru a0692 02-24 1140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Money, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0692,1,150</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs new material after 3rd graf pvs, Packwood
was; subs 2 grafs for 10th graf pvs, Bob Dove, to CORRECT date of
last arrest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican senators reacted angrily today
after U.S. Capitol police seized Sen. Robert Packwood and carried
him to the Senate floor _ feet first _ to answer a quorum call
during an all-night filibuster over campaign financing legislation.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said the parliamentary arrest of
Packwood by Senate Sergeant-at-Arms Henry Guigni and five
plainclothes Capitol policemen was ``demeaning and pointless.''
   Packwood was treated like a ``common criminal ... brought
forcefully to the floor of the United States Senate,'' said Specter.
   But several Republican senators actually ran away from police to
avoid arrest, said Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.
   ``Senators went off in a dead sprint. They should have been in
Calgary in one of the Olympic events,'' he said. ``The spectacle of
a United States senator running from the sergeant-at-arms in order
to keep from being compelled to attend a session of the United
States Senate is an outrage.''
   Packwood's spokesman, Bob Witeck, said the Oregon Republican
re-injured a broken hand, which has been in a cast the last two
weeks, when the police entered his office with a passkey. Witeck
said that Packwood went to a hospital early today to have X-rays
taken but that no new breaks were found.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said Packwood's arm was ``severely
jostled and hurt'' by ``Banana Republic'' tactics.
   ``When a senator is locked in his own chamber, I question
whether it is constitutionally sound to break into his office and
force him out of his office and carry him to the floor,'' Hatch
said.
   Packwood's spokesman said the senator ``tried to hold the door
closed with his shoulder, but they were able to push it open.''
   ``I had to take him in,'' siad Guigni, a one-time Honolulu
motorcycle and vice officer. ``I knew he was not going in under his
own power.''
   Guigni said Packwood walked with the detectives to the Capitol,
but made it clear he would not walk into the chamber. ``We picked
him up in the elevator'' and carried him to his desk, Guigni said.
   The motion to arrest absent senators was made by Senate Majority
Leader Robert Byrd of West Virginia and was approved on a 45-3 roll
call vote, with Democratic senators Dennis DeConcini of Arizona,
Howell Heflin of Alabama and Richard Shelby of Alabama voting no.
Specter said the actual warrants were signed by Sen. Brock Adams,
D-Wash.
   Senate officials said the arrest was the first since Democratic
senators Burnet Rhett Maybank of South Carolina and Lister Hill of
Alabama were compelled to come to the floor in 1942.
   Packwood, a leader of GOP opposition to a Democratic campaign
finance bill, was brought in by four officers under terms of an
unusual motion approved through late Tuesday by the majority
Democrats.
   The Democrats, who were forcing the Republicans to wage the
filibuster in an effort to subdue the GOP opposition to the
Democrats' proposed limits on campaign spending and contributions
from political action committees, employed the rarely used
procedure to require absent members to answer quorum bells or face
arrest.
   Republicans had been taking turns holding the floor to prevent
the Democrats from bringing the bill to a vote they can win. This
upset the Democrats, who had been forced to stay close to the
chamber, maintain a quorum and keep the Senate in session.
   When most Republicans stopped answering quorum calls, the
Democrats resorted to ordering Guigni to scour the hallways and
offices and arrest absent senators. He carried warrants for each of
the 46 Republicans.
   Packwood was found in his Russell Building office, Guigni said.
   ``I had to shove in a door to get into his office,'' Guigni
said. ``I think he hurt his finger. He was very courteous.''
   Packwood was not available for immediate comment.
   Some 13 hours after the filibuster began, the two sides called a
truce of sorts. Republicans would continue to talk, but there would
be no more quorum calls until 10 a.m., giving most members a chance
to sleep.
   As dawn broke, Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., wound up an hour
of holding the floor, speaking against the bill in a steady,
conversational tone.
   ``I've immensely enjoyed this, particularly at this time of day.
There's nothing I'd rather be doing,'' Durenberger said as turned
control of the floor over to Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I.
   Durenberger spoke to an almost-empty chamber. Freshman Sen. Kent
Conrad, D-N.D., sat at the podium, while Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky.,
represented the Democratic side of the aisle.
   Eight teen-aged pages sat quietly on the carpeted steps leading
to the podium and a few detectives sat in the otherwise empty
gallery.
   The ``full-fledged filibuster'' was formally proclaimed by
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., on Tuesday after Republicans
had done for five days what they had done for 22 days last year _
prevent a vote on the Democrats' campaign spending bill.
   Byrd has the votes to pass the bill, which would set voluntary
spending limits for Senate general elections. But he is still about
five votes short of the 60 he needs to shut off debate and force a
roll call.
   Early today, Democrats filed a cloture petition, which probably
will be considered on Friday.
   Republicans, who last year beat Byrd on a record seven cloture
votes, say the proposed system to curb escalating campaign spending
would prevent them from gaining seats in heavily Democratic states.
   Dove said the filibuster is the chamber's first knock-down test
of attrition since a nine-day battle in 1960 over civil rights
legislation.
   Four senators from each camp have been negotiating since last
week, trying to find a compromise. They say they have found some
common ground on issues such as better disclosure of money going to
political paries and forcing broadcasters to offer rock-bottom ad
rates to candidates.
   But they report nothing but disagreement over limiting campaign
spending, which has risen from $600,000 for the average Senate race
in 1976 to $3 million in 1986, with a big-state race often topping
$10 million.
   The chief GOP negotiator, Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, said
Republicans were willing to discuss a compromise on another
Democratic demand: putting a ceiling on how much money a candidate
can get from political action committees.
   The Democrats' bill would establish voluntary spending limits,
ranging from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's
population.
   A candidate observing the limit would get campaign funds from
the Treasury if the opponent exceeded the limit or an independent
group spent large amounts of money against the candidate.
   The Republicans would have some limits on individual PAC
contributions while strengthening campaign-finance disclosure
requirements and opposing spending limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
