<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-Subpoena     02-24 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Subpoena,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Member Turns Over Documents Demanded By House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Trade Commission member Terry Calvani
escaped a contempt of Congress citation Wednesday by turning over
documents demanded by a congressional panel, but he said he felt he
had become a scapegoat in a turf fight between two congressmen.
   Calvani had been subpoenaed to appear before the House Committee
on Energy and Commerce's subcommittee on oversight and
investigations because he had refused to turn over some internal
FTC documents sought by the panel concerning unfair advertising
practices by the airline industry.
   He told the panel that the subcommittee's insistence on
obtaining internal advisory documents ``represents a very poor
development in the exercise of this subcommittee's oversight
reponsibilities over the Federal Trade Commission.''
   Calvani said that ``violation of the confidence between a
commissioner and his or her personal attorney-advisers makes
government less efficient.''
   ``I tell the men and women that serve in my office that I want
their wholly candid assessment and unvarnished recommendation about
matters before me,'' Calvani said. Due to the subcommittee's
insistence on access to internal documents, he said, ``This morning
I have instructed my staff that from henceforth they should not
commit their work to paper.''
   He said that until Friday, the panel had not provided the legal
justification for him to provide the documents and said he could
not test the legality of the demand without being willing to stand
criminal trial.
   ``To my knowledge this Kafka-esque mode of operations is unique
in our system of justice,'' Calvani said.
   After his appearance, Calvani said he believed he had become
caught in a ``turf fight'' between panel Chairman John D. Dingell,
D-Mich., and Rep. James J. Howard, D-N.J., chairman of the
Committee on Public Works and Transportation.
   ``I'm the pawn,'' he said. ``They were looking for a scapegoat,
and I'm the unfortunate person chosen for that.''
   Subcommittee counsel Patrick McLain refused to comment on
Calvani's allegation. Dingell's office referred all request for
comment to McLain.
   At issue were internal documents concerning the FTC's views on
whether unfair and deceptive advertising practices were occurring
in the airline industry.
   A letter on the matter from the FTC to the National Association
of Attorneys General indicated that the agency had not studied the
matter, but a press release on the report indicated that the agency
believed there was no problem with the airline industry's practices.
   A reference to the press release comment, included in a story by
The Washington Post, was read on the House floor last October and
helped defeat an amendment by Dingell that would have transferred
responsibility for oversight for consumer protection regarding the
airline industry from the Department of Transportation to the FTC,
McLain said.
   The subcommittee began asking the FTC for internal documents on
the matter several days later. Two commissioners said they had no
such documents, two others allowed subcommittee staff to read
pertinent materials in their offices, but Calvani refused to
provide access to such documents.
   After several letters back and forth between the subcommittee
and Calvani, who was insisting on the legal justification for the
demand, the panel on Feb. 4 subpoenaed Calvani to appear and bring
the documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
