<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Goetz     02-24 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Goetz,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subway Gunman Changing Lawyer in Civil Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Subway gunman Bernhard Goetz is looking for a
new lawyer to handle his defense against civil suits seeking a
total of $63 million for three of the four youths he shot,
according to one of his attorneys.
   Goetz decided to break with Joseph Kelner, the attorney he had
hired for the civil cases, because of ``differences of viewpoint,''
said Mark Baker, who with Barry Slotnick last year won acquittal
for Goetz on the most serious criminal charges stemming from the
shooting.
   Published reports quoted Kelner as saying he was withdrawing
from the case because Goetz was not cooperating.
   Goetz was convicted of weapon possession but acquitted of
attempted murder, assault and reckless endangerment in the Dec. 22,
1984, subway shooting of four young men. Goetz, who is white, said
he feared the black youths were going to rob him.
   Two of the youths brought civil actions for $5 million and $8.5
million, while lawyers for Darrell Cabey, brain-damaged and
paralyzed by the shooting, seek $50 million. Cabey's lawyers say
the shooting was racist and ``wrongful retaliation for past
injury'' Goetz had suffered at the hands of others.
</TEXT>
