<HEAD>UNDATED: the outcome.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 21
   Bryan-College Station (Texas) Eagle on President Reagan's budget:
   Ronald Reagan is going down in history as the country's biggest
spendthrift president. He has put the nation in hock to the hilt,
and mortgaged the future of our children and their children.
   The budget he presented to Congress last week raised the
national debt to $2.5 trillion _ a figure that has doubled during
his administration. Interest payments alone cost $140 billion a
year. ...
   To be sure, the president has had lots of help getting us into
all this trouble. It was only with the help of a spineless Congress
that he was able to borrow vast sums to finance his massive defense
buildup and to offset revenues lost in his tax-cutting programs.
   The next president simply must force the country to face the
fact that we can't continue spending money we don't have.
   With all the presidential candidates whistling Dixie this month,
voters would be wise to listen closely for who is sounding the
clear notes on this issue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 18
   The News Tribune, Woodbridge, N.J., on the verdict in the Amtrak
crash:
   Sixteen people died, scores were injured, and tens of millions
of dollars worth of damage was done when a Conrail engineer ran his
locomotive through a stop sign and plowed into an Amtrak passenger
train. The engineer tested positive for marijuana use.
   After he pleaded guilty to one count of manslaughter, he was
given a maximum sentence of five years in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Unless he had been hiding in a cave, Rick Gates knew what
marijuana could do to the senses. Gates also had to know the damage
a misguided train could cause.
   So what was the message? Sixteen dead passengers equals five
years maximum, which doesn't sound like much of a deterrent to us.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 19
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on the 1990 census:
   Let's conduct a census and count everybody but Swedes ... or
maybe Irish ... or Americans who migrate with the seasons ... or
some other identifiable population group.
   Why do that? To fix the outcome, silly. What other reason could
there be?
   A coalition of congressional members wants to do that in 1990
when the Constitution says the country must conduct a decennial
head count.
   About 40 House members want to count everyone but illegal aliens
and will sue the Census Bureau to force the exclusion. It is
estimated there are about 2 million illegal aliens in the United
States.
   Why do these members of Congress want to ignore illegal aliens?
To fix the outcome of the 1990 census, of course.
   The national head count is used to distribute seats in the House
of Representatives, and they fear aliens will cause unfair shifts
from one state to another.
   To their credit, census officials say they read the Constitution
to say everyone must be counted (``the whole number of persons'').
   Of course, everyone should be included.
</TEXT>
