<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Simon 3rdLd-Writethru a0720 02-24 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simon, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0720,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon to Stay in Race but Skip Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with new quotes, details</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon, battered in the early
Democratic contests, said today he is bypassing the March 8 Super
Tuesday primaries and caucuses because he does ``not have the
resources for winning'' them.
   But the Illinois Democrat said he was not dropping out of the
race and would continue to campaign to win his home state primary
on March 15 and the contests in the states that follow.
   ``The campaign will begin anew after Super Tuesday, starting in
Illinois,'' Simon told a news conference.
   Simon was dealt a crippling blow Tuesday when he finished far
behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and was trailing Jesse
Jackson in Minnesota's caucuses. He came in a distant fourth in the
South Dakota primary behind Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri,
Dukakis and Albert Gore Jr.
   Last week after coming in third in the New Hampshire primary,
Simon said he would withdraw if he did not finish first in either
Minnesota or South Dakota. He later backed off that statement.
   Faced with primaries and caucuses in 20 states and American
Samoa on March 8, Simon said he cannot raise the money to match the
big warchests of Dukakis and Gore in the region.
   ``There is no sense in my fooling myself,'' the Illinois
Democrat said. ``We just don't have the money.''
   His campaign plunged into debt before the New Hampshire primary,
but he has been talking of close to half a million dollars gathered
in the past two weeks.
   ``We have had record-breaking fund-raising,'' Simon declared.
``Monday, for example, $137,000 came in. We never had a day like
that before. But you take $137,000 and then look at 20 states and
what it would cost for a media buy, and you're talking about
something that is nowhere near adequate.''
   Simon also said he had made the judgment that March 8 will not
settle the race and that the battle for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination will go to the convention in Atlanta in
July.
   ``Super Tuesday is likely to result in a very mixed picture,''
he said. ``Phase one of the selection process ends on March 8. ...
But we do not have the resources for winning in the Super Tuesday
states.''
   ``Phase two of the selection process begins March 15. I shall
use phase two to deliver the message that we must become a nation
with leadership characterized by compassion and vision and common
sense. It is on to Atlanta with that message.''
   Simon is on the ballot in all the Super Tuesday primaries, but
he said he will do little or no campaigning in those states _
except for the nationally televised debates that are a major
feature of the next two weeks.
   ``I'm not writing off the South. I want my friends there to vote
for me,'' he said. ``I'm realistic about resources. I simply cannot
do everything.''
   Dukakis and Gephardt have split the four major Democratic
contests so far. And Simon said he had concluded the party will not
have a certain winner going into the Atlanta convention.
   He cited ``growing evidence that for the first time in recent
history there will be no first-ballot winner at the Democratic
convention.''
   Simon's best day so far was in Iowa on Feb. 8, where he finished
a very close second to Gephardt. He was third in New Hampshire.
   He talked to reporters after a speech to the United Auto Workers
at a Washington hotel.
</TEXT>
