<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CampusTakeover 1stLd-Writethru a0719 02-24 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campus Takeover, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0719,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Occupy Dormitory Office, March</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with students complaints, racial makeup of
student body.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 Hampshire College students
occupied a dormitory office for a second day in a protest over
racism and marched across campus today to present a list of 12
demands to the college president.
   The group then withdrew to the Dakin House office they seized
Tuesday morning and said they did not plan to meet again with
president Adele Simmons until 9 a.m. Thursday.
   The protesters deliberately delayed negotiations, said Penny
Predmas, a junior from New York City.
   ``We are building our sense of our community, so we can feel
invincible,'' she said.
   The protesters were escorted across campus by about 100
students, who snaked through a classroom building and a building
housing administrative offices chanting, ``One, two, three, four.
Racism has got to go.''
   Among the protesters' demands were additional library materials
dealing with Third World nations, establishment of a college policy
on racial harassment, a full-time adviser for minority students, a
permanent meeting place for non-white students, a minority
recruitment week each semester, and no retaliatory actions against
the protesters.
   About a dozen white supporters pitched tents and staged an
overnight vigil outside Dakin House, and students from nearby
Amherst, Mount Holyoke and Smith colleges as well as the University
of Massachusetts joined the demonstraters this morning.
   A week ago about 125 minority students at the University of
Massachusetts began a six-day occupation at a building there.
   ``The problems are the same, although the sizes of the minority
communities are different,'' said Hampshire freshman Anita Fearman
of Los Angeles.
   ``There's a general feeling here that we've been more or less
pushed under the rug,'' said Ms. Fearman, who is black.
   Although there have been racial attacks at the University of
Massachusetts, there have been none at Hampshire, which lists 100
minority students among its 1,100 undergraduates. But minorities
complained of verbal harassment and a lack of attention to Third
World issues.
   ``We have been to the administration several times over the past
three years with our demands and concerns and nothing has been
done,'' Premdas said. ``It's been all lip service. It seemed this
was the only way to get something done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-A-Glance     02-24 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-A-Glance,400</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Wednesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   FALWELL-HUSTLER
   
   The court overturned a $200,000 award won by evangelist Jerry
Falwell against Hustler magazine and its publisher Larry Flynt,
extending the legal protections for parody and satire, even when
they are pornographic.
   The court unanimously ruled that even pornographic spoofs about
a public figure enjoy the free-speech protections of the
Constitution's First Amendment if those spoofs could not reasonably
have been interpreted as stating actual facts about the person.
   The case is Hustler vs. Falwell, 86-1278.
   
   RENT CONTROLS
   
   The court expanded the power of communities to impose rent
controls, ruling that hardships to tenants may be considered when
landlords seek rent increases.
   By a 6-2 vote, the justices upheld a San Jose, Calif., ordinance
that has been attacked as a ``Robin Hood'' law that steals from the
rich to pay the poor.
   The case is Pennell vs. San Jose, 86-753.
   
   ENTRAPMENT
   
   The court broadened protection for criminal defendants who claim
they were enticed by law enforcement officials into committing a
crime.
   By a 6-2 vote, the justices overturned a bribery conviction
against Frederick Mathews of Milwaukee, Wis., a former Small
Business Administration official.
   The case is Mathews vs. U.S., 86-6109.
   
   DEFENDANT'S TESTIMONY
   
   The court made it a bit easier for prosecutors to talk to
criminal trial juries about a defendant's failure to testify.
   In splintered voting, the court reinstated the mail fraud
conviction of a man who prosecutors say set his tennessee home
afire so he could file a false insurance claim.
   The case is U.S. vs. Robinson, 86-937.
   
   DEFAULT JUDGMENT
   
   The court bolstered the right default-judgment losers have to
challenge a judgment entered after they fail to respond to a
lawsuit.
   The justices unanimously ruled for a Houston businessman in his
challenge of a default judgment awarded against him six years ago
for a $5,000 debt owed to a medical center.
   The case is Peralta vs. Heights Medical Center, 86-1430.
   
   LAWYERS FEES
   
   The court ruled that federal judges lack authority to order the
government to pay fees to lawyers who successfully obtain overdue
federal welfare for poor people who are aged, blin or disabled.
   The 8-0 ruling in a case from Arkansas held that federal
officials are not required by law to withhold a portion of a
recipient's benefits to pay the attorney.
   The case is Bowen vs. Galbreath, 86-1146.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0736 02-24 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0736,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Reportedly Lynched By Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines a0736, a0596. CORRECTS girl to boy in 5th graf
``Security sources...'' Edits to trim and conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry Palestinians today lynched an Arab who
they apparently suspected of collaborating with the Israelis,
stringing him up on a utility pole after he went on a shooting
spree that killed a 4-year-old boy and wounded 13 other people,
security sources said.
   Israel radio called the incident in a West Bank village ``a
serious escalation'' of the unrest in the occupied territories and
linked it to the Palestine Liberation Organization's calls to deal
with collaborators.
   The dead man's identity was not immediately known.
   Details were sketchy concerning the incident in Qabatiye, near
Jenin, 60 miles north of Jerusalem. However, Israel radio said the
violence began when hundreds of residents marched to the man's
house, threw firebombs and setting it afire.
   Security sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
man shot into the crowd, which apparently suspected him of
collaborating with Israeli authorities, killing the boy and
wounding the others.
   Israel radio said the crowd then dragged the man away and hanged
him. Security sources confirmed the report.
   An army spokesman said soldiers arrived after the hanging.
According to the United Nations, 63 Arabs have been killed, most by
soldiers, since the wave of unrest began Dec. 8 in the occupied
territories.
   A general strike gripped the West Bank and Gaza Strip today as
businesses shut down and Arab workers stayed home in response to a
call for stepped up protests before Secretary of State George P.
Shultz arrives.
   Also today, the army reported what it said may be the first
armed attack against the military in the past 2{ months of unrest
in the territories seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
   An army spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
bomb exploded on a road near Gaza as a vehicle was passing Tuesday
night and shots were fired. There were no injuries.
   Extra-tight security arrangements went into effect today at Ben
Gurion airport in advance of Shultz's arrival Thursday. Airport
police said riot police units were called in and will stay on duty
through Tuesday as Shultz conducts his shuttle mission in the
Middle East.
   In the Gaza Strip today, few people were on the streets and only
one or two cars were seen moving. Most Arab laborers stayed away
from their jobs in Israel, there was little public transport, and
there were reports of a few scattered tire-burning and
stone-throwing incidents.
   Much of the West Bank was dusted white with a thin layer of snow
that fell overnight and some Arab youths in a Jerusalem
neighborhood threw snowballs at passing cars, a relief from the
stone-throwing of previous days.
   Business was at a standstill today. There was little traffic and
few workers left home, according to army radio.
   The underground National Leadership of the Uprising, in leaflets
distributed throughout the territories, called for a general strike
today and Thursday.
   Shultz is coming to Israel to launch a new peace initiative he
hopes will put an end to the violence of past weeks, bring the
Arabs and Israelis to the negotiating table and eventually achieve
an overall solution to the Mideast conflict.
   The secretary of state has acknowledged he has only a slim
chance of accomplishing that goal during his visit. The Shultz
initiative, which includes trading territory for peace, is likely
to encounter opposition from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud
Bloc.
   Deputy Prime Minister David Levy, interviewed on army radio,
said on Tuesday the new initiative contradicts the 10-year-old Camp
David agreement.
   ``There is confusion in it and an attempt to sell it to Israel
as Camp David and to sell it to the Arabs that will give them
almost all of the West Bank and Gaza,'' he said.
   The PLO has prohibited local Palestinians from meeting Shultz.
Fayez Abu Rahme, a Gaza lawyer who was among a group of Arabs who
met with a U.S. official on Saturday, said: ``As far as we are
concerned there won't be a meeting.''
   David Good, spokesman for the U.S. Consulate in Jerusalem, said
he did not know if Palestinians will meet with Shultz.
   Informed U.S. sources said Shultz would not meet with
Palestinians outside Jerusalem. ``We're not taking directions from
the PLO on how to meet with Palestinians,'' said the source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
