<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HowardBeachDriver     02-24 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Howard Beach Driver,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State DMV Revokes Driver's License In Howard Beach Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Department of Motor Vehicles today
revoked the driver's license of a man who was driving the car that
killed a black man in the Howard Beach racial assault case.
   DMV officials said the order against Dominic Blum's license
would take effect March 10. Blum would be eligible to apply to have
the license reinstated after 30 days, said DMV spokesman R. Bryan
Jackson.
   Blum's lawyer, William Breuer, said the order would be appealed
to the DMV's administrative review board and then to the courts, if
necessary.
   ``This is an aberration,'' Breuer said of the DMV's action.
``There's no evidence to support this.''
   Three white men were convicted of manslaughter in connection
with Michael Griffith being chased onto the Belt Parkway in Queens
where he was struck on the night of Dec. 20, 1986, by Blum's car.
   Blum, a court officer and son of a New York City policeman, was
not charged in connection with the case.
   In revoking Blum's license, DMV officials said Blum was guilty
of leaving the scene of a personal injury accident, operating a
motor vehicle at a speed greater than is reasonable and prudent,
and following too closely.
</TEXT>
