<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WestiesTrial     02-24 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Westies Trial,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partial Verdict In Westies Rackets Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven of eight accused members of the Westies
gang were found guilty today of various crimes including murder
conspiracy, extortion and drug dealing.
   The federal jury that convicted them will receive further
instructions and resume deliberations on the most significant
charges, racketeering and racketeering conspiracy.
   In its eighth day of deliberations, the sequestered jury in
Manhattan's federal court returned a finding that the Westies gang
was a racketeering enterprise and that seven of the eight
defendants were involved with the gang.
   The jury of 10 women and two men also found that all but one of
the defendants had each committed at least two of the 28 criminal
acts listed in the racketeering charges, including murders,
kidnappings, extortion, loansharking and drug dealing.
   But unlike other racketeering trials, U.S. District Judge
Whitman Knapp will give jurors additional instructions before
sending them back to determine if those acts were committed as part
of a racketeering enterprise.
   One defendant, John Halo, was acquitted on all charges.
   Convicted on various other charges were: reputed Westies leader
James Coonan; his wife, Edna; James ``Jimmy Mack'' McElroy; Richard
``Muggsy'' Ritter; William ``Indian'' Bokun; Thomas Collins; and
Collins' wife Florence.
</TEXT>
