<DOCNO> AP880224-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0642 02-24 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0642,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham's New Attorney Seeks Delay in Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Senate Majority leader
against delaying the trial again, prosecutors asking for contempt
sanctions against Mecham attorney. Pickup 4th graf, `Leonard
said...' ADDS 5 grafs at end with details of request for contempt
sanctions.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's new attorney says he
will seek a postponement of the impeachment trial before the
Arizona Senate, which is set to start Monday.
   ``We will be requesting ... that the trial be postponed,''
Jerris Leonard said in an interview late Tuesday night. He said he
would meet today with state Supreme Court Chief Justice Frank
Gordon, who is presiding over the trial, and with Senate President
Carl Kunasek.
   Senate Majority Leader Bob Usdane, a Republican, noted today
that the trial already has been delayed a week and added, ``My
inclination is to not give them another minute of delay. ... I
think it's a tactic. I think they've known all along what they were
going to be doing.''
   Meanwhile, the state House's impeachment prosecutors today asked
that contempt sanctions be imposed against Mecham attorney Murray
Miller for refusing to provide a list of planned witnesses before
the Senate trial begins. Prosecutors William French and Paul
Eckstein accused Miller of ``patent, blatant disregard and
disobedience'' of a deadline set by Gordon.
   Leonard, who headed the Law Enforcement Assistance
Administration in the Nixon administration, also said he planned to
meet with Miller.
   Leonard said he was retained by Mecham Monday night.
   ``I am certainly very enthusiastic to take the case,'' Leonard
said.
   ``We're going to put together a very strong defense in his
behalf, a very forceful, fruitful, responsible defense and hope
that the members will be persuaded by it,'' Leonard said.
   Roy Dunton, former Mohave County Republican Party chairman and
founder of the Mecham Legal Defense Fund, said Tuesday that Leonard
was hired as the lead defense counsel.
   Edith Richardson, chief spokeswoman for Mecham's recall election
campaign, said Tuesday night that Leonard had been added to the
defense team, ``but I'm not sure of the terminology, whether he is
the lead attorney.''
   She said she believed that Miller and Michael Scott, the
attorney for Mecham's brother, Willard, would handle the criminal
defense.
   In addition to the impeachment trial, Mecham and his brother
face felony charges stemming from Mecham's alleged failure to
properly report a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Leonard ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate from Wisconsin in
1968 and in 1969 was named director of the Law Enforcement
Assistance Administration by President Nixon. He also served as an
assistant U.S. attorney general in Washington.
   He joined the Washington law firm of Manatt, Phelps, Rothenberg,
Tunney & Evan in May 1986.
   French and Eckstein, in their motion for contempt sanctions,
said Mecham's defense should not be permitted to call any witnesses
during the trial unless they meet today's 5 p.m. deadline to
provide a list.
   The prosecution submitted a list of 41 possible witnesses Monday.
   Miller said in a letter Monday he did not want to disclose his
planned witnesses because he thought it was unfair to hold Mecham's
impeachment trial before his criminal trial is over.
   Gordon also had set a 9 a.m. deadline today for Miller to file
any objections to the impeachment counts, but no documents were
filed by that time.
   Usdane said he thought the deadlines set by Gordon appeared to
be more of a request than an order, and questioned whether
sanctions could be imposed if there was no direct order involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
