<HEAD>Swaggart Once Wrote That Pornography `Addictive'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Swaggart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, who is said
to have confessed an obsession with pornography, once wrote a
newspaper column saying pornography is as addictive as drugs.
   Swaggart faces disciplinary action by his denomination, the
Assemblies of God, for sexual misconduct. He was reportedly
observed and photographed while visiting a prostitute in New
Orleans.
   The Rev. Glen Cole of Sacramento, Calif., one of 13 members of
the Assemblies of God's ruling executive presbytery, said Swaggart
had confessed last week to having an obsession with pornography
dating back to his youth.
   James Hammill of Memphis, Tenn., a member of the denomination's
general counsel, said Monday night that the panel had been given
pictures of Swaggart going in and out of a New Orleans motel room
with a woman.
   In a July 1986 column for the Baton Rouge Sunday Advocate,
Swaggart wrote:
   ``Pornography is now considered as addictive as drugs, leading,
as with any addiction, to a need for escalated `doses' and
intensity. That, in turn, breeds desensitization, which leads to
the acting out of roles that have been at the heart of the nation's
most sensational serial murder and serial rape cases.
   ``Women and children, portrayed as nothing more than debased
objects on screen and in print, pay a particularly high price when
fantasy turns into reality.''
   Swaggart called those who make their living from pornography
``wretched, disgusting and dangerous.''
   In another column, Swaggart wrote: ``Most of today's sex, I'm
afraid, is a consequence of lust, and that has absolutely nothing
to do with love.
   ``You see, the laws of God cannot be abrogated with impunity.
Yes, we can do it, we are free moral agents. To do so, however,
means that we `pay the piper,' and we're now starting to do so.''
   The December issue of Swaggart's magazine, the Evangelist, was
critical of Mercer University, a Baptist school that did not take
disciplinary action against six women who posed for Playboy
magazine.
   ``It seems to us that if the standards set forth in the Word of
God were truly being taught, neither the girls nor the university
would find themselves in this embarrassing circumstance,'' the
magazine said.
