<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Portugal 2ndLd-Writethru a0697 02-24 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Portugal, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0697,610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 4 grafs new, picking up 3rd graf pvs, The Portguese</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portuguese Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva,
disappointed in American aid levels, said today his nation wants to
review a 1983 U.S.-Portugal defense agreement giving the United
States access to a key air base.
   Cavaco Silva, emerging from a two-hour meeting at the White
House with President Reagan, said he told the president that cuts
in American aid have posed difficulties ``particularly at a time
when we are committed to the re-equipment of our armed forces and
trying to modernize the country.''
   ``I stated to President Reagan that the Portuguese government
intended to request that consultations be held under the terms of
the agreement,'' Cavaco Silva said.
   Reagan reiterated U.S. desire to help Portugal, but he said
``the efforts remain firm, even within the context of the harsh
budger realities that we all face. The task of leadership is to
rise to the challenge.''
   The Portuguese leader is using his first official visit to
Washington to register disappointment that the United States is
providing barely more than half the $205 million that Portugal
wants in aid each year for U.S. rights at Lajes Air Base in the
Azores, a vital refueling point in the Atlantic.
   The U.S. deficit-reduction program is responsible for the cuts,
not just in aid to Portugal but to the Philippines, Greece, and
Turkey _ other base-rights countries with struggling economies.
   A senior U.S. official, briefing reporters in advance of Cavaco
Silva's meeting at the White House with President Reagan today,
said ``we're going to have a foreign policy job to do in convincing
them why we're doing it and why we have to share the pain
together.''
   Cavaco Silva arrived on Tuesday for three days of talks.
   Portugal is disappointed in the aid levels, which have dipped to
$117 million this year after hitting a high of $205 million in
1984, one year after the current base agreement was signed.
   In his budget proposal last week, Reagan asked Congress for $163
million for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   The U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he
doubted the prime minister wanted a ``confrontation'' during his
visit to Washington.
   ``Rather, we'll look for ways we can figure out _ at least in
the short run _ some of our problems,'' the official said.
   Earlier this month, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci appeared
to have soothed Portuguese feelings enough to head off a request
for a formal review of the U.S.-Portugal defense agreement. He
received permission from Cavaco Silva's government to send over
surplus U.S. military equipment to make up part of the shortfall in
financial assistance.
   Experts from both defense departments are to meet soon to figure
out what Portugal can use from U.S. stocks.
   In the past two weeks, however, Portuguese Foreign Minister Joao
de Deus Pinheiro and President Mario Soares have expressed
reservations about the plan.
   Nevertheless, the U.S. official said, ``I think what he (Cavaco
Silva) told Frank Carlucci at the beginning of February, we expect,
holds.
   ``Obviously the Portuguese are disappointed with the levels of
assistance. So are we,'' the official said. ``Invariably we've
requested more money out of Congress and in recent years have not
done very well. As the budget crunch is being faced by all
agencies, obviously security assistance is one of those areas hit.
   ``We're probably going to face it in a great amount of
countries, particularly countries that feel they have a commitment
for a certain level of military assistance and believe that they
have been good allies.''
</TEXT>
