<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     02-24 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Attacking Negative Ads, Wants Campaign ``Back On The High
Road''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael S. Dukakis said Wednesday he will do
whatever he has to do to counter any negative ads by his rivals for
the Democratic presidential nomination but hopes ``we can get this
campaign back on the high road.''
   The Massachusetts governor's second-place showing in the South
Dakota primary Tuesday was blamed in part on ``attack ads'' by top
vote-getter Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, Dukakis' South Dakota
chairman Fritz Wiecking was quoted as saying.
   The ads claimed Dukakis has no farm or trade policy and is the
biggest taxer in Massachusetts history. Dukakis called the ads
inaccurate.
   At a news conference, Dukakis said ``maybe it is a vain hope''
for the Democrats to avoid the kind of charges and countercharges
circulating among the Republican candidates, which Dukakis termed
damaging to the GOP, their candidates and the election process.
   ``I would prefer that the Democrats not copy the Republicans,
and that we try to run strong, positive campaigns in which if we
disagree with each other we do so agreeably and accurately,''
Dukakis said.
   But he added, ``negative campaigning and negative advertising
apparently is the thing all of the sudden. I have had to go through
that before, and if I have to do what I have to do, I will do so.
But I would hope that we can get this campaign back on the high
road.''
   Asked to elaborate, Dukakis said, ``I'll deal with that when the
time comes. I've had to do it before, I hope I don't have to do it
(again).''
   But he did specifically mention Gephardt and Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore.
   Dukakis said the American people ``are not interested with what
Mr. Gore thinks of Mr. Gephardt, Mr. Gephardt thinks of Mr. Gore,
what both of them think of me.
   ``These two guys are at it every day. Now they are trying to get
me into it,'' Dukakis said.
   ``There is nothing wrong with disagreeing on particular
issues,'' he said. ``I have no problem with that. But I would hope
we could avoid it (negative campaigning). Can we? We'll see.''
   Saying he was the only Democratic candidate competing with equal
force in all states, Dukakis summed up Tuesday's results, including
his victory in Minnesota, by saying, ``We competed aggressively in
Minnesota, competed aggressively in South Dakota. And the results,
I think, are very heartwarming.''
   But as the candidates head toward Super Tuesday March 8, with
1,307 delegates up for grabs in 20 states and American Samoa,
Dukakis said, ``I don't think any of us is in a strong position. I
think it's wide open.
   ``Super Tuesday is two weeks ahead, and if there is one thing
that we are learning as a result of this (process) is that nobody
knows what's going to happen next,'' he said.
</TEXT>
