<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HowardBeachDriver     02-24 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Howard Beach Driver,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Revokes Howard Beach Driver's License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of the car that struck and killed
Michael Griffith, the black victim in the Howard Beach racial
assault case, had his driver's license revoked Wednesday by the
state Department of Motor Vehicles.
   DMV officials said Dominic Blum's license was suspended
effective March 10. Blum would be eligible to apply to have the
license reinstated after 30 days, said DMV spokesman R. Bryan
Jackson.
   Blum's lawyer, William Breuer, said the order would be appealed.
   Griffith was struck by Blum's car on Dec. 20, 1986, as Griffith
was chased onto a highway by a mob of white youths. Three
teen-agers have been convicted of manslaughter in the case, and
seven other defendants face trial on lesser charges.
   Blum, 26, a court officer in New York City Family Court, left
the scene of the accident and didn't come forward for several hours.
   DMV officials said Blum was guilty of leaving the scene of a
personal injury accident, going 55 miles per hour in a 50 mph zone
and following too closely.
   Breuer said he filed a $20 million libel and slander suit last
week against lawyers C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr., who had
alleged that Blum had intentionally hit Griffith.
