<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDSCommission Bjt   02-24 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Commission, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Watkins Urges $20 Billion, 10-Year Effort To Deal With IV Drug
Users</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a White House commission
recommended Wednesday that federal and local governments spend an
additional $20 billion over the next decade to fight AIDS among
drug abusers.
   Retired Navy Adm. James D. Watkins, head of the AIDS commission
appointed by President Reagan last summer, acknowledged that the
call for such massive spending on drug addicts might prove
controversial.
   But he said 200 hours of testimony from 350 witnesses has left
the panel convinced that the deadly disease is spreading most
rapidly among the nation's estimated 1.3 million intravenous drug
abusers and their sexual partners.
   Watkins noted that some health leaders are estimating 10,000 to
20,000 infants could be infected with the AIDS virus three years
from now as a result of sexual unions involving drug addicts who
can easily spread the disease among themselves by sharing
contaminated needles.
   Any realistic attempt to combat AIDS in general must focus on
drug abusers, he said.
   Health leaders have long feared that any significant outbreak of
AIDS into the general population most likely would start with the
sex partners of IV drug users, most of whom are concentrated in 24
major cities.
   The full 13-member AIDS commission is expected to adopt most or
all of Watkins' recommendations at a day-long business meeting next
Monday and then formally submit them to Reagan the following week
in what will be the panel's first substantive report.
   A final report is due at the White House June 24. Watkins
promised it will get into such controversial areas as widespread
AIDS testing, discrimination against people with AIDS and other
legal and social questions.
   He said the commission would be ``at loggerheads with
ourselves'' if it tried to agree on recommendations on those
matters at this point. The commission will turn specifically to
hearing testimony on those topics next month.
   Meanwhile, he said, the panel saw no reason to delay making
recommendations in areas where there was consensus. There could be
subsequent interim reports before the final one this summer,
Watkins said.
   Watkins' call for an additional $1 billion a year in federal
spending on drug abuse intervention programs alone would nearly
double the total $1.3 billion Public Health Service AIDS budget
Reagan has proposed for fiscal 1989.
   The retired chief of naval operations told reporters that state
and local governments will need to increase their own combined
spending on drug programs by a like amount and that both the
federal and local efforts will need to continue for 10 years.
   ``You cannot just throw in some money one year and drop it out
next year,'' said Watkins.
   He said only 15 percent of the nation's intravenous drug abusers
are in treatment plans and tht there are three- to six-month
waiting lists in most major cities for addicts seeking help in
getting off drugs.
   ``Anyone crying for help should get help on demand,'' Watkins
said.
   Another major theme among Watkins' 60 pages of recommendations
is additional financial support for the Food and Drug
Administration, which he characterized as ``a kind of orphan agency
standing on their own'' in the annual budget fights.
   ``We're picking up his advocacy,'' Watkins said of FDA
Commissioner Frank Young. The chairman said the panel had toured
FDA headquarters in surburban Maryland and concluded ``we look
something like a Third World agency out there.''
   He noted that the new Reagan budget proposes $25 million for an
FDA laboratory. ``We're saying he needs another building'' in
addition to the one proposed, said Watkins.
   Watkins expressed confidence that the full commission would
adopt most of his recommendations and declared, ``It is not in our
charter to worry about the political impact.''
   Asked his reaction to the possibility of presidential
candidates, particularly Democrats, using his recommendations to
``zing the White House'' for not doing more earlier, Watkins
replied:
   ``How do you avoid politicizing something in an election year?
If they all adopt this and say `Let's get on with it,' that's the
kind of politicization I like.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
