<HEAD>Cabinet Opposes Combat Training Flights Over Everglades</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force combat training over
Everglades National Park would spoil the wilderness and threaten
endangered species, the state Cabinet concluded Tuesday.
   Voting unanimously, the Cabinet urged Air Force Secretary Edward
C. Aldridge not to pursue a proposal for low-level, high-speed jet
fighter missions over the national park.
   Park Superintendent Michael Finley agreed with the Cabinet and
said the park already is stressed by South Florida's expanding
population.
   ``To add one more type of stress to Everglades National Park
could be the nail in the coffin,'' said Finley. ``At some point ...
the Everglades will be to South Florida what Central Park is to New
York City.''
   Gov. Bob Martinez was on a trade mission in Europe and did not
participate in the Cabinet vote.
   Lt. Tom Barth, deputy for public affairs at Homestead Air Force
Base, said the training missions still were in the planning stage
and might not be carried out over the park. A second site is being
examined southwest of Lake Okeechobee, north of Alligator Alley.
   The training missions would not use live ammunition or bombs, he
said.
   Air Force officials say the South Florida missions would be
cheaper than continuing to send figters to other bases for combat
training.
   Homestead, once solely a training base, has been converted to an
active fighter base. The base is home to two wings, the 31st and
482nd. In October, it will have three squadrons of F-16s and F-4s.
</TEXT>
