<2ND_LINE>AM-WVa Budget, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0766,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What Crisis? West Virginia Rolls Along</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 10th graf, ``A lawsuit ...'' to restore dropped word
``West.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crisis over an unconstitutional state
budget blew over Wednesday almost as quickly as it developed after
West Virginia officials agreed to continue government as usual
until they hear more from the state Supreme Court.
   The high court issued a 3-2 opinion on Tuesday calling the
budget unconstitutional because it contains a $26 million deficit.
But the court granted a 60-day grace period during which the order
would be suspended while a rehearing is requested.
   Check-writing officials were thrown into a panic initially, with
Treasurer A. James Manchin saying he would not process any more
state bills. But Manchin reversed himself overnight and said
Wednesday he would process the checks as usual.
   He called the high court's ruling a ``whimper in the wind'' and
said it carried enough delays to put off any final action until the
new fiscal year that starts on July 1.
   Manchin released a number of checks for hospital workers on
Wednesday. Manchin's reversal also apparently clears the way for
the state payroll to be distributed on Monday as scheduled.
   Gov. Arch Moore already has scheduled a special session of the
Legislature for April 12 to look at education matters, and the
budget problem presumably could be considered at that time.
   The governor has a possible safety valve. On Tuesday, he
received a bill that would allow him to borrow up to $50 million
from the state's pension and workers' compensation trust fund, said
gubernatorial press secretary John Price.
   If he signs the bill, it might be possible to solve the crisis
by simply dumping $26 million into the current budget.
   Auditor Glen Gainer, who also signs the state's checks, said he
questions whether the loan is legal but said he would not contest
it in court.
   A lawsuit filed last fall by the West Virginia Education
Association challenging $13.5 million in cuts in education this
year sparked the high court decision.
   The unprecedented ruling comes as lawmakers grapple with bills
that Gainer estimates will be $170 million by the June 30 end of
the fiscal year. In addition, lawmakers are trying to write a
budget for the next fiscal year.
   Tax collections are $35.7 million behind predictions this year,
and a national investment firm issued a national bond rating
warning against West Virginia on Dec. 15 because of the financial
crisis facing the state.
   House Finance Chairman George Farley suggested his colleagues
simply ignore the high court decision and continue to work on the
budget for next year.
</TEXT>
