<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BaytownOil     02-24 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baytown Oil,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Town to Seek Oil Under City Hall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYTOWN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Baytown, banking that City
Hall may be sitting on a pool of oil, is looking in its own back
yard for more income.
   The City Council has approved a plan for Trace Oil and Gas to
drill a shallow 5,000-6,000-foot well near the entrance to the
30-acre, wooded City Hall complex. The city would receive a 20
percent royalty on any petroleum uncovered under the agreement.
   ``We're keeping our fingers crossed,'' said Emmett Hutto, mayor
of this town of 57,000 people about 30 miles east of Houston. ``If
the well brings in $100,000 a year, we could knock a half-cent off
our tax rate.''
   Jim Bob Jackson, a geologist and co-owner of Trace Oil in
Houston, projects the company has a 50-50 chance of hitting oil.
   ``We feel confident. We drilled a well 500 feet south of there
on Maryland Avenue last year and got the smell of oil,'' he said.
   After careful calculations, his research indicated an oil pool
could be trapped beside a fault under the lush complex, he said.
   The company has permission to drill about 2,000 feet from the
city buildings. An 80-foot derrick will be erected and the drilling
will continue around the clock for five to six days, Jackson said.
If oil is discovered, a fence will be erected around the site and
landscaping will be used to disguise the oil pumping operations, he
said.
   ``We made stipulations in the lease so that it won't be a messy
operation,'' Hutto said.
   The company will spend about $150,000 on the prospecting venture.
   ``We expect it could bring in anywhere from $500 to $15,000 per
day in revenue, which is a minor find,'' Jackson said.
   The prospect of oil under the building is not outlandish, said
Assistant City Manager Bobby Rountree.
   ``After all, this is an oil town,'' agreed Jackson. ``Exxon, one
of the world's largest refineries, made Baytown what it is today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ScotusRdp Bjt   02-24 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Expands Parody Protections by Rejecting Award to
Falwell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court expanded significantly the
legal protections for parody and satire Wednesday as it overturned
a $200,000 award evangelist Jerry Falwell had won against Hustler
magazine and publisher Larry Flynt.
   The justices ruled unanimously that ``emotional distress''
lawsuits filed by public figures targeted by such spoofs should be
as difficult to win as libel suits.
   And the court unanimously said that even pornographic spoofs
enjoy the free-speech protection of the Constitution's First
Amendment.
   The Hustler material was a phony ad purportedly quoting Falwell
discussing an incestual encounter with his mother in a Virginia
outhouse and his habit of getting drunk before giving sermons.
   Small print at the bottom of the page said the ad was ``not to
be taken seriously.''
   Led by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, the court rejected
Falwell's arguments _ and a federal appeals court's ruling _ that
some parodies are so outrageous they do not deserve legal
protection.
   ``Outrageousness in the area of political and social discourse
has an inherent subjectiveness about it which would allow a jury to
impose liability on the basis of the jurors' tastes or views,''
Rehnquist said, adding that such results are constitutionally
impermissible.
   The decision was praised by news organizations.
   ``It's easy to stand up for nice talk from nice people but the
First Amendment protects all speech, even the outrageous,'' said
Paul McMasters of the Society for Professional Journalists.
   ``Editorial cartoons have been a particular target of lawsuits
lately,'' McMasters said. ``The court was right to speak up so
forcefully on behalf of ... tools editorial cartoonists wield so
well.''
   But Falwell, a Baptist minister and founder of an organization
called the Moral Majority, disagreed. ``No sleaze merchant like
Larry Flynt should be able to use the First Amendment as an excuse
for maliciously and dishonestly attacking public figures,'' he said
after learning of his defeat. ``I'm sure the justices were holding
their noses while making the ruling.''
   Flynt said he was ``absolutely delighted'' by the ruling.
   ``Even though the suit had no merit in the beginning, I still
spent over $1 million in attorney's fees. ... It's what you call
paying to defend the First Amendment,'' Flynt said by telephone
from Los Angeles.
   He said he was concerned about small newspapers and house organs
and others unable to afford to fight such a battle.
   ``They just go out of business,'' Flynt said.
   Rehnquist's opinion drew a distinction between the Hustler ad
and more traditional forms of parody such as editorial cartoons,
calling the Falwell spoof ``a distant cousin of the political
cartoon, and a rather poor relation at that.''
   Following publication of the parody in November 1983 and March
1984, Falwell sued Hustler, a sexually explicit magazine, and its
publisher for $45 million in damages for libel, invasion of privacy
and the intentional infliction of emotional distress. He won on the
emotional-distress allegations only and a federal jury in Roanoke,
Va., awarded him $200,000 in damages in late 1984. The 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the award.
   But the high court said the same tough standard of proof Falwell
faced in trying to prove he was libeled should have applied as well
to his emotional-distress allegations.
   The Supreme Court since 1964 has required that free-speech
considerations be taken into account in libel cases. But those
considerations never before have been required in
emotional-distress cases.
   In order to win a libel suit, a public figure must prove that
the allegedly libelous statement was false and was made with
``actual malice'' _ knowledge or reckless disregard of its falsity.
   Until Wednesday, winning an emotional-distress suit was easier
for public figures. They only had to prove that the defendant
intended to cause the distress, that the defendant's conduct was
extreme and that emotional distress actually was suffered.
   Now, if public figures sue over some spoof _ whether alleging
libel or emotional distress _ they must meet the actual-malice
standard of proof. And in proving falsity, they must show that the
spoof reasonably could have been interpreted as stating actual
facts.
   The court's vote was 8-0. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who joined
the court Thursday, did not participate in the decision.
   In other decisions, the court:
   _Expanded by a 6-2 vote the power of communities to impose rent
controls, ruling in a case from San Jose, Calif., that tenant
hardships may be considered when regulating the increases sought by
landlords.
   _Ruled unanimously in an Arkansas case that federal judges may
not order the government to pay fees to lawyers who successfully
obtain overdue federal welfare benefits for the aged, blind or
disabled.
   _Made it a bit easier for prosecutors to talk to criminal trial
juries about a defendant's failure to testify as it reinstated a
man's Tennessee mail fraud conviction.
   _Broadened protections for criminal defendants who claim they
were enticed by law enforcement officials into committing a crime
by overturning, 6-2, on entrapment grounds a Milwaukee man's
bribery conviction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
