<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperTuesday-TV     02-24 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Tuesday-TV,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Networks Scaling Down Super Tuesday Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the networks have decided that the Super
Tuesday primary is so unlikely to produce a clear winner in the
presidential nominating races that they are cutting back on their
planned prime-time coverage.
   CBS had planned to pre-empt its entire prime-time schedule for
Super Tuesday coverage on March 8, but decided Tuesday to cut back
to two hours. NBC, which had planned a two-hour special, cut it to
one hour.
   ``The reasoning is that after Iowa and New Hampshire, we
determined that Super Tuesday was not going to be as conclusive as
previously thought,'' said NBC News spokesman Bill McAndrew. ``In
planning coverage, we protectively booked two hours and decided we
could cover it comprehensively in one.''
   Gene F. Jankowski, president of the CBS Broadcast Group, said
the network decided the public wasn't interested enough in the
primary results to spend more than two hours.
   ``What we did was took a look at the public's attitude in Iowa,
what the public's reaction to the coverage in New Hampshire was and
did a reevaluation of what the reaction was going to be to the
primaries that take place on March 8 and said to ourselves, from an
editorial point of view and journalistic point of view, can we
really fill three hours in a meaningful way that the audience would
want to watch?'' he said.
   ABC was sticking to its plan to have two hours of coverage,
despite the fact that Tuesday is its highest-rated night of
prime-time programming. CNN will have comprehensive coverage
throughout the evening, beginning at 6 p.m. EST.
   On PBS, ``The MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour'' will wait until
Wednesday to assess the results.
   ``Because we're not stupid, we're going to avoid projecting or
predicting what may happen,'' said associate editor Jim Lehrer.
``It is so diverse and diffused down there, who knows what all of
these many, many results are going to add up to when it's all said
and done.''
   This is the first year for Super Tuesday, when 20 states, most
of them in the South, will select delegates to the two presidential
nominating conventions. Coverage of the event, stretching from
Massachusetts to American Samoa, has confounded the networks, who
are additionally hampered by budget cutbacks in the news divisions.
   Before the presidential campaign began, the networks believed
Super Tuesday would likely clinch the race in one or both parties.
But after the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary failed to
produce clear frontrunners, the networks decided Super Tuesday was
less likely to be decisive.
   ``The networks are backing and filling. They're less sure than
they were that we'll actually know who the nominee will be,'' said
ABC correspondent Jeff Greenfield. ``You have to assume at present
it's going to be an extremely diffuse result. We may come out of
this not knowing a thing.''
</TEXT>
