<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lamm Predicts Next President Will Face Sick Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Colorado Gov. Richard Lamm says the next
president of the United States could end up in history books like
Herbert Hoover, who was the nation's leader during the Great
Depression.
   ``I think there is a four-out-of-10 chance that it's 1929 over
again,'' Lamm said Tuesday in an address to journalism students at
the University of Denver.
   Lamm, who practices law, also teaches at the university.
   ``I think there is a six-out-of-10 chance that it's a very
severe recession that's going to cause lots of trouble,'' he said.
   Lamm said he's not sure if any of the current presidential
candidates are willing to take the tough steps he thinks are needed
to deal with the nation's economic problems, including massive
cutbacks in the federal budget.
   He was asked by one student if he ever considered himself
presidential timber.
   ``Would I like to run for president of the United States?'' Lamm
said. ``I not only would not like to run for president of the
United States, but if the good fairy godmother would come down
tomorrow and offer me the presidency of the United States for the
next four years, I would say `no.'''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Kids to Make Their Presidential Choice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairmen of both major political parties
are supporting a National Student-Parent Mock Election scheduled
for Nov. 3, five days before the real election that will determine
the next president.
   Two million students and parents took part in the 1984 mock
election, picking President Reagan as did the general electorate.
   The organizers, based in Tucson, Ariz., have the support of 46
national civic, religious and educational organizations, and former
presidents Ford and Carter are honorary chairmen.
   Both Frank J. Fahrenkopf, Jr., chairman of the Republican
National Committee, and Paul Kirk, chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, joined in a statement urging educators to
support the mock election.
   It is open to students of all ages, from kindergarten through
college. Participants will meet at local, state and national
``election headquarters'' on the Thursday before Election Day to
cast votes for federal offices and to make recommendations on key
national issues.
   The party chairmen said it was one way to help overcome youth
apathy about voting.
   Four out of five eligible voters under age 30 never bothered to
go to the polls in the last election, Kirk said.
</TEXT>
