<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     02-24 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Says Washington Has Sold Out Afghan Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moslem guerrilla leader said
Wednesday that the United States has struck a secret deal with
Moscow to betray the insurgents fighting to overthrow Afghanistan's
Soviet-backed government.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, head of the extremist Islamic Party
guerrilla group, reiterated his vow to keep fighting in Afghanistan
until peace is forged on the insurgents' terms.
   Speaking to reporters and diplomats, he said evidence of
Washington's alleged betrayal was its acceptance of Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's offer to begin removing Red Army troops from
Afghanistan on May 15 if a U.N.-sponsored peace accord is signed
next month.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979, and by
Western estimates 115,000 are still there.
   Hekmatyar said the Soviet pullout would leave the country in the
hands of the communist Kabul government, making it impossible for
the nearly 5 million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and Iran to return
home.
   ``I don't think Gorbachev (made the offer) without making a deal
with the Americans,'' he said.
   Pakistan recently has insisted that any U.N. accord on foreign
intervention in the Afghan conflict include an agreement that an
interim government would be installed in Kabul during the
withdrawal.
   Asked why he thought the United States would betray the
guerrillas after supporting them throughout the war, Hekmatyar
said, ``That's an impertinent question.''
   Asked whether his group would continue to accept U.S. military
aid, he said, ``Nobody can buy us or sell us out.''
   The Mujahedeen Alliance, comprising the seven political factions
of the insurgents, this week announced its own blueprint for a
government to replace the Soviet-backed one in Kabul.
   It envisons a joint executive committee composed of all seven
guerrilla leaders to preside over a 28-member cabinet composed of
mujahedeen, Afghan refugees and ``Moslems presently living in
Kabul.''
   The plan says the head of the cabinet would also be head of
state but it did not suggest who would have that post.
   Hekmatyar's said that if Pakistan, the mujahedeen's
headquarters, signed a U.N. accord without the guerrillas'
approval, they might change their external operating base to Iran.
   The next round of peace talks is scheduled to begin March 2 in
Geneva. Islamabad, the capital of Pakistan, and Kabul have been the
principal negotiators in the talks.
   Pakistan has indicated it might not sign any agreement until a
new government is installed in Kabul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
