<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Exports     02-24 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Exports,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Dollar Decline Has Opened Opportunities for US
Exporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday the decline in
the value of the dollar has opened opportunities for U.S. exporters
but they could be undermined by protectionist legislation being
considered in Congress.
   ``The fact that the dollar's exchange rate is at a far more
realistic level is of great significance'' to the market for U.S.
exports, the president told members of Export Now, a public-private
group organized by the Commmerce Department.
   ``New opportunities are emerging because of the adjustment in
the value of the dollar,'' he said. ``At the current exchange rates
many American companies can now quote a lower price to customers in
Hamburg, Antwerp or Osaka than their competitors and still make a
higher profit than on sales in the domestic market.''
   In addition, he said, ``In the last few years, American industry
has been going through an unprecedented period of renovation,
computerization and modernization.''
   ``What we don't need now, however, is protectionisn that
undermines all the progress we've made,'' the president said.
   ``I strongly urge Congress to send me a trade bill that does not
imperil our ability to export by causing other countries to close
their markets,'' he said. ``We shouldn't shoot ourselves in the
foot after we have worked so hard and are in a position to win the
race.''
   The president said legislation being considered by a
House-Senate conference committee contains provisions that
encourage exports ``and we don't want to lose those.''
   But he said other provisions would violate the General Agreement
on Trade and Tariffs and make U.S. business less competitive.
   ``We ask for your support to ensure that we don't end up with an
economy-killing, protectionist bill,'' Reagan told the group.
   Secretary of Commerce William Verity introduced Reagan, saying
he was to ``make introductory remarks and wave the flag.''
   Verity said the president had told him ``in no uncertain terms''
that the Comemrce Department would lead an effort to expand sale of
U.S. goods overseas. The commerce secretary said there ``has been a
tremendous improvement in the climate for exporting.'' He
attributed that to an exchange rate that favors the United States
and to an administration in Washington ``that cares and would like
to do more'' to stimulate U.S. sales abroad.
</TEXT>
