<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1525EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Filibuster 1stLd-Writethru a0759 02-24 1096</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Filibuster, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,1,020</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Outraged After Sen. Packwood Arrested and Hauled Onto Senate
Floor</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 9-11, bgng: ``I rather, with Packwood
comments; SUBS pvs 3rd graf, bgng: It was, to CORRECT times; SUBS
pvs 4th graf, bgng: Giugni found, to CORRECT precedent; SUBS pvs
19th graf, bgng: Democrats and, to CORRECT to 52 co-sponsors sted
56; adds 2 grafs to give arrest precedent</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans angrily complained of ``banana
republic'' tactics Wednesday after armed Capitol police broke into
GOP Sen. Bob Packwood's locked office, arrested him and hauled him
feet-first into the Senate chamber during an all-night filibuster
over Democratic campaign finance legislation.
   On a motion by Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
Sergeant at Arms Henry K. Giugni was handed warrants for the arrest
of absent Republican senators, thus forcing them to answer a quorum
call and keep the filibuster alive.
   It was after midnight, more than 10 hours after the filibuster
began, when Giugni and five armed plainclothes Capitol policemen
began stalking Senate hideaways and senators' suites in nearby
office buildings.
   Giugni found several senators' offices empty but saw Sen. Steve
Symms, R-Idaho, running down a hallway to escape arrest. Then in an
extraordinary incident that the Senate historian said had not
occurred since 1942, Giugni used a passkey to unlock Packwood's
office door.
   Bob Witeck, a spokesman for the Oregon Republican, said Packwood
resisted and somehow jammed a finger he had broken two weeks ago in
a fall. ``He tried to hold the door closed with his shoulder, but
they were able to push it open,'' Witeck said.
   ``I had to shove in the door to get into his office,'' said
Giugni, a stocky Army veteran of World War II and former vice squad
policeman in Honolulu. ``I think he hurt his finger. He was very
courteous.''
   Packwood walked with Giugni and his police escort a block or so
from the Russell Senate Office Building to the Senate wing of the
Capitol but refused to ``walk on the floor willingly,'' Witeck said.
   At that point, three policemen grabbed Packwood by his ankles
and both arms and carried him bodily into the Senate chamber, feet
first. Packwood later went to a hospital, where X-rays showed that
his left hand _ enclosed in a cast _ had not been reinjured during
the scuffle with Giugni.
   ``I rather enjoyed it,'' Packwood told reporters later. ``I
instructed four of my staff to bring a sedan chair. But except for
the honor of it, I'd rather walk.''
   Packwood said he bolt-locked his main office door after his
staff reported that Giugni would try to arrest him.
   The senator said ``it sounded like a battering ram'' at the
door, with his shoulder pushing from inside against three shoulders
on the other side. ``Their mass beat my mass,'' Packwood said,
adding that he suffered only swollen knuckles.
   Giugni served the arrest warrant signed by the presiding
officer, Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., after 1 a.m.
   On a more serious note, Packwood said the campaign spending bill
has no chance of becoming law, because Senate Republicans have more
than enough votes to sustain a certain veto by President Reagan,
and that Byrd succeeded only in alienating his GOP colleagues.
   Packwood's arrest provoked angry clashes between Democrats and
Republicans. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said the incident brought
to mind the police-state measures of ``Nazi Germany and communist
Russia.'' He protested that Packwood was hustled into the Senate
chamber like a ``common criminal.''
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, complained of ``banana republic''
tactics, and said Packwood's arrest ``flaunted the Constitution of
the United States.'' He proposed a change in the Senate rules to
forbid any future arrest of absentee senators.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., responded that Republican senators had
engaged in a ``shameful display'' of fleeing the chamber to avoid a
quorum call, requiring Giugni to search them down like a
``headmaster chasing schoolchildren.''
   ``Senators went off in a dead sprint,'' said Sen. Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark. ``They should have been in Calgary in one of the Olympic
events.''
   The incident was prompted by a walkout by Republican senators
from the filibuster that they had started in opposition to the
Democratic proposal to impose voluntary spending limits in general
election campaigns for the Senate.
   The Republicans charge that the bill was a Democratic attempt to
discriminate against them in states with a heavy Democratic edge in
registered voters. They began a filibuster early Tuesday afternoon
to prevent the Democratic majority from bringing the bill to a
floor vote they are virtually certain to win.
   But when the GOP senators failed to answer repeated quorum calls
requiring the presence of a majority of no fewer than 51 senators,
Byrd invoked a parliamentary rule that requires every senator to
attend floor sessions unless excused. After a series of roll calls
failed to lure Republicans back to the floor, Byrd moved to have
the sergeant at arms arrest the absentees and escort them to the
chamber.
   His motion was approved, 45-3, with dissenting votes cast by
Democrats Howell Heflin and Richard Shelby of Alabama and Dennis
DeConcini of Arizona. The arrest warrants were signed by Adams, who
was presiding over the Senate at the time.
   Byrd said later he had no choice but to resort to the arrest
tactic because only 50 senators _ one short of a majority _ had
answered the last quorum call and three Democrats were unavoidably
absent. He appealed for an end to the Republicans' ``guerrilla
warfare'' against the bill.
   The Senate rules provide that the sergeant at arms can be
ordered to ``request'' or ``compel'' the attendance of absentees.
If that doesn't work, the Senate can ``direct the sergeant at arms
or his deputies to arrest absent senators and bring them to the bar
of the Senate.''
   Democrats and Republicans have been at loggerheads for nearly a
year over the Democratic proposal, which has 52 co-sponsors, to
impose voluntary Senate campaign spending limits of $950,000 to
$5.5 million, depending on a state's population.
   Under the bill, a candidate who observes the voluntary spending
limit would get campaign funds from the Treasury if an opponent
exceeded the limit or an independent group spent large amounts of
money in opposition.
   Senate historian Richard Baker said the last time something
similar to the Packwood incident ocurred was on Nov. 23, 1942, when
a deputy sergeant at arms carried a subpoena to the Mayflower Hotel
and escorted Sen. Kenneth McKellar, D-Tenn., to the Senate floor
for a vote on poll tax legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
