<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HoaxIndictment     02-24 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hoax Indictment,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Faking Plane Crash Indicted By Feds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly made a false report
that he was in the wreckage of a plane crash was indicted on a
federal charge Wednesday.
   U.S. Attorney Richard Wiebusch said Mark Blair, 29, would face
up to five years in prison and a fine if convicted on the charge of
making a false statement to a federal government agency.
   Blair is accused of talking by radio for four hours with an
airborne Navy plane on Jan. 8, saying that he was aboard a small
jet that crashed near Meredith, killing one and injuring three. The
Navy plane also detected intermittent beeping from an emergency
locator transmitter.
   Officials said as many as 100 people, 15 planes, five
helicopters, six police agencies, a snowmobile club and search dogs
joined in the search for the aircraft. Harold Buker, state
aeronautics director, said the search may have cost as much as
$50,000.
   Blair, who was arrested Blair at his apartment four days after
the hoax, already faces a state misdemeanor charge.
</TEXT>
