<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TaxReturns     02-24 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Returns,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filing Tax Forms Through Computers Speeds Returns, IRS Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 1 million taxpayers will receive federal
refunds as much as three weeks earlier this year by having a
professional file their tax returns directly into the IRS computer.
   Already this year, 119,494 returns have been filed
electronically _ compared with 77,612 for the entire filing season
in 1987. If the taxpayers choose, their refunds will be deposited
directly into their bank account.
   Although the number of electronic returns are up considerably
this year, the volume of ordinary, paper returns filed so far is
6.7 percent below last year's pace. However, the gap _ which
officials blame partially on the new tax law _ is closing each week.
   Through Feb. 19, the Internal Revenue Service said Wednesday,
23.55 million returns had been filed, compared with 25.24 million a
year ago. The IRS has processed 9.74 million of this year's
returns, up slightly from 9.72 million last year.
   The inventory of unprocessed return totaled 13.8 million last
week, compared with 15.5 million a year ago.
   The number of returns qualifying for refunds is down 14.4
percent, a decline that IRS officials cannot explain. Through last
week, 3.8 million refunds had been certified; the figure was almost
4.5 million at this time last year.
   The average refund is bigger this year: $782 compared with $727.
By the time all 107 million individual returns are filed this year,
the IRS estimates, nearly 80 percent will qualify for refunds
averaging about $1,000.
   It is taking the IRS about five weeks to process a return and
certify a refund check this year. But those taxpayers who file
electronically are getting refunds within two or three weeks.
   This is the third year of electronic filing, and within three or
four more years, says Richard F. Moran, who manages the project,
about 35 million returns will be filed annually by computer.
   Electronic returns save the IRS considerable time, said Moran,
and these returns generally have fewer errors that would delay a
refund. The IRS estimates electronic filing could save $200 million
in processing and storage costs over the next 10 years.
   And if a taxpayer who files electronically chooses to have the
refund deposited directly into a bank account, that saves the
treasury 23 cents that would have been spent to issue and mail a
paper check.
   So far, electronic filing is available only to taxpayers in 10
states and parts of four others who are due refunds and who pay any
of about 2,000 professional preparers to fill out their returns.
Although the preparer sends the completed return directly into the
IRS computer by telephone line, the taxpayer must sign a signature
form which is mailed to the IRS.
   Electronic filing is avaible in Alabama, Arizona, Indiana,
Kentucky, Nebraska, North Carolina, Utah, Virginia, Washington and
Wisconsin and in the Albany and Buffalo areas of New York, the
Sacramento and San Jose areas of California and the Cincinnati and
Dallas areas.
   All electronic returns are processed to IRS centers in Ogden,
Utah, or Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
