<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ComaExperiment     02-24 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coma Experiment,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boss Says Doctor Experimented on Comatose Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anesthesiologist performed experiments on a
comatose patient, his superior said Wednesday after France's health
minister suspended the doctor for experiments on another comatose
patient.
   On Tuesday, a professor of medicine testified in a criminal
trial in the western city of Poitiers that a doctor he did not
identify had placed a deeply comatose patient, considered legally
dead, on sabotaged medical equipoment.
   Professor Jean Lassner said the experiment was carried out to
see if the effects were the same in the case on trial, in which a
young woman died, possibly from medical sabotage.
   Maurice Peria, director of the Regional Hospital Center of
Amiens, said Wednesday that the experiment was carried out by Dr.
Alain Milhaud on 24-year-old man who had been in a deep coma since
late January. He said the man's family had been notified and the
patient survived the experiment.
   ``The experiment was videotaped and sent to Dr. Lassner so he
could use it at the trial,'' Peria said. He said Milhaud proceeded
without the consent of the hospital.
   Lassner gave his testimony in the trial of three doctors charged
in the 1984 death of Nicole Berneron after her operation for a
benign tumor at Jean Bernard Hospital in Poitiers.
   Mrs. Berneron, then 33 and the mother of two children,
apparently received nitrous oxide instead of oxygen after the
operation and died of asphyxiation. An investigation showed that
the tubes had been switched.
   Milhaud was condemned by the medical community after he admitted
experimenting in 1985 on a 20-year-old comatose man.
   Health Minister Michele Barzach on Wednesday ordered Milhaud
suspended from his duties in Amiens, north of Paris, and asked the
state prosecutor to investigate to find out who had carried out the
latest experiment.
   The minister, a doctor, said she was ``indignant and revolted
that in this country one can carry out experiments on humans,
obviously without their consent, given their state.''
   In comments during the 1985 controversy, Milhaud called patients
in a prolonged, chronic vegetative state ``almost perfect human
models, who constitute intermediaries between animal and man.''
   In the 1985 experiment, he injected in two minutes a quart of
blood into the patient's bone marrow to try to show this was a
viable treatment for patients in shock. The man, comatose for three
years, died within months but no link between the experiment and
the death was established.
   President Francois Mitterrand condemned human experimentation.
   ``Human beings are not instruments,'' he said. ``Neither the
search for truth nor scientific progress must distance us from this
certitude, this value of civilization.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
