<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Senate-ArrestWarrant     02-24 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Arrest Warrant,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sergeant-at-Arms Knew What He Had To Do _ and Did It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Filibuster Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrest warrant used by the Senate to bring
Sen. Bob Packwood to the floor early Wednesday left no question
about what Sergeant-at-Arms Henry Giugni had to do.
   ``I had to take him in. I knew he was not going under his own
power,'' Giugni told reporters.
   The warrants given to Giugni listed missing Republican senators
individually by name:
   ``To Henry K. Giugni, Sergeant-at-Arms, United States Senate:
   The undersigned, presiding officer of the Senate, by virtue of
the power vested in me, hereby command you in pursuance of the
order of the Senate, this day made, to forthwith arrest and take
into custody and bring to the bar of the Senate, Bob Packwood, who
is absent without leave.
   Hereof fail not and make due return of this warrant.''
   The order was signed by the presiding officer, who at the time
was Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash.
   Packwood, R-Ore., was physically carried onto the floor after
Giugni and five detectives shoved their way into his office.
   Packwood later quipped to reporters, ``Real men don't get
arrested by Brock Adams.''
</TEXT>
