<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2116EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Glance     02-24 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Glance,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Differences Between Peres, Shamir</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the major differences between
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres on
peacemaking strategy and the plan by U.S. Secretary of State George
Shultz:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE _ Peres has agreed to Jordan's demand
that the five permament members of the U.N. Security Council meet
to start peace talks.
   Shamir opposes the idea, arguing such a forum would be weighted
against Israel and would give the Soviet Union too much of a say.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LAND-FOR-PEACE _ Peres favors territorial compromise, returning
some of the land captured in the 1967 Middle East war for peace
agreements with Jordan, Syria and other Arab states.
   Shamir says he is willing to negotiate the territorial issue,
but he will not pledge in advance that Israel will return any land.
His party views the West Bank and Gaza Strip as essential to
Israel's security.
   Both leaders agree to giving Palestinians some form of autonomy
as a temporary solution in the occupied lands.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SHULTZ PLAN _ Shamir has expressed reservations, especially over
U.S. proposals to start talks by the end of the year on a final
disposition of the occupied lands. He insists the five-year interim
period called for in the Camp David Accords is needed to build
trust between the Palestinians and Israelis.
   Peres has not objected to any elements publicly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOVIET INVOLVEMENT _ Peres has argued the Soviets are already
involved in the region. He conditions Soviet participation on a
significant change in the number of Jews allowed to come to Israel.
He has placed less emphasis on a demand for full diplomatic
relations.
   Shamir opposes any opening that will increase Soviet influence
and has insisted on full diplomatic relations and free emigration
for Soviet Jews as conditions for any Soviet role.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PLO _ Peres leaves open the possibility of talking to PLO
chairman Yasser Arafat if the Palestine Liberation Organization
ends all forms of violence against Israel and accepts the right of
the Jewish state to exist.
   Shamir rules out any dealings with PLO leaders.
</TEXT>
