<DOCNO> AP880224-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MatchingFunds     02-24 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Matching Funds,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Gore, Hart Could Lose Matching Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Democratic presidential candidates could
lose future federal matching funds based on poor showings in the
South Dakota primary but they have 30 days to turn that around
before the money is cut off.
   Democrats Jesse Jackson, Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and
former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart became ineligible for matching funds
by attaining less than 10 percent of the vote in two successive
primaries _ South Dakota on Tuesday and New Hampshire a week
earlier.
   But election law stays the actual cut-off of money for 30 days
after the second primary, giving the candidates a chance to
re-establish their matching fund status by doing better in a
subsequent primary.
   During the 30 days, the candidates can continue to receive
federal matching funds for every contribution of $250 or less that
they raise privately.
   ``There is absolutely no harm done to the campaign by this,''
said Gore spokesman Paul Risley. He added that Gore, by focusing
his campaign on the South, had never expected to do well in New
Hampshire or South Dakota but anticipated better results before the
30-day period ended.
   The candidates can regain eligibility by achieving a 20 percent
or better showing in a successive primary.
   That means they have a chance to redeem themselves on March 8
when the Super Tuesday series of 20 primaries occurs. Most of the
states are in the South, where both Jackson and Gore have strong
support.
   Jackson's campaign manager, Gerald Austin, said he anticipates
no problem in keeping matching-fund eligibility. He said that since
Jackson's respectable showing in Iowa's caucuses on Feb. 8, when he
came in fourth, the campaign has raised $400,000.
   Hart's possibilities are weaker. His campaign organization is
tiny and he raised only $70,000 during January.
   The matching money is distributed from an U.S. Treasury account
that is supported by the voluntary $1 checkoff on individual income
tax forms.
   GOP contender Pat Robertson dropped below the 10 percent
threshhold in New Hampshire, but he redeemed himself with a 20
percent showing in South Dakota.
   To be declared eligible initially by the FEC, a candidate must
raise $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
