<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People-PrinceCharles     02-24 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Prince Charles,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prince Charles Bans Aerosols From Household</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles said Tuesday he has banned the use
of aerosols in his household because of concern that they damage
the environment, and so far the only problem has been finding an
alternative to hair spray.
   Aerosols contain chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) which float into the
stratosphere and attack the ozone layer, a 20-mile-deep belt of
protective gas around the Earth.
   ``We are always told that it is not scientifically proved,''
Charles said.
   ``But I, personally, as I have become older and more autocratic,
have banned the use of aerosols in my household.''
   In a light-hearted reference to his wife, Princess Diana, the
39-year-old heir to the British throne added:
   ``Trouble still remains with finding adequate and good enough
alternatives to hair spray _ as I am sure all husbands here will
find.''
   He spoke to representatives of businesses which won awards for
improving the environment under a program organized by the Royal
Society of Arts.
   He said the award-winners had found solutions to environmental
problems, ``so if anybody can come up with a really good answer, an
alternative to hair sprays, then for God's sake do so and I will
come and give the award next year.''
   The environmental group Friends of the Earth welcomed the
prince's action, but said he did not have to ban sprays completely
from his household.
   ``There are environmentally safe alternatives for every single
kind of spray, including hair spray,'' said Charles Secrett, a
spokesman for the group.
   Holes in the ozone layer allow the sun's ultraviolet rays to
reach the Earth, causing skin cancer and threatening to damage
crops and alter weather patterns.
</TEXT>
