<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Chase     02-24 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Chase,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Hears Case Stemming From Police Pursuit In Detroit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court was told Wednesday that
police should be allowed to pursue someone who starts running at
the sight of them without having any other reason to suspect a
crime has been committed.
   ``The alternative is for the police to shrug their shoulders and
let a crime occur,'' said Andrea L. Solak, an assistant state
prosecutor from Detroit.
   But Carole M. Stanyar, representing a man who started running
when he spotted a police cruiser on a Detroit street, said,
``People run from the police for a variety of reasons.'' She said
some people fear harassment, that they will be falsely accused of a
crime or ``they may not like the police.''
   The justices, hearing arguments in a case that could expand
police power to stop people on the street, reacted skeptically to
Ms. Stanyar's assrtions.
   ``Don't you think sound law enforcement would want (the police)
to see what's up?'' asked Justice Antonin Scalia.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall suggested that Ms. Stanyar's client,
Michael Mose Chesternut, initiated the chase. ``Could it be he had
a guilty conscience?'' Marshall said.
   Michigan authorities are seeking to reinstate as evidence drugs
dropped by Chesternut, who was standing on a Detroit street corner
talking to another man a little after midnight on Dec. 19, 1984,
when he saw the cruiser.
   Police said Chesternut immediately started running away and they
followed him in the car. After turning a corner and as the cruiser
drew alongside of him, Chesternut threw a number of packets to the
ground and then stopped.
   The officers said they picked up the packets, which appeared to
contain narcotics, and they then arrested Chesternut. He was
charged with possessing heroin, codeine and diazapan.
   A judge in Detroit threw the case out on grounds police lacked a
reasonable suspicion to pursue Chesternut and therefore seized the
evidence unlawfully.
   Michigan law enforcement officials said the judge may have
dismissed the case out of a concern for innocent joggers.
   Mrs. Solak argued Wednesday that the show of police authority
which apparently prompted Chesternut to drop the packets and stop
did not amount to an illegal search and seizure barred by the
Constitution's Fourth Amendment.
   She also said that when Chesternut dropped the packets he
abandoned any right of privacy he had to protect them from a police
search.
   Ms. Stanyar countered that Chesternut reasonably believed he was
being seized when police chased him and acted in ``an aggressive
and confrontational'' manner.
   ``Under the circumstances, a reasonable person would feel he was
not free to leave,'' she said. He was prevented from asserting
``his right to go on his way,'' she said.
   The Supreme Court previously has held that police must have a
reasonable suspicion of wrongdoing before stopping and questioning
someone in a public place. The court also has said police must have
more specific probable cause to believe a crime has been committed
when arresting or detaining someone.
   A ruling in the case argued Wednesday is expected by July.
   The case is Michigan vs. Chesternut, 86-1824.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
