<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     02-24 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Disappointed But Not Surprised By Showing In S.D., Minn.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, saying ``you
can't win them all,'' said Wednesday he was disappointed but not
surprised by finishing third in South Dakota's Republican
presidential primary and fourth in Minnesota's GOP caucuses.
   ``I think the result was somewhat anticipated,'' he told
reporters, but ``you can't go everywhere.''
   In South Dakota on Tuesday, Bush finished behind Sen. Bob Dole
of Kansas and Pat Robertson, while Bush trailed Dole, Robertson and
Rep. Jack Kemp of New York in Minnesota.
   Bush won the New Hampshire primary Feb. 16 after coming in third
in Iowa's GOP caucuses Feb. 8 behind Dole and Robertson.
   ``We've done well out there,'' Bush said. ``We've won in
Michigan (at the convention Jan. 29-30) and in Nevada (in a
non-binding straw poll at caucuses Feb. 18). So you can't win them
all,'' he added.
   Bush is favored in Maine's Republican town caucuses this
weekend. Bush said that ``I think we have to do our best. The same
is true for all these Southern states'' in the March 8 Super
Tuesday balloting, which also includes primaries in Massachusetts
and Rhode Island.
   State Sen. Pamela Cahill, a leader of Dole's Maine campaign,
said he is ``still optimistic'' but she did not expect him to win;
instead, she said, at best, Dole will finish second or third in
Maine.
   Meanwhile, in Burlington, Vt., on Wednesday, Bush asked
Robertson to apologize or provide proof for suggestions that
political motivations were behind the timing of reports of sexual
misconduct by television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   Robertson, a former TV evangelist, provided no evidence to
support his accusation on the timing, and declined to say who might
be behind any such effort. But he claimed Bush's campaign was the
only one in the GOP engaging in ``dirty tricks.'' Robertson said it
was odd that Swaggart's tearful confession of sin came just two
weeks before Super Tuesday.
   ``By sundown in the old South, I'd like to see him stand up like
a Southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' Bush said. ``I'd
like to see an apology or proof.''
   Bush was in Vermont to meet with supporters, and shook hands
with about 100 backers at Burlington airport. He said he was
looking for a victory in Vermont, which holds a non-binding
presidential primary next Tuesday.
   Asked whether he would support a regional approach to federal
dairy policy, a key issue in Vermont, Bush said he has not taken a
firm stand on the matter.
</TEXT>
