<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Whale     02-24 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Whale,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Seamen Free Whale Trapped in Fishing Nets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors from an American guided-missile
cruiser risked their lives in a three-hour operation to free a
30-ton sperm whale tangled in fishing nets in the Arabian Sea, U.S.
officials said Tuesday.
   At one point, Lt.j.g. James M. Syvertsen of Wading River, N.Y.,
rode the back of the 40-foot mammal like ``something out of a
rodeo'' while cutting the nylon cords, according to a Navy news
release issued in Manama.
   He was one of four divers who went into the water to cut the
nets loose in the dangerous operation Sunday.
   In the end, the female whale was freed and swam off, with one
last piece of line dangling ``like dental floss'' between its
teeth, according to Capt. Clinton J. Coneway, skipper of the
cruiser Truxtun..
   ``Through the ordeal the whale made no attempts to harm the
swimmers. It seemed that she knew they were trying to help,'' said
Coneway. ``All in all it was a most unusual and rewarding way to
spend a Sunday afternoon. Jacques Cousteau would be proud.''
   The rescue occurred after crewmen aboard a helicopter from the
nuclear-powered carrier Enterprise spotted the whale floating
listlessly. The helicopter was on a routine patrol and the crew
dropped smoke flares to mark the spot for the Truxtun, which was 30
miles away.
   The two ships are part of a U.S. battle group that arrived in
the Arabian Sea earlier this month to support naval operations in
the Persian Gulf.
   The helicopter crewmen said they thought the whale was dead
until they ``saw water spouting from its blowhole,'' according to
Petty Officer James Cox, a rescue specialist aboard the helicopter.
   Rear Adm. Guy Zeller, commander of the Enterprise's escort
group, ordered the Truxtun to the scene.
   Its crew used grappling hooks to snag the net and pull the tired
animal next to the ship where they worked to remove the net. The
Navy said the nylon net was a type used by fishermen in the area,
but it was ``of unknown orgin.''
   Curtis Michitsch of Reno, Nev., was lowered in a sling to cut
the nets.
   When he became exhausted, he was replaced by Seaman Gerald
Samples of Wilbur, Neb.
   Although they appeared to have nearly freed the whale, which
swam a short distance away, Coneway said he feared the animal still
might not survive because of the the remaining nets and he
dispatched a whaleboat to overtake it.
   Syvertsen, one of two volunteers, became entangled in the net
for about 15 minutes, and finally was relieved by Seaman Adam
Webber, a rescue swimmer from Portland, Maine, who finished the
task.
   Coneway said he doubted at first his sailors would be able to
free the whale from the ``tangled mess,'' but ``I completely
underestimated the ingenuity, perseverance and courage of Truxtun's
swimmers and deck force.''
</TEXT>
