<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bulgaria-Turkey     02-24 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bulgaria-Turkey,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bulgaria, Turkey Sign Protocol On Good Neighborly Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria and Turkey signed a
protocol on good neighborly relations Tuesday in an apparent effort
to resolve their bitter dispute over Bulgaria's estimated 1 million
ethnic Turks.
   The text of the protocol, as released by the Yugoslav state news
agency Tanjug, was a clear indication that the two feuding
neighbors are determined to normalize relations after years of
discord.
   The signing averted a clash between the two countries at the
Balkan foreign ministers' meeting opening here Wednesday.
   Earlier, sources said the Turkish delegation was planning to
raise the issue of the ethnic Turks, who were forced by Bulgarian
authorities to adopt Bulgarian names. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The ``Bulgarization campaign'' began in 1984 and reportedly led
to violent clashes between the Turkish population and Bulgarian
police. It was first reported by Turkish newspapers and was later
confirmed by Western diplomats and Amnesty International.
   Foreign ministers Peter Mladenov of Bulgaria and Mesut Yilmaz of
Turkey signed the protocol at a meeting in a Belgrade hotel, said
Tanjug.
   Mladenov and Yilmaz arrived in Belgrade on Tuesday for the first
meeting of foreign ministers from six Balkan countries. The other
participants come from Albania, Greece, Romania and Yugoslavia.
   Neither the protocol nor the two ministers in news statements
mentioned Bulgaria's Turkish minority, whose existence has so far
not been acknowledged by Bulgarian officials in public.
   ``The protocol we have just signed does not solve the problems,
but I am convinced that it will serve as a sound basis for seeking
positive solutions to the existing problems,'' Mladenov was quoted
as saying.
   Tanjug quoted Yilmaz as saying the protocol ``makes it possible
for us to develop and settle a number of issues of our bilateral
relations.''
   The protocol, as reported by Tanjug, provides for a joint
working group ``with a view to finding a solution to the existing
problems in bilateral relations, the area of humanitarian
cooperation included.''
   It said, ``Another high-level working group shall be established
to determine specific measures to speed up cooperation ... in the
field of economics, trade, tourism, technology, transport,
communications and culture.''
   Under the protocol, the two countries' foreign ministers are to
make periodic visits to the other country and ``review the
activities'' of the two working groups with regular political
consultations between the two foreign ministries.
   A similar protocol between the two countries was signed in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
