<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HongKong-Hostage     02-24 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong-Hostage,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Rescue Hostages Held 9 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed a Social Welfare Department
office in a cloud of tear gas Wednesday and rescued eight hostages
who had been held nine hours by a man with a cleaver.
   One policeman was slightly injured but the eight hostages were
unharmed. The hostage-taker, identified only as Shum, 44, was
hospitalized with head injuries.
   Reports from the scene said Shum was homeless and had applied to
the office for public assistance. He went there Tuesday afternoon
armed with a cleaver and two knives and demanded to see the person
handling his application, police reported.
   When he was told the person was not in, Shum argued with the
staff, who called the police. He locked himself and the employees
inside the office until police broke the door down.
   Robert Yiu, a police spokesman, said officers made their assault
at about 1:45 a.m.
</TEXT>
