<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Steel     02-24 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Steel,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>80,000 Protest Loss of Steel Industry Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUISBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 80,000 people joined hands
to form a 42-mile link through the industrial Ruhr Valley Tuesday
to protest the loss of jobs in the steel industry, union organizers
said.
   After spending hours forming their line, the demonstrators
joined hands for about 15 minutes, according to the IG Metall labor
union.
   Thousands of people held flares and banners calling for aid to
unemployed steelworkers, while church bells pealed throughout the
area.
   Police said they could not confirm that the human chain ran
unbroken for 42 miles and they did not provide a crowd estimate.
   Traffic was disrupted on main roads during much of the evening.
   The demonstrators formed their line from the Krupp steel works
in Duisburg-Rheinhausen in the western Ruhr region to the
Hoesch-Westfalen steel works in Dortmund.
   Tens of thousands of steel workers are scheduled to be laid off,
retrained or retired early because of the expected closure of steel
plants.
</TEXT>
