<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Afghanistan     02-24 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Afghanistan,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Report Says Afghan Diplomat Defects To West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian newspaper said Tuesday that the chief of
Afghanistan's diplomatic mission in Italy, reported missing since
last week, defected to the West with American help.
   The Foreign Ministry confirmed that the Afghan Embassy reported
last Thursday that Charge d'Affaires Mohamed Nazir Fedaiy, 43, had
``disappeared.''
   But a ministry spokesman declined comment on the front-page
report in the Turin newspaper La Stampa that the diplomat defected
with his wife and was flown to another European country with the
help of U.S. intelligence agents.
   The state-run RAI-TV, without giving attribution, said the envoy
was probably being held under the protection of American agents,
possibly in the United States.
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy said she had no comment on
the case.
   The officials spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   La Stampa said Fedaiy had sought to defect for some time and a
few weeks ago met with a representative of the former king of
Afghanistan and offered him information on his country.
   Former King Mohammad Zaher Shah, deposed 14 years ago while
vacationing in Italy, has been mentioned as possibly playing a role
in a peace settlement in Afghanistan. He lives in exile in Rome.
   Italian-Afghan relations are at the charge d'affaires level.
Italy recalled its ambassador from Kabul after Soviet troops
entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to support the communist
government in its battle with Islamic rebels.
</TEXT>
