<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     02-24 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acquaintance Fails to Link Hamadi with Explosives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An acquaintance of Abbas Hamadi
testified Tuesday he could not link the defendant to explosives
that were smuggled into West Germany.
   The Lebanese-born Hamadi is on trial of charges of masterminding
the kidnapping of two West German businessmen in Beirut in January
1987 in a bid to force the release of his brother, Mohammed Hamadi,
held as a TWA hijacker.
   Abbas Hamadi is also charged with smuggling liquid explosives
into West Germany from Lebanon for possible use in terrorist
attacks.
   Rashid Hage, an acquaintance of Abbas Hamadi's, testified that
he and his three sons helped the defendant pick up suitcases from a
train station in the town of Merzig in mid-January 1987. But he
said he did not know what was in the suitcases, nor what Hamadi
later did with them.
   On Jan. 20, Hage's son, Ali, told the court he helped Hamadi
pick up the suitcases and that he suspected the luggage contained
explosives.
   Police found explosives buried in a field near Merzig on Jan.
27, 1987, and said Hamadi had left them there.
   The 47-year-old Hage on Tuesday repeatedly denied any knowledge
of Hamadi's activities.
   In earlier testimony, Hamadi was linked to the Beirut
kidnappings by a West German government official and by transcripts
of wiretapped telephone conversations with his friends and
acquaintainces in West Germany.
   In January 1987, West German businessmen Rudolf Cordes and
Alfred Schmidt were abducted separately in Beirut.
   The abductions followed the Jan. 13, 1987 arrest of Mohammed
Hamadi at the Frankfurt airport.
   Mohammed Hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in
connection with the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA airliner, in which
39 people were held hostage 17 days and a U.S. Navy diver was
killed.
   Schimidt was released in September, but Cordes remains a
hostage. Another West German, Ralph Rudolf Schray, was kidnapped in
Beirut Jan. 27 and is still being held.
</TEXT>
