<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama     02-24 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle May Break with Noriega, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle has
indicated to associates that he may be ready to break his close
links to military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega, according to
U.S. officials.
   The officials, in interviews this week, said any such move would
narrow further Noriega's base of support and possibly hasten his
demise as Panama's dominant political force.
   The Reagan administration looks upon Noriega as the principal
obstacle blocking its goal of an eventual transition to elected,
civilian-led rule in Panama.
   The officials, who asked not to be identified, said Delvalle has
privately expressed his intention for many weeks to distance
himself from Noriega, but they recognize that such a step would
require considerable courage.
   ``We get information from all sorts of sources, including
friends and relatives, that he is about to do something along these
lines,'' one official said. Congressional sources, also insisting
on anonymity, said they have heard the same reports.
   Since last summer, the administration has been publicly
encouraging Panama's military officers to withdraw from politics as
a means of promoting a return to rule by civilians. In the
meantime, much of the U.S. aid program to Panama has been suspended
and Panama has expelled all American aid personnel.
   Two federal indictments against Noriega on drug trafficking
charge added a new dimension to the already strained relationship.
The indictments, handed down in Florida earlier this month,
portrayed Noriega as a key member of an international
drug-smuggling conspiracy. In Congress, opposition to Noriega spans
the political spectrum.
   Delvalle assumed the presidency in 1985 under circumstances that
strongly suggested Noriega had forced his predecessor, Nicolas
Ardito Barletta, from office.
   It was a constitutional succession, but Delvalle has been widely
perceived as no more than Panama's titular head.
   Noriega has maintained that executive authority rests with
Delvalle and that Panama has achieved a full transition to
democracy. Noriega says his U.S. critics are campaigning against
him for the purpose of annulling the Panama Canal treaties, under
which the waterway reverts to Panamanian control at the end of 1999.
   Attempts to obtain comment from the Panamanian Embassy on
Delvalle's purported intentions were unsuccessful.
   For the United States, the stakes in Panama are extraordinarily
high. The administration believes that a democratic, politically
stable Panama offers the best assurance for the continued efficient
operation of the canal.
   The U.S. officials noted that challenging Noriega would not be
an easy step for Delvalle. They said the president's extensive
business interests and his family could be threatened if he breaks
with Noriega. In addition, Delvalle's health is said to be tenuous
because of a heart operation.
   However, the officials said Delvalle has become increasingly
disturbed by his ties to Noriega and that some of his friends have
rebuffed him because of that association.
   Delvalle also may be tempted to act because of Panama's growing
financial crisis. ``The country is falling apart all around him,''
said one source.
   Lawrence Chewning Fabrega, a Panamanian diplomat who resigned
recently in protest over Noriega's rule, said in an interview this
week that the country's financial problems are so severe the
government may not be able to meet its payroll next month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Swaggart     02-24 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart Penalty May Be Stiffened After Wave Of Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assemblies of God leaders, swamped with
protests that the penalty recommended for television evangelist
Jimmy Swaggart's moral lapses was too mild, indicated Wednesday it
may be stiffened.
   A torrent of complaining telephone calls has poured into the
denomination's headquarters here, more than 3,000 of them in the
past two days.
   ``There's a strong sense of moral outrage at the leniency
applied in this case,'' said the Rev. Howard Cummings of Aurora,
Colo., who said he got that assessment from two of the
denomination's top executives.
   A special meeting was called for Thursday of the church's
13-member executive presbytery, which rules on such matters, to
examine the Louisiana state presbytery's recommendation that
Swaggart be suspended from preaching for three months and undergo
two years' rehabilitation.
   Swaggart, known for his harsh denunciations of sexual lapses in
his worldwide TV preaching, was charged with such an offense
himself, although details have not been specified.
   Photographs showing Swaggart with a prostitute reportedly were
given to church officials by rival evangelist Marvin Gorman, who
filed a $90 million suit charging Swaggart with unjustly accusing
him of numerous sexual affairs.
   An unidentified New Orleans prostitute said on ABC-TV Tuesday
night that she had had sex with Swaggart, while other reports
described the case as involving ``pornographic'' activity.
   A suburban New Orleans sheriff said Wednesday that a tattooed
prostitute with an arrest record in Louisiana, Florida and
Tennessee is believed to be the woman photographed with Swaggart
last October.
   Jefferson Parish Sheriff Harry Lee told the State-Times that the
28-year-old woman was rumored to be in Florida on Thursday. He said
he has a warrant for her arrest for failure to show up for a Dec. 9
hearing on a soliciting for prostitution charge.
   The likelihood that Swaggart's penalty may be extended came in
official word that the issue was expected to be turned back to the
Louisiana district, which had proposed the penalty, for
reconsideration.
   That is the prescribed procedure under church bylaws for getting
a punishment revised if it is deemed inadequate.
   If the matter is returned to the state district, a final
decision may not come for several weeks, said Juleen Turnage, the
denomination's information officer.
   Church sources also said the Louisiana district, in announcing
its decision Tuesday, had violated a church bylaw that such
recommendations are not to be disclosed until approved by top
officials.
   ``It created tremendous pressures, appearing that the Louisiana
district was trying to dictate its judgment,'' Cummings said.
   It was learned that some members of Swaggart's board are on the
Louisiana district council, and did not abstain from participating
in the case.
   Asked whether the $12 million that Swaggart contributes annually
to the denomination might have been a factor in the Louisiana
handling of case, Ms. Turnage said, ``It won't affect the decision
here.''
   The church's final verdict, when it comes, will be in accord
with ``the seriousness of the offense,'' Ms. Turnage said.
   An unwritten church precedent is that those involved in sexual
offenses are barred from preaching for at least a year. ``It's
never been less than a year,'' she said.
   Ms. Turlage said a ``high percentage'' of those calling the
church about the Louisiana district's proposal ``were not pleased.''
   ``A lot of people are unhappy with the initial recommendation,''
said the Rev. Richard Champion, editor of the denomination's
weekly, Pentecostal Evangel. But he added, ``Many thought it too
light. Some thought it too severe.''
   Cummings, pastor of 2,000-member First Assemblies of God Church
in Aurora and former district presbyter, said protests at the
lightness of the sentence had come from overseas as well as across
the United States.
   ``Pastors and leaders are deeply concerned about the adverse
effects on young people and church efforts to teach them moral
principles,'' he said, as well as on the ``image of the church and
American Christianity'' generally.
   ``Most pastors take their marriages seriously,'' he said, and to
``give approval to this sentence is to say we're soft on sin.''
   He said some overseas leaders have demanded immediate cutting
off of Swaggart's overseas broadcasts.
   The denomination has 2 million members nationally, and about 16
million in autonomous Assemblies churches overseas.
   ``Nobody is out for blood, or after Swaggart's hide,'' Cummings
said. He said most want the case handled not only with compassion
and forgiveness, but ``with a sense of accountability'' for conduct.
</TEXT>
