<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Church     02-24 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Church,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Indirectly Attacks Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist official who monitors
religious affairs indirectly attacked Thursday a group of Roman
Catholics who organized a petition to the government signed by more
than 300,000 believers.
   Deputy Culture Minister Frantisek Jelinek said ``so-called
activities we have witnessed in recent days not only do not explain
accurately (church problems), but essentially damage'' their
solution.
   Jelinek oversees church affairs in the Czech republic.
   The 31-point petition, said by knowledgeable religious activists
to have garnered 243,000 signatures in Slovakia and about 100,000
in the Czech lands, demands separation of church and state, more
religious education and permission for priests and bishops to fill
vacant positions in 10 dioceses.
   It gained support from Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek and was signed
by far more people than any other document of its kind in 40 years
of communist rule in Czechoslovakia.
   Authorities were slow to comment on the petition, which has
circulated since late December. An article in the Communist Party
daily Rude Pravo last Saturday, however, attacked some points as
unconstitutional, while admitting that some demands, such as the
one for more bishops, were ``natural.''
   In reporting Jelinek's remarks, the state news agency CTK did
not quote him as mentioning the petition. But the comments appeared
directed at petition organizers, who have been attacked in the
state-run media.
   Jelinek was speaking in the Moravian capital of Brno to leaders
of the government-sponsored Pacem in Terris group, a priests'
organization not recognized by the Vatican.
   In Prague, an official at the state office for church affairs
said talks between the Communist authorities and the Vatican on
filling vacant sees will not resume for at least one month. The two
sides met last month but did not report progress.
   The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The government favors Pacem in Terris candidates to fill the
vacant sees. The Vatican wants other candidates. No new bishops
have been named in Czechoslovakia since 1973.
   No official statistics are kept on the number of believers in
Czechoslovakia, but church sources estimate the Roman Catholics
make up about 60 percent of the 15.5 million population.
   Interest in Roman Catholicism and other religions in
Czechoslovakia has revived in recent years, particularly among
young people.
   In an article Feb. 13, the North Bohemian Communist party daily
Pruboj attributed this to what it described as the low morals of
society and suggested the new believers could not be condemned for
turning to religious faith.
   A public show of the strength of religous belief is expected
March 6 in Prague during a Mass for the Blessed Agnes, a
13th-century Czech princess who became abbess of a Prague convent.
She is to be made a saint later this year.
   Czechoslovakia is a federal socialist republic consisting of two
nations, the Czech Socialist Republic and the Slovak Socialist
Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
