<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseSpending     02-24 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Webb Never Complained To Him About Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Navy Secretary James H. Webb never
approached Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci to complain about
proposed Navy budget cuts before Webb quit in anger, Carlucci told
Congress on Wednesday.
   Carlucci said he had heard that Webb was unhappy but said Webb
``never elected to come and talk to me about it.''
   Webb abruptly resigned Monday with a public blast at Carlucci
for rejecting Webb's proposals on the Navy budget, which was
reduced along with budgets for the other services to meet lowered
military spending totals approved by Congress and President Reagan.
   Webb will be replaced by William L. Ball III, a veteran Capitol
Hill lobbyist for the administration.
   Carlucci appeared before the House Armed Services Committee to
defend Reagan's military budget, unveiled last week, and Carlucci's
decisions about how to reduce defense spending by the $33 billion
total approved by Reagan and Congress late last year.
   To meet the lowered spending goals, Carlucci said, he ordered
reductions in ships, helicopters and other hardware and chose to
retain spending for pay raises and training.
   Carlucci pronounced himself committed to the 600-ship Navy, the
fleet size set by Reagan shortly after he took office in 1981 when
the Navy had about 450 ships.
   Carlucci ordered 16 aging frigates mothballed, which will mean
that the Navy will have 580 ships at the end of the current fiscal
year. But Carlucci also pointed out that the Navy would be
authorized to build 17 ships in Reagan's proposed budget.
   ``As most people who've worked with me know, I function with an
open door,'' said Carlucci, a veteran of numerous top government
jobs.
   He said Webb ``never came to me with any protest over the budget
cuts nor was I aware of his intention to resign until the letter
actually landed on my desk (Monday).''
   Carlucci was generally praised Wednesday by legislators who
noted that he had a difficult job, taking office late last year at
about the same time the $33 billion cut was ordered. Because of
that reduction, the proposed Pentagon budget for the next fiscal
year will be $299 billion.
   Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., ranking Republican on the panel,
referred to Webb and noted, ``I don't understand where this fit of
pique comes from...If anybody's living in fat city, it's the Navy
the past few years. We've worked toward a 600-ship Navy, that's
fine, but there's nothing magic about that.''
   He criticized Webb for what Dickinson said was ``ill grace.''
   Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Stafff, also disputed Webb's statements that the Joint Chiefs had
opposed Carlucci's plan to mothball the 16 frigates. Webb said the
ships should have instead been transferred to the reserves, where
they could later be returned to the active fleet.
   Crowe said didn't support putting the ships into the reserve
fleet.
   Both Crowe and Carlucci reiterated their warnings that U.S.
security might be damaged if defense budgets are not increased.
   The budget ``reflects significant force structure reductions _
fewer ships, fewer aircraft, fewer weapons systems _ that have
long-term implications for our national security,'' said Carlucci.
   He added: ``We must weigh carefully our future decisions on
defense budgets and programs if we are not to reverse the
substantial achievements in our military forces realized at great
cost over the last seven years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
