<DOCNO> AP880224-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2108EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FemaleCondom     02-24 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Female Condom,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Female Condom Being Tested in Europe and United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new ``condom for females'' pioneered in Europe
will be tested this spring in the United States, and its developers
predicted Wednesday it would be a major weapon in the fight against
AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
   The new disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane,
resembles a condom but is worn by women, researchers said Wednesday
as they unveiled the device.
   ``It takes the advantages of both the male condom and the female
diaphragm and gets rid of significant disadvantages,'' said Mary
Ann Leeper, head of the research team developing the device for
Wisconsin Pharmacal Co., which will market it in the United States
and Canada.
   But Dr. Gerald Zatuchni, a gynecologist with 25 years experience
in researching and developing new contraceptives, said he saw the
potential for ``real problems'' with the device.
   ``I have not seen the device nor have there been any published
studies that would indicate its acceptability to couples, the
effectiveness of the device in preventing pregnancy or any
side-effects from using the device,'' Zatuchni said.
   The device, known in Europe as a ``fem-shield'' or vaginal
shield, isn't sold anywhere yet, but testing has begun in Europe
and is scheduled to start in the United States in March, officials
said.
   The contraceptive consists of a soft, loose-fitting polyurethane
sheath and two flexible polyurethane rings, Ms. Leeper said.
   One of the rings lies inside the sheath and serves as an
insertion mechanism and internal anchor, fitting against the
woman's cervix much like a diaphragm, she said. The other ring
forms the outer edge of the sheath and remains outside the vagina.
   ``It is no more difficult to insert than a tampon,'' said Dr.
Paul Salmon, who helped organize tests of the device at London's
Middlesex Hospital.
   The company, based in Jackson, Wis., said the device would
provide more protection than the male condom, in part because the
material is stronger than most condoms and covers a larger physical
area, reducing chances of infection or exposure to body fluids.
   ``From a medical perspective, this product is likely to offer
additional protection against sexually transmitted diseases,''
Salmon said.
   It also is more convenient to use than a diaphragm, Ms. Leeper
said, because it doesn't have to be initially fitted by a doctor
and can be inserted up ``six hours before the sex act or six
minutes before.''
   Zatuchni, a gynecology and obstetrics professor at Northwestern
University Medical School in Chicago, said the idea of a
``one-size-fits-all'' condom for women ``would be sort of
ridiculous because women's anatomy varies so much.''
   ``It would be hard to envision such a device staying on during
the act of intercourse,'' he said.
   Ms. Leeper said secure and proper fitting actually would occur
during intercourse.
   She said the company had no estimate on how much the device
would cost consumers.
   The ``female condom'' was developed by an group of gynecologists
and obstetricians headed by Danish gynecologist Dr. Erik Gregersen
and his wife, Bente.
   The device has been tested so far on 80 couples in the United
Kingdom, Denmark and Sweden, and clinical trials are continuing in
Europe, Ms. Leeper said.
   The World Health Organization also plans to conduct clinical
trials in 15 countries, including Brazil, Thailand, Singapore and
African nations battling the spread of AIDS.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is believed to be spread
mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and
from infected mothers to their infants at or before birth.
   Researchers won't have statistics on how effective the device is
in preventing pregnancy or the spread of diseases like AIDS until
additional studies are completed, Salmon said.
   The company hopes to apply to the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration sometime this summer for permission to begin
marketing the device commercially in the United States.
   ``If everything goes as planned,'' Ms. Leeper said, ``this
product will be available to the consumer by the end of the year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
