<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EquityLoans     02-24 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Equity Loans,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves New Disclosure Requirement on Home Equity
Loans</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel voted unanimously Wednesday to
approve legislation requiring additional disclosures for
increasingly popular home equity loans.
   The measure received the full support of the eight-member House
Banking consumer affairs subcommittee, chaired by Rep. Frank
Annunzio, D-Ill., including Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
chairman of the House Banking Committee.
   Similar legislation is expected to be introduced in the Senate
in the near future. Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of
the Senate Banking consumer subcommittee, held hearings last year
on the general subject of home equity loans, in which a home owner
borrows money against the equity in his or her home.
   According to U.S. Housing Markets, a research survey published
by Lomas & Nettleton, the Dallas mortgage banking and financial
services firm, the value of new second mortgages and home equity
loans were to increase to more than $150 billion by the end of 1987.
   Home equity loans totaled $30 billion in 1981, according to the
report, but topped $50 billion in 1984. The popularity of such
loans began mushrooming when a new tax law took effect in January
1987 that limited the deductibility of interest on most consumer
loans, but preserved deductions for home loans.
   The House bill, introduced by Annunzio and Rep. David Price,
D-N.C., would, among other things, put limits on a creditor's
ability to terminate a home equity credit line and demand full and
immediate repayment of the balance due.
   The measure also prohibits the creditor from unilaterally
changing the terms of the home equity credit line agreement and
allows states leeway to provide for additional requirements.
   The Consumer Bankers Association, a group representing retail
banks, savings and loans and credit unions, supported the
subcommittee's action.
   Two major consumers organizations, Consumers Union and the U.S.
Public Interest Research Group, applauded Annunzio for moving the
bill out of the subcommittee but criticized the panel ``for failing
to correct major abuses in the HEL (home equity loan) market.''
   The organizations said panel members promised to work toward
changing the bill when it is considered by the full Banking
Committee.
   Michelle Meier, counsel for government affairs with Consumers
Union, said the present bill ``doesn't do enough to protect
consumers. It doesn't prohibit some fundamentally unfair contract
terms. It only makes the lenders tell you about them.''
</TEXT>
