<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Minnesota     02-24 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Minnesota,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Camp Says Minnesota Showing Demonstrates Electability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's campaign manager on Wednesday
heralded his second-place finish in the Minnesota caucuses as a
``rainbow coalition'' victory and proof that the so-called
electability issue is dying off.
   Jackson got 20 percent of the vote in a state with a voting-age
black population of 1 percent, proof that his appeal went far
beyond the his traditionally strong base among blacks, said Gerald
Austin.
   ``We're thrilled about what happened yesterday,'' he said.
   Observers said there was evidence that Jackson's targeting of
the hard-pressed, blue collar workers may be paying off, although
there were no exit polls to confirm that.
   Austin predicted that as voting occurs in more states, people
will stop talking about whether the fact that Jackson is black
means he can't be elected.
   ``I haven't heard it in a couple of weeks,'' he said of the
electability issue.
   Opinion polls tend to support the notion that Jackson has made
some strides in his effort to reach out out to whites, although
this early in the election season it is not yet clear how much of
that will translate into votes across the country.
   ``Overall, I think he has made a slight inroad into the white
vote. I do not think there's any evidence so far that it has been
substantial,'' said polling associate John Brennan of ABC-TV's
polling operation.
   Pollster Geoffrey Garin of Peter Hart Research Associates said
the firm's polling has consistently found ``that we're looking at
very different Jesse Jackson than in 1984.''
   ``The sense of polarization that was there four years ago really
isn't there this time. There are obviously some white voters who
are not open to Jesse Jackson, but the negatives and the degree of
antagonism ... has really worn out over four years.''
   ``For whites who are either strongly liberal or sort of feel
ignored by the establishment, there is a real sense of sympathy for
the things that Jackson's been saying.''
   Jackson himself makes a particular point of chiding white voters
who think along the lines of ``I like Jackson, I like what he's
saying _ but ...''
   He told a ballroom full of receptive United Auto Workers members
this week that those people ``should move from `but' to
`therefore.'''
   Jackson edged out Sen. Paul Simon for second place after the
Illinois senator had banked heavily on a good showing there.
   Jackson also had targeted the state _ where he got only 2.4
percent of the vote in his 1984 race _ but had spent only four days
campaigning there this time around, and put only about $45,000 into
the state, said Austin. He credited much of the success to
organizing by a devoted crew of volunteers.
   Minnesota political analyst D.J. Leary said Jackson's support
appeared strong among liberal whites and blue collar workers.
Jackson has gone after union worker support across the country,
travelling to many strike locations to back them, including the
Hormel strike in Austin, Minn.
   ``He was doing very well among working people,'' Leary said. He
said he attended a Minneapolis caucus where 44 of the 134
participants supported Jackson, and only one of those 44 was black.
   Austin said Jackson also got strong support from gays in
Minnesota. Jackson had drawn a capacity crowd during a campaign
appearance last week at a Minneapolis church led by a lesbian
pastor.
   In the Super Tuesday primaries on March 8, Jackson expects also
to expand his large base of black supporters into the gay community
and trade union groups, Austin said.
   Nationwide, polls show Jackson has his work cut out for him
among white voters. A CBS-New York Times poll taken last week
showed Jackson was the choice of 3 percent of the white voters, and
13 percent overall.
   In a mid-January poll, he did better, getting 6 percent among
the whites polled, said CBS News Director of Surveys Kathleen
Frankovic.
   However she noted the polls have also shown that he gets ``a
clear measure of respect'' from whites, admiration for his
leadership qualities, and a feeling that he cares strongly about
their problems.
   In Jackson's adoptive home state, a Chicago Tribune poll in
mid-January showed that among 507 Democratic voters, 39 percent
picked him as their first or second presidential choice. The
electorate is 26 percent black.
   Among the whites, 35 said they had a impression of him, and 37
percent reported a negative impression.
</TEXT>
