<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Biaggi     02-24 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel To Hold Off on Biaggi Expulsion Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee has decided to hold
off introducing a resolution calling for the expulsion of 10-term
Rep. Mario Biaggi because he is involved in litigation, according
to a letter released Wednesday.
   The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct will not bring
the matter berfore the House for a vote until ``an appropriate time
can be established with Congressman Biaggi in order to allow for
his particiaption in the floor proceedings,'' the letter said.
   Biaggi, D-N.Y., is appealing his conviction on charges of
accepting illegal paid vacations from an old political friend and
ally. He is also due to be tried on bribery and racketeering
charges in the Wedtech case starting March 7 in U.S. District Court
in New York.
   The ethics committee announced last week it would recommend that
Biaggi be expelled for violating the House code of conduct by
accepting the vacations and not reporting them on his financial
disclosure forms; obstructing justice; and illegally crossing state
lines to accept the free trips.
   In a 148-page report explaining why it was recommending its most
severe punishment, the 12-member committee said, ``the offenses for
which Representative Biaggi was convicted involved criminal conduct
of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational
responsibilities.''
   Biaggi has vowed to fight the expulsion resolution on the House
floor, but his spokesman, Bob Blancato, said the congressman needs
time to prepare his defense. He declined to say how much time.
   A resolution to expel must pass by a two-thirds vote of the
435-member House.
   The last member of Congress to be expelled was Rep. Michael
Myers, D-Pa., in 1980, who had been captured on videotape accepting
a $50,000 bribe in the Abscam sting.
   Biaggi was convicted Sept. 22 of illegally accepting a paid
Florida vacation from Meade Esposito, the former Brooklyn, N.Y.,
Democratic leader. Esposito was seeking government help for Coastal
Dry Dock and Repair Corp., a financially troubled Brooklyn shipyard
which owed $280,000 in premiums to Esposito's insurance brokerage
firm.
   Biaggi was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and a $500,000 fine.
He is free pending appeal.
</TEXT>
