<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0803 02-24 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0803,0891</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike, Violence Reported in Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-10 UPDATE with details of shooting, giving names,
describing weapon. Picks up 10th graf pvs, An army ... with minor
editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Bank villagers burned the home of a fellow
Arab accused of helping the Israelis and lynched him after he fired
on a crowd Wednesday with a submachine gun, killing a 4-year-old
boy and wounding 13 people, security sources said.
   Israel radio called the event ``a serious escalation'' of 11
weeks of violence in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and
linked it to calls by the Palestine Liberation Organization for
harsh action against collaborators.
   A reporter for the Arabic-language Jerusalem newspaper Al Quds
said residents of Qabatiya village accused the man of collaborating
with Israeli authorities. The reporter, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, identified the man as Mohammed Al Ayad.
   Palestinians began a general strike in the occupied territories
Wednesday and the army reported the first attack on Israeli
soldiers with explosives and firearms since riots began Dec. 8.
   The army said a bomb exploded on a road near Gaza as a military
vehicle passed at about 11 p.m. Tuesday and shots were fired at the
soldiers, but no one was injured.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz arrives in Jerusalem on
Thursday to discuss a new U.S. plan for ending the unrest and
reviving negotiations for Middle East peace.
   Israel radio said hundreds of residents marched to the suspected
collaborator's house in Qabatiya, near Jenin, 60 miles north of
Jerusalem, and destroyed it with firebombs.
   Security sources said the man killed the boy and wounded the
others when he fired from the house at the attackers.
   The national Itim news agency said Ayad fired an Uzi submachine
gun and that after the shooting, people dragged him away and hanged
him. Security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the report, saying the man was strung up on a utility
pole.
   The Arab-run Palestine Press Service identified the slain boy as
Mohammed Qassem Abu Zeid Kmeil.
   An army spokesman called it a fight among Arabs and said
soldiers arrived later.
   At least 63 Arabs have been killed by Israelis since the
violence began, according to U.N. figures. About 1.5 million
Palestinians live in the West Bank and Gaza, which Israel captured
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Three Arabs were shot and wounded Wednesday during disturbances
at the Nuserat refugee camp in the Gaza Strip, including a
9-year-old girl, hospital officials said. Several other
confrontations were reported between soldiers and young Arabs
throwing stones and burning tires in the streets.
   Jerusalem's police force has been strengthened for the Shultz
visit by 1,500 officers, to at least twice its normal size.
   The military also provided extra manpower at the request of
Jerusalem police, an army spokesman said.
   No details were available on the attack on the military vehicle.
   Palestinian protesters have avoided using firearms in what they
call ``the uprising'' against Israel, confining themselves to
throwing stones, bottles, and occasionally firebombs. Several knife
attacks have been reported.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat has said arms would not be used at this
stage, but did not rule out using guns and explosives later.
   Escalation of the violence could prompt an even harsher military
response and might cost the Arabs much of the sympathy they have
won abroad.
   In Jerusalem, police said about 20 Arabs were arrested in recent
days on suspicion of taking part in disturbances. All Palestinians
leaving Silwan, an Arab village inside the Jerusalem city limits,
were checked and searched Wednesday.
   A senior police officer at the scene said: ``We are throwing the
book at them: traffic violations, drug trafficking, not paying
taxes. The people in Silwan for the last two months thought they
belonged to Palestine. We are now teaching them they live in
Israel, and they will never forget it.''
   Amnesty International, the human rights organization based in
London, urged Israel to conduct a thorough investigation of human
rights violations.
   ``Sometimes soldiers have found themselves in the immediate
context where some force was necessary, or maybe even gunfire was
necessary, but in our view the step toward firing a combat rifle at
people who are not themselves armed with firearms is a very big
step to make,'' Clayton Yeo, head of research for Amnesty, said on
Israel radio.
   The general strike, called for Wednesday and Thursday by the
underground ``United National Leadership of the Uprising,''
appeared to be almost total.
   Few people were on the streets in the Gaza Strip. In the West
Bank, business was at a standstill.
   Shultz is likely to meet resistance in Jerusalem, particularly
from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, whose right-wing Likud bloc
opposes the secretary's idea of trading land for peace.
   It also appeared Shultz will not be able to meet with
Palestinians during his Mideast shuttle between Jerusalem and Arab
capitals. Those invited say they will not confer with him because
the PLO has forbidden such a meeting in Jerusalem.
   A meeting with Palestinians is considered critical to the peace
effort.
</TEXT>
