<2ND_LINE>AM-National Press Awards,170</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 9 p.m. EST; Time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>National Press Foundation honors Oppel, Turner, Friendly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard A. Oppel, editor of the Charlotte
Observer, and Ted Turner, chairman of the Turner Broadcasting
System, were honored Wednesday night with the National Press
Foundation's awards for journalistic achievements in 1987.
   Oppel received the George D. Beveridge Jr. Editor of the Year
Award for directing the Observer's ``aggressive yet careful''
coverage of the Jim and Tammy Bakker-PTL story.
   Turner was presented the Sol Taishoff Award for Excellence in
Broadcast Journalism for inaugurating CNN as the first 24-hour
television news network.
   In addition, Fred W. Friendly, an educator, media critic and
former president of CBS News, received the Foundation's award for
Distinguished Contributions to Journalism.
   Friendly's selection was based on his contributions to the
quality of American broadcast journalism over more than two decades.
   The National Press Foundation is an independent, non-profit
organization devoted to the support and improvement of journalism.
It offers in-career training and other programs to print and
broadcast journalists.
