<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-PLO     02-24 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assembly to Meet Monday on PLO Mission Closure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 159-nation General Assembly will
convene Monday on the dispute between the United States and the
United Nations over the fate of the Palestine Liberation
Organization mission, U.N. officials said.
   Congress passed an anti-terrorism law ordering the PLO observer
mission closed by March 22, despite a 1947 treaty in which the
United States agreed to let official delegations function in New
York, the U.N. headquarters.
   ``The legislation is really an assault on the independence of
the United Nations and on its integrity,'' said former U.S.
Attorney General Ramsey Clark, who has been providing legal advice
to the PLO.
   State Department and U.N. officials also said closing the
mission would violate the treaty under which the United States
became U.N. headquarters.
   But Attorney General Edwin Meese III has reportedly said he
intends to enforce the measure.
   What plan of action the General Assembly might advance at the
special session is not clear. It has already passed a resolution
calling on the United States to leave the mission alone.
   The PLO and the 21-nation Arab League say the assembly may ask
the International Court of Justice in Holland for a ruling. The PLO
and the league have also said they may ask the assembly to move
from New York to Geneva if the United States closes the mission.
   Clark said binding arbitration, as called for in the treaty, is
the best way to resolve the dipute. He said the PLO would bring
suit in a U.S. court ``only as a last resort.''
   The PLO was given official observer status 13 years ago. Its
mission is a Manhattan townhouse with a staff of three political
officers and two secretaries.
</TEXT>
