<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Doctors-Nicaragua     02-24 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctors-Nicaragua,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Propose US Hospital For Both Sides In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Contra Aid Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors who believe any humanitarian aid to
Nicaraguans must help both sides in the conflict said Wednesday
they are seeking $20 million to set up an American hospital in the
war-torn country.
   They want the money from Congress, which is voting on a
Democrat-sponsored aid package Thursday, but say they'll try to
raise it elsewhere if necessary. The hospital proposal has been
sent to congressional leaders but is not included in the Democrats'
plan.
   Dr. William Burman of the newly formed Pan American Trauma
Association said he and Swiss Dr. Hansjurg Holdener would be
willing to work for one year in Nicaragua to set up the facility
which they said should include three airplanes, 10 ambulances and a
150-bed hospital to treat Sandinista, Contra and civilian victims.
   Burman described the proposal as an unprecedented offer by
American doctors to help the United States provide humanitarian aid
to Central America. He provided a list a dozen doctors supporting
the project and said U.S. doctors would work in Nicaragua for a
salary of no more than $20,000 a year.
   ``There is no way to consider food and clothing for an army
engaged in a war as humanitarian,'' said Chris Orsinger of the
Council on Hemispheric Affairs, which sponsored a news conference
with the doctors and endorsed their project. The council describes
itself as a nonpartisan supporter of democratic political processes
in the Western Hemisphere.
   Burman said he resigned as an assistant professor of orthopedic
surgery at the State University of New York to work full-time on
the Nicaraguan proposal. He and Holdener said they met last
November with medical officials in Nicaragua and toured the area
where the hospital would be set up.
   Burman said East Germany, Cuba and Czechoslovakia all have
hospitals in Nicaragua, which he said are apparently open to all
victims of the conflict.
   He said the U.S. hospital proposal was intended to ``put the
United States' best foot forward in the region and express the
highest ideals of medical ethics.''
   Wilson Morris, an aide to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas,
said congressional leaders had seen the doctors' proposal, but
funding for it it was not included in the Democrats' $30.5 million
Contra aid measure which Wright said he is confident will pass. The
House narrowly defeated President Reagan's proposal for $36.2
million in military and other aid to the Contras three weeks ago.
   The Democrats propose to give $14.6 million for food, clothing,
medicine and shelter for the rebels and about the same amount for
medical aid to Nicaraguan children who are victims of the conflict.
An additional $1.4 million would go for aid to Miskito Indians, who
ended their resistance to the Sandinista government earlier this
month.
</TEXT>
