<DOCNO> AP880224-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     02-24 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montevecchi Opens off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quintessential chanteusse, Liliane
Montevecchi, has brought the songs, the movements, and all the
atmosphere of the cosiest French cabaret to the off-Broadway
Kaufman Theater.
   The petite singer, with gamin face and haircut, wins the
audience before she sings a note. She wears a long-sleeve,
high-neck, black minidress which almost covers her black leotard,
revealing slim, shapely legs in black hose and spike heels.
   When she sings, her voice proves even more winning. And her
jolie, unflappable air delights.
   Draping herself across the top of Joel Silberman's upright piano
to sing what she calls ``New Frangles Tango,'' she says: ``This
song, I have not done it yet once perfectly.'' She flubs the first
line; everybody laughs, and she starts over.
   Miss Montevecchi's show, ``On the Boulevard,'' which opened
Monday night, wisely varies its mood. She dips into bittersweet
regret, a mood which fits a French singer so well _ but only does
it a couple of times. And she throws herself entirely into songs,
but again not too often, fervently raising temperature and volume.
   She has a light touch with humor and exquisite timing.
Introducing Cole Porter's ``You Don't Know Paree,'' her voice is as
beautifully inflected as any dramatic actress conveying emotion as
she says, ``I have friends there. Some are still there and some are
gone.''
   Miss Montevecchi's French-accented English singing has been
heard here before, in ``Nine'' on Broadway. Here, she often moves
directly from one song to the next, so the audience doesn't break
its French enchantement with applause.
   Lighting by Jeffrey Schissler is subtle and effective. Martin R.
Kaufman, who owns the tiny theater, with seats on two sides of the
stage, is the presenter in association with Jean-Claude Baker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Korea     02-24 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Condemns North Korea Over South Korean Jetliner Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday unanimously condemned
North Korea for the bombing last year of a South Korean airliner
that killed 115 people aboard.
   On a 396-0 vote the House approved the resolution, which urges
``other countries, particularly with close relations with North
Korea,'' to adopt sanctions and other measures against the
Pyongyang government.
   ``The bombing was one of the most outrageous acts of terrorism
perpetrated since the end of the Second World War,'' said Rep.
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House subcommittee on Asian
affairs.
   Kim Hyun-hee, a surviving member of an alleged two-agent North
Korean team, confessed on South Korean television that she helped
plant a time bomb on Korean Air Lines Flight 858 before leaving the
plane in Abu Dhabi. The plane exploded off Burma.
   Solarz said the United States has ``fairly persuasive''
independent evidence of North Korean responsility for the bombing.
</TEXT>
