<HEAD>Nationalist Demonstration in Estonia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Armenia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonian nationalists shouted ``Get the Russians
Out!'' in the streets of Tallinn on Wednesday to commemorate the
small Baltic nation's brief generation of independence from the
Soviet Union, which ended in 1940.
   Tass noted the demonstration, the latest expression of unrest
among the nation's more than 100 nationalities. The official news
agency did not say how many people took part, but a Moscow
dissident in touch with an Estonian journalist put the number at
2,500 to 3,000.
   The Associated Press could not get a telephone call through to
Tallinn, the Estonian capital, to verify the reports.
   Wednesday was the anniversary of Estonia's declaration of
independence in 1918. The Soviets took it back in 1940 under a
secret agreement with Nazi Germany.
   Nationalists in Estonia had asked official permission for a
demonstration Wednesday but were refused.
   Alexander Podrabinek, the Moscow dissident, gave this account of
the day's events in Tallinn:
   About 1,000 people gathered in the downtown area late in the
afternoon for an official rally intended as a protest of what the
government called U.S. provocation of Estonian nationalists.
   Nationalists rallied in a Tallinn square Wednesday night at a
monument to Estonian writer Antonu-Hansenu Tammsaare, laying
flowers on it as militiamen watched. Plainclothes police
photographed the protesters.
   An elderly man began speaking to the crowd about Estonian
independence and militiamen tried to take him away, but other
demonstrators intervened. The militiamen backed off and remained at
a distance for the rest of the three-hour rally.
   Speakers shouted ``Independence to Estonia!'' and ``Get the
Russians Out!''
   Authorities brought in a bus with a loudspeaker blaring music
and official propaganda. Demonstrators were invited to hold their
discussion in the warmth of nearby buildings, but most refused.
   No one was detained and the people remaining outside dispersed
on their own.
   Tass quoted Tallinn's mayor, Harry Lumi, as saying people
gathered at the monument to discuss ``the actual problems of
modernity and the historic past of Estonia.''
   Lumi said the demonstrators were invited to go inside buildings
to continue their discussion because it was cold and windy, Tass
said, and quoted him as saying:
   ``There occurred an improvised meeting with leading scientists
of the republic, deputies of the city council. Problems of the
economic development of Estonia, national relations, ecology and
the democratization of society were discussed.''
   Podrabinek said his information came from a correspondent in
Tallinn for the underground weekly ``Express Chronicle,'' which
Podrabinek edits.
   Nationalists in Tallinn also demonstrated on Aug. 23 against the
German-Soviet pact under which the Soviets annexed Estonia.
</TEXT>
