<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dry Day In Most Places, `Lake-Effect' Snow Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Wednesday across much of the Great Lakes region, the
upper Ohio Valley and the central Appalachians, and light rain fell
in southern Florida, while most of the rest of the nation had dry
weather.
   Winds gusting to 35 mph caused ``whiteout'' snow squalls in
eastern Upper Michigan, particularly west of Sault Ste. Marie.
   Up to 8 inches of snow were forecast for the Erie, Pa.,
lakeshore, which receives ``lake-effect'' snow brought by cold air
blowing across the Great Lakes.
   A snow squall warning was posted in upstate New York. Up to 6
inches of snow were reported at Boonville, N.Y., overnight.
   Snow advisories went up across northwestern Pennsylvania and
extreme northeastern Ohio. Three to 7 inches of snow fell in
Astabula County, Ohio, early Wednesday.
   Heavier snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 3 inches at Erie, Pa., and 1 inch at Grand Rapids, Mich.
   Clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed elsewhere across the
nation. Rainfall was largely limited to a few light showers in
southern Florida.
   Northwesterly winds of 15 to 25 mph with a few gusts to around
30 mph were common across the Midwest. The wind, combined with
midday temperatures in the teens and 20s, produced subzero
wind-chill readings across the upper Midwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 80 degrees at Homestead,
Fla., and Fort Myers, Fla. The early-morning low for the nation was
17 below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Thursday called for scattered snow in upper
Michigan, the lower Great Lakes region and the central
Appalachians, and rain in southwestern California.
   Highs were forecast in the 20s and 30s from the Dakotas across
the northeastern quarter of the nation, except from eastern
Minnesota across Upper Michigan, where highs in the teens were
forecast. Highs in the low 60s were forecast for parts of
southwestern Oregon, Louisiana and southern Mississippi, and in the
60s and 70s from California through much of Texas and in Florida.
The rest of the nation will generally have highs in the 40s or 50s.
</TEXT>
