<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Cellist     02-24 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Cellist,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Cellist Accused Of Drug Possession Arrives In Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexei Magarik, a Jewish cellist
imprisoned in the Soviet Union on charges of drug possession,
arrived in Israel on Wednesday after a five-year struggle for an
exit visa.
   Magarik, 28, was accompanied by his wife Natasha, 26, and their
2-year-old son Chaim.
   Magarik, a poet and songwriter, was active in Jewish musical
groups in Moscow. He first applied for an exit visa in 1983.
   In March 1986, Magarik was arrested on his way back to Moscow
from Tbilisi on a domestic flight when airport authorities searched
his luggage and reported finding a cigarette pack containing drugs.
   Magarik said he never saw the pack before, and a blood test
revealed no trace of drugs.
   But he was sentenced in 1986 to three years in prison on charges
of drug trafficking and possession. A year later he was released
after Soviet authorities reviewed his case.
   Magarik's release was attributed to the policy of greater
political openness initiated by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``When I was released from prison I was told that I was the last
of the Prisoners of Zion. But in this great and terrible country,
the Soviet Union, you never can tell who is still being held in
jail,'' Magarik told dozens of friends at Ben Gurion Airport in Tel
Aviv.
</TEXT>
