<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugTesting-Justice     02-24 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing-Justice,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Seeks To Reinstate Drug Testing of Railroad
Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government will seek Supreme Court
review of a ruling that overturned mandatory drug and alcohol
testing for railroad workers, the Justice Department said Wednesday.
   In a 2-1 decision, a federal appeals court in California
declared on Feb. 11 that such testing violates the constitutional
protection against unreasonable search and seizure.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said the government
planned to seek high court review within the next several weeks.
   Brown also said the Justice Department will notify the court
that the government no longer opposes Supreme Court review of
another drug testing case, involving the U.S. Customs Service.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans last year
supported a drug testing program for Customs workers in sensitive
positions such as those involved in drug interdiction. The appeals
court overturned a U.S. District Court decision which had held the
testing to be unconstitutional.
   The Justice Department originally had opposed Supreme Court
review of the Customs Service case because at that time there were
no conflicting decisions from other appeals court circuits.
   The National Treasury Employees Union, which brought the suit
challenging the Customs program, went to the Supreme Court last
summer seeking review.
</TEXT>
