<HEAD>Reports Girl Killed in Anti-Government Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl was shot and
killed Tuesday and three other people were wounded during an
anti-government demonstration in the town of Azua, Radio Commercial
reported.
   It identified the slain girl as Mary Ramirez, 17, and said she
was shot in the head when protesters clashed with police and
soldiers in Azua, 75 miles west of Santo Domingo, the capital. The
brodadcast said another youth, who was not identified, and two
policemen hit by rocks were treated at hospitals.
   Demonstrators had started their protest Monday, stoning cars and
businesses to demand the government build more public works
projects in the town.
   Demonstrations also were reported Tuesday in two other towns,
both involving claims of pollution by the government-owned Rosario
gold mine north of Santo Domingo.
   In Cotui, 60 miles north of the capital, 500 farmers joined the
Rev. Carlos Guerra in a protest at the town's Roman Catholic
church, according to Radio Popular. It said the rally was held at
the end of a 72-hour general strike by Cotui residents.
   A protest demonstration also was held in Bonao, 50 miles north
of the capital, according to local news reports, but no details
were given.
   President Joaquin Balaguer declined comment on the latest
demonstrations. He said Sunday the disturbances were organized by
political opponents, but no oposition party has identified itself
with the protests.
