<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0872 02-24 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0872,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees South African Problem as More Tribal than Racial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This serves as 1st Ld-Writethru to a0872, AM-BRF--US-South
Africa. Top 7 grafs new to UPDATE with Reagan comments; picks up
2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``By acting ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday the U.S.
government was constrained from helping black South Africans
fighting the government partly because of divisions among them.
   Reagan was asked at a news conference whether he had considered
aiding the African National Congress or other groups opposing the
Pretoria government since his administration has aided guerrillas
fighting oppression in other countries.
   ``No, we have not involved ourselves in that, other than things
such as the sanctions and so forth,'' Reagan said. ``We have tried
our best to be persuasive in this very difficult problem.''
   He was asked what the difference was between South Africa and
other countries where the United States is supporting ``freedom
fighters.''
   ``The difference is that we don't have an armed insurrection
going as we have in some other countries and we have a great
division even among the people who are being oppressed,'' he said.
``It's a tribal policy more than it is a racial policy and that is
one of the most difficult parts here.''
   Reagan noted that the State Department had contacted the South
African government earlier Wednesday to object to the government's
banning of anti-apartheid organizations.
   ``They should be working toward a multiracial democracy and not
oppressing political organizations there, and we've made our
feelings clear about that,'' he said.
   The State Department had said it was ``appalled'' by South
Africa's decision to ban political activity by the nation's largest
anti-apartheid group and 17 other opposition organizations.
   ``By acting to outlaw non-violent political activity of these
organizations, the South African government has dealt a severe blow
to efforts to achieve a a peaceful solution to South Africa's
problems,'' State Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   He said the affected organizations represent the aspirations of
a broad cross section of the black community.
   ``We are appalled by the announcement from the South African
government today that it is effectively outlawing the activities of
a large number of organizations,'' Redman said, adding: ``This is a
giant step backward for South Africa.''
   Redman said Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker had
summoned South Africa's ambassador to the State Department to
register ``shock and distress'' over the crackdown.
</TEXT>
