<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0849 02-24 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0849,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filipinos Mark Second Anniversary of Marcos Ouster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with nation marking second
anniversary of Marcos ouster. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church bells rang Thursday and
thousands of Filipinos joined hands in a ``chain for peace'' to
mark the second anniversary of the ouster of Ferdinand Marcos.
   President Corazon Aquino clasped the hands of Defense Secretary
Fidel Ramos and Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa on Epifanio de
los Santos Avenue.
   It was along the broad avenue, known popularly as EDSA, that
hundreds of thousands of civilians rallied to support military
mutineers in the uprising that forced the former president from the
country on Feb. 25, 1986.
   As church bells pealed Thursday, a Philippine air force T-28
swooped low over the crowd dragging a banner reading ``People
Power.'' Police estimated that by 8:30 a.m. (7:30 p.m. Wednesday
EST) about 20,000 people had packed the avenue for the all-day
celebrations.
   Leftists scheduled their own rallies Thursday at which they
planned to accuse Mrs. Aquino of abandoning the reformist goals of
the 1986 revolution. On Wednesday, about 20,000 people marched
along the boulevard and burned an effigy of Mrs. Aquino.
   During celebrations Thursday, armored personnel carriers carried
images of the Virgin Mary in a procession along Epifanio avenue.
Officials said the images were the ones carried by priests and nuns
during the 1986 revolt.
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Jaime L. Sin, archbishop of Manila, said
in a radio broadcast that the celebrations showed ``we want
brotherhood and not bloodshed.''
   In 1986, Sin called on Filipinos to fill the streets to support
mutineers led by Ramos and former Defense Minister Juan Ponce
Enrile.
   They had broken with Marcos, charging him with fraud in the Feb.
7, 1986, presidential election in which he ran against Mrs. Aquino.
The rebels' action galvanized the opposition that began after the
1983 assassination of opposition leader Benigno Aquino, Mrs.
Aquino's husband.
   Marcos fled to Hawaii.
   During a leftist protest Wednesday, about 200 police officers
blocked the road leading to the military's Camp Crame in suburban
Quezon City as helicopters hovered above. The crowd of students,
workers, farmers and Roman Catholic clergy dispersed without
incident after three hours of anti-government speeches.
   The leftist protesters chanted ``dismantle the U.S.-Aquino
regime'' and burned effigies of Mrs. Aquino. Red banners said
``Advance the People's Genuine Revolution'' and one poster read:
``Cory _ Closet Dictator.''
   ``We had high hopes when Cory Aquino said she would be the exact
opposite of Marcos. But after two years, we have no more hope that
she will fulfill her promises,'' Crispin Beltran, head of the
militant May First Movement labor organization, told the rally.
   People distributed leaflets of the outlawed National Democractic
Front, the umbrella organization of 12 Marxist groups including the
Communist Party and its armed wing, the New People's Army.
   ``The Aquino government has betrayed the Filipino people's hope
for fundamental changes in society after ousting Marcos...,'' the
Democratic Front statement said.
   Also Wednesday, Mrs. Aquino denied charges by the wife of a
discredited navy officer that Ramos was involved in a November 1986
coup attempt.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, General Ramos has proven himself not
only now but in the past, especially in his abiding by the
constitution,'' she told reporters. ``He has not been any part of
any coup attempt.''
   Ramos also denied the charges by Marilyn Robles, wife of Capt.
Rex Robles.
   The plot involved killing leftist officials, installing a
military junta and reducing Mrs. Aquino to the role of a figurehead.
</TEXT>
