<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Guatemala-Rebels     02-24 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Rebels,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Agrees to Mediate Talks With Rebels, Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic prelate of Guatemala
offered Wednesday to mediate peace talks between the government of
President Vinicio Cerezo and leftist guerrillas who have waged a
sporadic war since 1960.
   Monsignor Prospero Penados del Barrio told reporters he accepted
a request to act as mediator from the general command of the
Guatemalan National Revolutionary Union, which is made up of three
leftist armies.
   There was no immediate comment from the president's office.
   The archbishop told at a news conference, ``We would carry out
our mediation at any place, whether it be proposed by the
guerrillas or by the government, since the important thing is to
end the fratricidal fight that ... has served to blind useful
lives.''
   He said the first round of talks should be held before Holy Week
at the end of March.
   The talks would be held in accordance with a Central American
peace plan signed last August by the presidents of Guatemala,
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras and Costa Rica.
   Asked about the talks, Defense Minister Gen. Hector Alejandro
Gramajo Morales said the army ``is very close to achieving a total
victory'' over the rebels.
   ``In a very short time,'' he said, ``the subversive activity in
the country will be ended.''
   He said the guerrillas number 500 to 700.
   Last October, representatives of the government and the
guerrillas met for the first time since the rebels took to the
hills in 1960 after a failed coup attempt. Their four-day talks
were held in Madrid, Spain.
   The talks foundered over the role of the army, how to interpret
the term ``cease-fire,'' and rebel concern over whether the
government can control rightist death squads.
   Foreign Minister Alfonso Cabrera said then that further peace
talks would be pointless and called on the rebels to ``become part
of the country's political and productive framework once again.''
   The request to the archbishop to negotiate new talks was made by
leaders of the three rebel armies in the Revolutionary Union _
Rolando Moran of the Guerrilla Army of the Poor; Gaspar Ilom, a
pseudonym for Rodrigo Asturias, of the Organization of People in
Arms and Pablo Monsanto of the Rebel Armed Forces.
   In ads in local newspapers, the guerrillas said a dialogue with
the government ``is the only way to avoid death and suffering.''
   Gramajo Morales, the defense minister, said the rebels should
put down their arms and rejoin public life before any talks are
undertaken. He said Guatemala was complying fully with the new
peace plan.
   The plan calls for cease-fire talks between the government and
rebels in El Salvador, Guatemala and Nicaragua as a first step
toward democratic elections. It also urges political amnesties and
a ban on all outside military assistance to rebel groups.
   Right-wing death squads have operated for the past decade in
Guatemala, kidnapping and killing labor leaders, suspected
communist leaders and human rights activists.
</TEXT>
