<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ireland, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0948,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Blast in Belfast Kills 2 Part-Time Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-12 UPDATE with two dead, three hurt. Changes
details. Picks up 13th graf pvs, Earlier Wednesday ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb exploded in central
Belfast late Wednesday night, killing two part-time soldiers of the
Ulster Defense Regiment and wounding two others and a civilian
pedestrian, police said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility in a telephoned
statement to Belfast news organizations.
   Belfast police headquarters said in a statement that the
explosion occurred at security gates in Royal Avenue.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said the blast was heard more
than 12 miles away. Police estimated the size of the bomb at 150
pounds. The explosion shattered shop and office windows hundreds of
yards away.
   The police statement said the four soldiers were on patrol in a
Land Rover. It said police believe the bomb was hidden behind an
advertising billboard fronting a building site.
   Police earlier said they believed the bomb was thrown by hand
but later amended this, saying they thought the bombers detonated
it from some distance away using a control wire.
   The vehicle was stationary at the time. One soldier died almost
instantly. The other died later in Belfast City Hospital, police
said.
   They said a 57-year-old pedestrian passing by was slightly hurt.
The army said the two wounded soldiers received only minor injuries.
   Chief Inspector Jim Boyd of Belfast police said the attack
occurred about 11 p.m. when few people were around.
   The locally recruited Ulster Defense Regiment is part of the
British army.
   Wednesday's death brings to at least 2,628 Northern Ireland's
overall toll since sectarian and political violence flared in 1969.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to drive the British from
Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic under socialist
rule.
   Earlier Wednesday, police charged an 18-year-old British soldier
with unlawfully killing an unarmed Roman Catholic civilian.
   A magistrate in Cookstown, 25 miles west of Belfast, ordered
Pvt. David Jonathan Holden held in police custody until his
appearance at a Belfast court on March 9.
   The defense said Holden will plead innocent to the charge of
unlawfully killing Aidan McAnespie, 23. He was hit Sunday by a
bullet fired from an army observation post at a checkpoint near
Auchnacloy, half a mile from the Irish Republic's border.
   The Irish government angered Britain by launching its own police
investigation.
   Anglo-Irish relations have also been strained by Britain's
refusal to prosecute police officers involved in shooting to death
six unarmed Catholics in 1982.
   British and Irish leaders Wednesday held their first meeting
since October under the auspices of the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement,
which gave Ireland an advisory role in Northern Ireland affairs in
an effort to redress grievances of the Catholic minority.
   Ireland's foreign affairs minister, Brian Lenihan, met with
Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the top British official in
the province. After the meeting, King said they had arranged for
their police chiefs to meet next month to discuss security
cooperation along the border.
   But the Irish government later denied that the two sides agreed
on such a meeting.
   A joint communique issued after Wednesday's talks focused on
proposed British legislation aimed at guaranteeing a fair division
of employment between Catholics and Protestants in Northern Ireland.
   Meanwhile, police in Dublin said they had uncovered a cache of
weapons, including 30 Soviet-made Kalashnikov semi-automatic
rifles, in a makeshift bunker beaneath a shed at Malahide in the
city's northern outskirts.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the weapons
apparently were destined for the IRA and may have been part of four
shipments they believe were smuggled from Libya into Ireland over
the last three years.
   The cache included a dozen rocket warheads, 64 hand grenades,
30,000 bullets and 500 pounds of explosives.
</TEXT>
