<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-Mideast 3rdLd-Writethru a0972 02-24 1124</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Mideast, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0972,1150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Outside Agitators Spark West Bank Troubles</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: When he, with 7 new grafs to include
additional comments; Trims last 7 grafs for length</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday night the
administration has information that suspected terrorists from the
outside have been stirring up trouble in the Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Reagan made his statement in a nationally televised news
conference as Secretary of State George P. Shultz headed for the
Middle East with admittedly little chance of setting up
Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   Reporting on Shultz' mission, Reagan said, ``In the Middle East,
it's time for all parties to rid themselves of old ideas and
stances that cannot work and to begin a serious process of
negotiation and reconciliation.''
   He was not specific, however, and he passed up several
invitations to criticize Israeli action against Arab protesters in
the occupied territories.
   ``We have spoken to the government there and we have also spoken
to the Palestinian leadership because there is every evidence that
these riots are not just spontaneous and home grown,'' the
president said.
   Asked about the Israeli actions against Palestinian protesters,
Reagan said, ``We don't support that sort of thing and we are
trying to persuade all the participants to try to arrive at a
solution representing justice for all.''
   When he was asked to whom he was referring in his statement
about the riots not being ``home grown,'' the president responded,
``We have had information that there have been certain people
suspected of being terrorists, outsiders coming in, not only with
weapons, but stirring up and encouraging the trouble in those
areas.''
   ``Now, that isn't something you can go out and say we absolutely
know, but certainly the violence is both ways,'' the president said.
   He said he could not be more specific ``because I get into areas
there that would be violating security rules, and I don't think I
should.''
   On a related subject, Reagan was asked about reports out of
Geneva that Palestinian Liberation Organization leader Yasser
Arafat might be willing to accept two United Nations resolutions,
which he has scorned in the past and which are the cornerstone of
U.S. policy in the Mideast.
   ``Well, I know that this is one other thing we're pursuing,''
the president said. ``If he really is, and if he is willing to
acknowledge the right of Israel to exist as a nation ... I'm sure
that the secretary of state will be _ is apprised of that fact, and
will see what we can do there.''
   Reagan said his administration would continue to seek ways to
alleviate Israeli-Arab conflict.
   ``That's a goal that I think would ... be one of the greatest
achievements of this administration, if before I leave, we could
bring about a peace in the Middle East,'' he said.
   Before departing for Jerusalem, Shultz added Syria to his
itinerary despite U.S. sanctions against a country the State
Department has condemned as a supporter of terrorism.
   ``When we have an issue to address we're going to address it in
the most effective way we can,'' department spokesman Charles E.
Redman said. He called Syria ``one of the key players in the
region.''
   Sources in Damascus said Shultz would visit on Saturday. Redman
refused to provide a specific itinerary, saying only that Shultz
would make stops in Israel, Jordan, Egypt and Syria, and that he
``was ready to meet with Palestinians.''
   He will remain in the region until next Tuesday when he flies to
London to see King Hussein of Jordan, who is in the British capital
for dental work, and then to Brussels for a summit meeting of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Shultz is leaving his schedule open for a return to the Middle
East next Thursday for a few more days of diplomacy before
returning to Washington on March 6.
   Shultz rates his chances of setting up negotiations as slim, and
said succcess would depend on the Israelis and Arabs moderating
their ``extree positions.''
   At a news conference Tuesday in Brussels, he said ``it's just
possible attitudes have shifted enough.''
   ``Looking forward to it?'' Shultz joshed. ``It's going to be
tough.''
   The U.S. goal is to find a way for Israel and a mixed delegation
of Jordanians and Palestinians to hold negotiations to lower
tensions on the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza.
   Temporary self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs who
live under Israeli control is the short-term aim. Negotiations by
December that leave open the option of a state linked to Jordan is
the projected second step.
   This would mean Israel's surrendering most of the territory it
gained from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Six-Day war. Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir and his Likud bloc do not accept the State
Department's concept of ``trading territory for peace,'' while
Hussein refuses to commit himself to negotiations with an uncertain
outcome.
   The Palestinians, meanwhile, are divided about their objectives
and unable to agree on who would represent them in negotiations.
   ``I don't think many people give me much chance,'' Shultz said
in Brussels. He said he found ``intense skepticism'' even among the
NATO allies.
   ``However,'' he said, ``we do have a few ideas. The engagement
of the United States on an intense basis is welcomed. I believe
that even if the chances are small it's worthwhile trying, and you
can't be too afraid of failing.''
   Shultz will have some good news for Mubarak. A U.S. official
said Wednesday the State Department will notify Congress it plans
to go ahead with a $2 billion, 10-year project to produce M-1 tanks
jointly with Egypt.
   The official, who demanded anonymity, said the project would
involve the first foreign purchase of the top-of-the-line U.S.
tanks. It will be financed from the $1.3 billion in grants that
Egypt receives annually from the United States.
   Shultz returned to Washington Tuesday night to report to
President Reagan on his two days of talks in Moscow. He also met
with visiting Portugese Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva and
spoke to a meeting of the Business Council.
   Ten years ago, the United States, Israel and Egypt produced the
Camp David agreements. This led in 1979 to a peace treaty between
Israel and Egypt and to unsuccessful negotiations over Palestinian
``autonomy,'' or limited self-rule.
   As Shultz weighed a trip to the region this month, many Arab
countries led by Egypt and Jordan informed the United States that
they firmly rejected another interim negotiation based on Camp
David.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who heads the only Arab
country formally to make peace with Israel, called the Camp David
formula ``a thing of the past whose time has ended.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
