<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Feb 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Getting the Best Tax Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The news lately has been anything but comforting
for people getting ready to file their tax returns for 1987.
   When the General Accounting Office made test queries in the
Internal Revenue Service's telephone assistant program for
taxpayers, it says it got wrong answers 39 percent of the time.
   When Money magazine asked 50 professional preparers to compute
the taxes owed by a hypothetical family, no two came up with the
same number. And the preparers' fees ranged from $187 to $2,500.
   A person might conclude from this that the annual exercise of
reckoning up with Uncle Sam is becoming a high stakes game played
under very uncertain rules.
   If you can't rely totally on the IRS's own people for guidance,
and if the professionals appear to be taking no more than educated
guesses, to whom should you turn for guidance?
   Even for middle-income taxpayers, a lot rides on the answer to
that question. You don't want inadvertently to pay a bigger tax
bill than you have to _ but at the same time, you don't want to
venture into territory that invites an IRS audit.
   And the value of, say, a $500 tax saving pales if it costs you
$600 in preparation fees to get it.
   The whole situation is certainly troublesome, but it need not be
cause for panic. As Money magazine describes it, the ``financial
profile'' of its theoretical family was more complicated than most
people in the real world are likely to have.
   The tax reform law that contributed so much to all this
confusion also made it possible for larger numbers of Americans to
file using short forms.
   Furthermore, there have been gray areas for many years in the
black and white of the income tax forms. Though many people
complain about this, few have been eager to give up their favorite
deductions and credits to the cause of ``simplification.''
   Even in the present turmoil, many people relish the challenge of
tackling the tax forms on their own. They reason that it is about
the only chance they get to work for aftertax pay, since a refund
isn't taxable income.
   If you prefer to let somebody else do the work, there are ways
to improve your chances of coming out in good shape.
   First of all, says Robert Smith, an assistant professor of
accounting at Boston University School of Management, it's
important to figure out what kind of help you need.
   If you determine that your situation is pretty simple, for
instance, you don't want to choose a high-priced preparer who
specializes in dealing with top corporate executives or rock stars.
   If you're not sure whether your case is simple or complicated,
Smith suggests asking for a meeting with a preparer simply to
evaluate the degree of service you need.
   ``Get organized as soon as possible,'' Smith says. ``If your
preparer has to spend time sorting through your records, your bill
may be higher.
   ``Organized records reduce the chance that an error will
occur,'' he adds.
   Another incentive not to put the business off until the April 15
deadline approaches: That is precisely the time when preparers are
the busiest and most in demand.
   ``Some firms lower their fees for clients who come in early or
who are willing to have their return filing date extended,'' Smith
observes.
   Should you find that you need continuing and fairly elaborate
tax help, it makes sense to seek out a preparer the way you would a
family dentist, doctor or lawyer.
   As Smith concludes: ``You may establish a long-term relationship
that will save tax dollars for years to come.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Feb 25</NOTE>
