<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 26,0695</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Feb. 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U. S. Catholic Conference has petitioned
the Supreme Court to throw out lower court decisions ordering
extensive records about abortion turned over to a group seeking to
eliminate the church's tax exemption.
   The conference maintained the group, Abortion Rights
Mobilization, has no standing to attack the church's tax exemption,
and that allowing it would invite similar challenges to all
religious bodies by political opponents.
   The group wants the IRS to revoke tax exemption of the church's
functions, national and local _ thousands of parishes, schools,
hospitals, religious orders and other agencies _ on grounds the
church engaged in political activity against abortion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Works of 34 Asian Christian artists offer their
interpretations of faith in a special exhibition, ``That All May be
One,''now touring the United States through the fall.
   The 40 works by artists from Japan, Indonesia, Thailand, Sri
Lanka, Korea, Australia and India are being shown Feb.16-March 18
at Manhattan's Interchurch Center, in New Haven, Conn., March
21-April 15, in Arlington, Texas, May 20-27, and in Purdue, Ind.,
July 13-18, with further showings being arranged.
   The exhibition is being sponsored by the East Asia and Pacific
committee of the National Councidl of Churches.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two interreligious affairs leaders say
Catholic-Jewish relations are undergoing a ``severe time of
testing'' which must not be allowed to undermine the extraordinary
improvements in mutual trust since Roman Catholicism's reforming
Second Vatican Council of 1962-65.
   Eugene L. Fisher, executive secretary of the U.S. Catholic
Bishops' Secretariat for Catholic-Jewish Relations, told a
conference real problems remain, but the past gains are
``irreversible and filled with enormous promise.''
   Rabbi James Rudin, the American Jewish Committee's
interreligious affairs director, said, ``In a world filled with
growing religious fanaticism and extremism, we are planting the
seeds of reconciliation'' between Catholics and Jews. ``This
legacy...must be nurtured for the future.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading evangelical theologian says
continued controversy in the Southern Baptist Convention has
reduced its influence as an evangelical force.
   The Rev. Carl F. H. Henry, a visiting professor at Southern
Baptist Theological Seminary here, said the denomination's
theological-political struggle has produced the image of a divided
denomination, discouraging people from identifying with it.
   ``People in the secular city feel they don't want anything to do
with either'' side in the conflict over Bible interpretation and
organizational control, he said.
   He said energies that would have been devoterd to evangelistic
efforts have been devoted to denominational in-fighting.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Missouri expert in
church-state law contends the confirmation of Justice Arthur
Kennedy to the U.S. Supreme Court may result in reopening religion
cases from the past four decades.
   Law professor Carl H. Esbeck says Kennedy, a Roman Catholic, can
be expected to support government aid to parochial schools, a more
balanced role for religion in public school textbooks, and a
voluntary moment of silence for school children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa, founder of the Missionaries of
Charity and winner of the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize, is to receive
Greek Orthodoxy's third Athenagoras Human Rights Award at a banquet
here Saturday, Feb. 27.
   The award, named for the late Eastern Orthodox Patriarch
Athenagorus, is made by the Archons of the Order of St. Andrew, an
organization of Greek Orthodox laymen.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, a Southern Baptist, received the
award last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A noted church growth specialist says
the ``prognosis for the Sunday school in America is not good,''
with total enrollment in Sunday schools falling from 40.5 million
in 1970 to 26.6 million in 1986.
   Win Arn, head of the Institute for American Church Growth, says
that in 1970, only 10 percent of the adult population said they
received no religious training as a child, while in 1986, the
proportion had climbed to 27 percent.
</TEXT>
