<DOCNO> AP880224-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1337EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-AfghanTalks Adv29   02-24 0927</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Talks, Adv 29,0960</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Geneva Talks Will Take Up Thorny Issues of Afghanistan Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: The main story of a package of four. Note talks begin March
2. Najib, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>An AP Extra</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union both are
pushing for an end to the war in Afghanistan as negotiations in
Geneva enter a decisive stage this week, but complex issues remain
to be settled.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz's talks in Moscow last week
ended on a note of optimism. The Kremlin said again it wants to end
the Red Army intervention that has cost an estimated 10,000 Soviet
lives in what Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called a ``bleeding wound.''
   Pakistan and Afghanistan are negotiating with United Nations
mediation. But the two major players are the Soviet Union, which
intervened in 1979, and the United States, which backs the Moslem
guerrilla forces fighting Afghanistan's Marxist government.
   The Soviet leader sent hopes soaring when he pledged Moscow will
withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops within ten months starting
May 15, provided a peace settlement is signed by Pakistan and
Afghanistan by March 15.
   With the Geneva talks starting Wednesday, Gorbachev's deadline
would leave just 13 days to tie up the package of agreements
designed to end nine years of fighting.
   After a 20-day shuttle between Kabul and Islamabad, U.N.
mediator Diego Cordovez reported early this month ``virtual
agreement'' on the timetable of the Soviet withdrawal. The United
States and Pakistan still would prefer to give the Soviets less
than 10 months to leave.
   In almost six years of negotiations, accords have been reached
on mutual non-interference, on superpower guarantees that
Afghanistan will be non-aligned, and on the return of 3.5 million
Afghans sheltered by Pakistan _ the largest concentration of
refugees in the world.
   But crucial aspects are still unresolved. The major issues:
   _At what stage is the aid to the guerrillas to be cut off?
Gorbachev hinted in a Feb. 8 statement the American support is no
longer a problem.
   But Washington officials have said the timing of the cutoff has
not yet been determined. U.S. supplies reportedly totaled $670
million in 1987. The supplies funneled through Pakistan include
shoulder-fired Stinger missiles said to have downed more than 200
Soviet and Afghan aircraft.
   _How should the withdrawal be phased? Gorbachev has said a
``relatively greater portion'' of the Soviet forces will be
withdrawn rapidly. But a diplomatic source close to the talks, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said there were still ``very
different approaches'' to the pace of the withdrawal.
   _Will the settlement involve Iran, host to another 2 million
Afghan refugees and base for other Moslem resistance groups
pressing for a non-Marxist Islamic government? Iran has refused to
join in the talks but says it will accept any settlement satisfying
the ``legitimate aspirations'' of the Afghan people.
   The most difficult question, however, is outside the scope of
the Geneva talks: Who will sign for Afghanistan and what government
will be installed in Kabul during the withdrawal?
   Pakistan argues that a durable settlement requires the prior
formation of a ``broad-based'' interim government to prevent more
bloodshed and assure the refugees' safe return.
   President Zia Ul-Haq said in an interview in The Washington Post
last month that Pakistan would not sign any settlement with the
present Marxist government headed by President Najib in Kabul, the
Afghan capital.
   Pakistan does not recognize Najib's government and insists the
Geneva talks be conducted in an indirect fashion, with Cordovez
acting as go-between. Zia reportedly would like to see an interim
coalition in Kabul, including the anti-Marxist guerrillas, Afghan
exiles and some representatives of Najib's People's Democratic
Party.
   Gorbachev, who assured a visiting Najib in December 1986 that
Moscow would not abandon him, says the makeup of the future
government is an internal matter and ``none of our business.''
   Still, Gorbachev is expected to seek some guarantee to prevent a
bloodbath during or after the troop withdrawal. Otherwise, Najib
and members of his government, as well as departing Soviets, could
be left defenseless against reprisal killings.
   The Soviet Union shares a long border with Afghanistan and there
has been no indication whether the Kremlin will be willing to
relinquish any attempt to influence events in the country once the
Red Army is withdrawn.
   Most of the Pakistan-based groups representing the estimated
200,000 Moslem guerrillas fighting the Soviets and the Kabul
government's army of about 50,000 have ruled out any power-sharing
with Najib.
   Last week, the guerrillas announced plans for a 28-member
transitional Cabinet to replace Najib's government and sign the
Geneva settlement on behalf of Afghanistan ``if the terms are
deemed acceptable.''
   The insurgents vowed they would not lay down their arms until an
Islamic government was established.
   Kabul radio reported that Najib insisted a new government should
be formed after the Soviet forces withdraw and the composition of a
new government is a matter for ``Afghans alone.''
   At the same time, Pakistan is trying to win allies in its push
for an intersion would be similar to President
Reagan's proposal that was narrowly killed by the House three weeks
ago, but would exclude any money for new weapons. It would retain
the CIA as delivery agent for the supplies, and would give
President Reagan the right to seek a new vote on a weapons package
after May 1.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, called the Democratic
proposal ``the most workable kind of program'' and one that will
provide ``balanced incentives'' for the Contras and the leftist
Sandinista government to pursue peace talks called for in a
regional accord.
   The package was unveiled late Tuesday by Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich., after two weeks of intensive negotiations among several
factions of the chamber's majority party. It went before the Rules
Committee today, where Republicans were expected to demand the
right to offer their own alternative.
   President Reagan did not immediately react to the Democrats'
package. His own $36.2 million aid proposal for the rebels,
including weapons, was narrowly rejected by the House three weeks
ago.
   Among major elements in the Democratic proposal:
   _About $3.6 million a month for the Contras: half to buy food,
clothing, medicine and shelter, and the other half to pay for
delivery of the supplies to rebel troops inside Nicaragua. The aid
would run from March 1, after current aid expires, until June 30.
It could continue until the end of the year if a cease-fire is
reached by June 30.
   _About $1.4 million for Nicaragua's Miskito Indians, an
opposition group that has been carrying out its own battle against
the Sandinistas, but has consistently refused invitations to join
with the Contras. The Indians already have worked out their own
cease-fire with the Managua regime.
   _A new $14 million ``Children's Survival Fund,'' to provide
medical help for children on all sides of the conflict. The aid
would be administered by ``non-political'' private aid groups or
international relief agencies already working in the region.
   Not included in the package was any long-term economic
development aid for the region, but a Democratic fact sheet said
``Congress will welcome proposals'' from Reagan on that subject.
   Current aid to the rebels expires Feb. 29, and with it the legal
authority for the CIA to continue air drops of previously
stockpiled weapons and ammunition. The new package contains no such
authority.
   Under the new proposal, the Contras' ``humanitarian'' supplies
would be delivered by private contractors supervised by the Defense
Department until the Contras and the Sandinistas are able to agree
on a cease-fire.
   The deliveries would be monitored by the congressional
intelligence committees and the General Accounting Office,
Congress' investigative arm, to ensure that no weapons were
included.
   After fighting stops, responsibility for delivery would shift to
a private aid group or an international relief agency such as the
Red Cross.
   The package also would provide for an expedited procedure for a
vote on new military aid for the rebels _ a high priority for the
Reagan administration _ if a cease-fire should fall apart and the
Sandinistas should fail to keep their promises to democratize.
   The determination of whether expedited procedures should be
initiated would be made by the House Intelligence Committees,
according to a fact sheet on the package. But Republicans were
skeptical of the provision, saying it was not a solid guarantee
that military aid would come to a quick vote in both the House and
Senate.
   Wright said he was ``not necessarily'' confident of the votes to
pass the package. Republicans have remained aloof from the drafting
process, holding out for more aid and for continued authority for
the CIA to deliver previously stockpiled eapons.
   ``The key to this really will be how much support it gets on the
Republican side,'' said Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., a longtime
Contra aid opponent who added that he planned to vote against the
package.
   Other Democrats said they expected at least 70 in their party to
oppose the proposal.
   ``The party is seeking a middle ground on an issue that is not
compromisable,'' said Rep. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``It appears
to me to be an exercise in attempting to cover ourselves'' and
avoid political blame if the Contras go out of business and the
Sandinistas renege on promises to increase civil liberties.
   Democrats have argued against new military aid, saying that
providing it would endanger peace efforts. Talks between the
Contras and Sandinistas broke off over the weekend without
progress, and no date has been set for their resumption.
   Reagan and many congressional Republicans have countered that it
is only consistent military pressure from rebel attacks that has
forced the Sandinistas into peace talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
