<1ST_LINE>a i AM-AfghanGuerrillas Adv29   02-24 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Guerrillas, Adv 29,0703</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Resistance Leaders Pulling Together On Afghan Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One of a package of four stories.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen turbaned, bearded men with
machine guns patrol a walled villa where the seven leaders of
Afghanistan's guerrilla alliance draw up plans for an Islamic
nation of Afghanistan.
   The meetings have become almost continuous in this dusty
frontier city, a short ride from the Afghan border, since the
Soviet Union announced last month it planned to pull out troops
backing Afghanistan's Marxist government. Moscow said it would
withdraw its estimated 115,000 soldiers within ten months starting
May 15 if Pakistan and Afghanistan sign a peace agreement by March
15.
   With the Geneva talks entering a crucial stage on Wednesday, the
time pressure is helping fuse the often fractious Mujahedeen
guerrilla military alliance into a united political force.
   ``They're closer than before but the question is, for how
long?'' said Abdul Haq, a guerrilla commander from Kabul province.
   So far, the resistance leaders have agreed to install themselves
as a joint executive over a 28-member cabinet that will include
guerrillas, Afghan refugees and Moslems ``presently living in
Kabul.''
   It calls for the head of a cabinet to be head of state, but the
plan contains no names. It proposes to replace the Soviet-backed
Kabul government before an accord is signed at the U.N.-sponsored
talks in Geneva.
   Neither Pakistan, which backs the guerrillas, nor the Afghan
communists appears likely to accept the proposal unchanged. The
Pakistanis have told the insurgents they may have to share power
with the communists, at least in a transitional regime.
   ``We're in a hurry. There is little time,'' said Abdul Qadir
Karyad, head of the political wing of the fervent Moslem party
Hezb-i-Islami, led by Gulbaddin Hekmatyar.
   Although his party is considered the most extreme of the
``fundamentalist'' groups, Karyad indicated the Hezb-i-Islami was
coming around to compromise with the more moderate ones in the name
of unity.
   ``We want to be logical. We want to show the world we can accept
responsibility for our country,'' Karyad said.
   Nevertheless, the guerrillas' blueprint for a new government
does not explain just how it would come to power. It assumes the
Soviet-backed Kabul regime will simply step aside.
   The flurry of compromise follows Pakistan's insistence that an
Afghan settlement must consist of a military accord, such as the
one near completion at Geneva, and a political accord for a
``broad-based'' interim government that could head off a bloody
power struggle as Soviet troops head home.
   The three ``moderate'' guerrilla parties _ Ittehad, the Afghan
National Liberation Front and the National Islamic Front for the
Liberation of Afghanistan _ apparently have dropped their support
of bringing back ousted King Zahir Shah to head a neutral
transitional regime.
   ``It's not really proper to raise the Zahir Shah issue just
now,'' said Zabiullah Mojaddedi, son of ANLF leader Sibghatullah
Mojaddedi. ``We should have a leader from within the Mujahedeen. If
not, then we can consider that option.''
   All seven parties fully agree on one point: They refuse to join
even a temporary coalition with communists.
   ``How can I work in an office with somebody who killed my
brother, my neighbors?'' said Karyad.
   Hezb-i-Islami, along with the Jamiat-i-Islami and the
Hezb-i-Islami faction led by alliance chairman Yunis Khalis, have
gone so far as to threaten to ignore a Geneva accord as long as the
Mujahedeen are excluded from the talks.
   The indirect negotiations have been between the Kabul government
and Pakistan, which serves as the guerrillas' headquarters and
shelters about 3.5 million Afghan refugees. The United States,
which backs the guerrillas, and the Soviet Union are to be the
guarantors of an accord.
   All seven resistance parties say they want to negotiate directly
with the Soviets because they view the Kabul government as Moscow's
puppet.
   ``I hope the Soviets will be wise enough to sit down and discuss
the technicalities (of a withdrawal) with the Mujahedeen,''
Mojaddedi said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb 29</NOTE>
