<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Afghan-Soviet-Glance Adv29   02-24 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviet-Glance, Adv 29,0331</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Soviet Goals in Afghan Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One of a package of four stories.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at what the Soviet Union
hopes to achieve in the March 2 negotiations in Geneva between its
ally, Afghanistan, and Pakistan.
   _ Through their Afghan allies, the Soviets likely will formally
commit themselves to withdrawing their estimated 115,000 troops
starting May 15 and to completing the process within 10 months.
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced the plan on Feb. 8.
   _ The Kremlin is likely to reiterate its demand that the United
States, Pakistan and other Western countries stop supplying weapons
to the Moslem guerrillas fighting the pro-Soviet Kabul government.
The Soviets have suffered heavy losses of aircraft since the United
States and Britain first began sending the rebels Stinger
antiaircraft missiles, which can track and down aircraft by sensing
engine heat.
   _ Gorbachev has said his country wants no say in who governs
Afghanistan or the country's politics after the troops come home.
Even so, he is expected to seek some guarantee that a bloodbath
will not occur during or after the troop withdrawal. Without such a
promise, Afghan leader Najib and members of his government, as well
as departing Soviets, would be left defenseless against a
widespread insurgency, which could lead to reprisal killings.
   _ The Soviets likely will resist any attempts by Pakistan to tie
an Afghan settlement in Geneva to formation of a coalition
government in Afghanistan. Gorbachev said Afghanistan's future
government should be decided as ``an internal matter.'' Ranking
Soviet officials have accused Pakistan of delaying a settlement by
insisting the future government issue be resolved before the troop
withdrawal begins. Soviet First Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli
Vorontsov contended in a Pravda interview published Thursday that
the future government ``has nothing to do with the Geneva
agreements.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb 29</NOTE>
