<1ST_LINE>a w AM-Afghan-US-Glance Adv29   02-24 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-US-Glance, Adv 29,0374</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>US Goals in Afghan Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One of a package of four stories.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at what the United States
hopes to achieve in the negotiations between Afghanistan and
Pakistan in Geneva:
   _ The withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops from
Afghanistan has been a high priority for the White House and
Congress since the Soviet occupation began in December 1979.
   Quick withdrawal remains an immediate goal of the United States,
the anti-Marxist Moslem guerrillas and the pro-Western government
in Pakistan, which has provided sanctuary for 3.5 million Afghans
and channels millions of dollars in covert military aid to the
resistance from the United States, China and Arab nations.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz and other U.S. officials
welcomed the statement by Kremlin leader Mikhail Gorbachev that he
wants to start pulling the estimated 120,000 Red Army soldiers out
of Afghanistan by May 15 if U.N.-sponsored negotiations produce an
agreement by March 15.
   But the Reagan administration is pushing the Soviets to either
shorten their proposed 10-month withdrawal, or to pull out most
troops early.
   ``We don't see any reason why they couldn't be out by the end of
the year if they start in the middle of May,'' Shultz said.
   Under a plan being discussed behind the scenes, the United
States would stop sending military aid as soon as the Soviets began
to withdraw. Half the Soviet troops would withdraw within the first
90 days, 30,000 more over the next 90 days, and the remaining
30,000 over the following four months.
   _ A longer term goal, on which guerrilla groups and the
Pakistani government are split, is over the government to replace
the Soviet-backed regime in Kabul. U.S. officials believe that no
pro-Soviet regime could survive after the Red Army leaves.
   Shultz said this month that the guerrillas would not accept
positions in a government run by President Najib, the head of the
Kabul regime.
   ``It is difficult to imagine how an interim regime is going to
be put together,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb 29</NOTE>
