<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-24 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0546</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governing boards of two of the nation's
largest energy unions have met separately in Denver to discuss a
possible merger, according to a union source.
   Executive boards of the United Mine Workers of America and the
Oil Chemical and Atomic Workers International Union have been
meeting privately in Denver since Monday, the source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said Tuesday.
   Experts said the combination of the unions _ each of which
report about 100,000 active members _ would consolidate the
bargaining power of the two unions in their dealings with major oil
companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that businesses
may not be sued in federal court in certain cases involving their
contributions to union benefit funds.
   The court said Tuesday the federal courts have no authority over
cases in which companies refuse to contribute to multi-employer
union benefit funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires.
   In an 8-0 ruling in a case from California, the court rejected
Reagan administration arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases
could undermine the solvency of the multi-employer pension plans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. surpassed two
competitors last year to reclaim the title of largest U.S. defense
contractor, the Pentagon says.
   In its annual rating of the top 100 military contractors, the
Pentagon said Tuesday that McDonnell Douglas jumped past General
Dynamics Corp. and General Electric Co. to win the top ranking for
fiscal 1987.
   St. Louis-based McDonnell Douglas increased its Pentagon work by
$1.1 billion during the year to a new total of $7.7 billion, easily
surpassing General Dynamics' $7 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Governors' Association has voted
30-5 to support ratification of the U.S.-Canada free trade
agreement despite some governors' fears that it will hurt home
state industries.
   The governors acted Tuesday after amending their resolution to
express ``significant concerns about issues created or not fully
resolved by the agreement,'' and demanding to be consulted on
legislation to ratify and implement the treaty.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nike Inc., which has been using the Beatles'
recording of the song ``Revolution'' in its advertising despite the
group's protests, will discontinue the ads in late March.
   Nike's license to use the Beatles' recording expires next month,
but before it runs out, the company plans to run one more new
commercial with the song, Gerald Sobel, a New York-based lawyer for
the athletic footwear company, said Tuesday. The ad campaign began
last spring.
   The three surviving Beatles, through their recording company,
Apple Records, have claimed they never intended their recordings
for use in commercials.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished little changed Tuesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrial stocks slipped 1.17 to 2,039.12.
   Precious metals futures fell sharply on Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan's predictions of modest economic growth and
continued low inflation. On other futures markets, livestock, meat,
orange juice, grains, soybeans and stock indexes retreated.
   Bond prices rose in response to falling commodity prices and
Greenspan's remarks.
   The dollar mostly was lower in choppy foreign currency trading.
Gold prices also fell.
</TEXT>
