<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Nike-Beatles Bjt   02-24 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nike-Beatles, Bjt,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nike Plans To Drop Ads With Beatles' `Revolution' in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Footwear maker Nike Inc., which has been using
the Beatles' recording of the song ``Revolution'' in its
advertising despite the group's protests, plans to scrap the ads
next month.
   Nike spokesman Kevin Brown said the athletic footwear company
was happy with the results of the ads, which have been running
since last spring, but wants to freshen its advertising approach.
   As a result, he said Nike decided against exercising its option
to use the Beatles' recording for another year.
   Its license to use the recording expires March 22, but before it
runs out, Brown said Nike plans to run one more new commercial with
the song. The new ad, which debuts this week, is aimed mainly at
women, he said.
   Nike's ``Revolution'' commercials to date have shown people
walking, playing basketball and participating in other sports while
wearing Nike shoes. The only sound is the Beatles' recording.
   The three surviving Beatles, through their recording company,
Apple Records, have claimed they never intended that their
recordings be used in commercials.
   Nike, which is based in Beaverton, Ore., has insisted it is an
innocent bystander in a longstanding dispute between Apple and
companies that hold the licensing rights to the Beatle's original
recordings.
   Nike reportedly paid $250,000 to Capitol Records Inc., which
holds the North American licensing rights to the Beatles'
recordings, for the right to use the group's rendition of
``Revolution'' in Nike ads for a year.
   Last July, Apple Records, controlled by the three surviving
Beatles and John Lennon's widow, Yoko Ono, filed a suit charging
that Nike was using the rock group's ``persona and goodwill'' in
its advertising without permission.
   The suit, which is still pending in U.S. District Court in New
York, asked for $15 million in damages and named Nike and its ad
agency, Capitol Records and EMI Records Ltd., which holds licensing
rights outside North America.
   Nike has contended it had a valid contract to use the recording,
intended no disrespect to the Beatles and was an innocent victim in
a dispute between Apple, Capitol and EMI.
   Leonard M. Marks, an attorney for Apple, said he felt the
decision showed Nike was ``being responsive to the lawsuit and the
numerous complaints of Beatles fans'' about its use of the
recordings.
   He said he was optimistic that after Nike's action ``we will be
able to reach a settlement of the case with Nike shortly.''
   But Brown insisted the decision not to renew rights to the music
was unrelated to the suit.
   ``It was a business decision,'' he said. ``It makes sense to
continuously update your ads.''
   He said Nike had received about 150 to 200 letters from people
objecting to Nike's use of the song, but said the company was
generally satisfied with the performance of the ads. He said sales
for the six months ended Nov. 30 were up substantially from the
same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
