<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PSNH-Takeover Bjt   02-24 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PSNH-Takeover, Bjt,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financially Troubled Utility Now a Takeover Target</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Co. of New Hampshire, which
sought bankruptcy-court protection because of the stalled $5.2
billion Seabrook nuclear plant, has attracted takeover interest
from a neighboring utility.
   The proposed takeover disclosed Tuesday by New England Electric
System, based in Westborough, Mass., would not include Public
Service's 36 percent share of Seabrook.
   It also would require approval by a bankruptcy judge, state
regulators in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, both companies'
directors and possibly some federal agencies.
   Public Service, New Hampshire's largest power company and the
lead Seabrook owner, sought federal bankruptcy protection last
month, a move that symbolized the difficulties facing public
utilities with heavy investments in nuclear power. It became the
first major investor-owned utility to seek the refuge of bankruptcy
court since the Depression.
   Under New England Electric's proposal, Public Service, would be
left only with its share of the reactor, which is completed but has
been unable to surmount evacuation-planning obstacles to an
operating license.
   New England Electric subsidiary New England Power Co. owns 10
percent of Seabrook. Officials of the parent company would not
comment on why they don't want to increase their share of the
controversial plant.
   Samuel Huntington, president of the parent company, said in a
statement that the takeover would let the new Public Service pay
its share of the costs of keeping Seabrook ready while plant owners
keep fighting for an operating license. Huntington did not explain
how that would happen.
   A spokesman for Seabrook's joint owners, David Scanzoni,
speculated that ``It would be likely that there would be some kind
of cash infusion that would be part of the arrangement'' to let the
new Public Service maintain its share of Seabrook carrying costs,
estimated at $3 million to $4 million a month.
   Scanzoni said New England Electric would want to continue
supporting Seabrook since it already owns a chunk of the plant.
   ``In many ways this a very positive step for Seabrook Station,''
Scanzoni said of the takeover talks.
   One Seabrook foe said he can't see how the takeover would let
the remaining Public Service pay Seabrook carrying costs on its own.
   ``They can't gt any revenue out of it unless they license it,''
Manchester lawyer Robert Backus noted.
   New Hampshire law bars utilities from charging ratepayers for
power plants before they operate commercially. The state Supreme
Court upheld that law on Jan. 26, denying Public Service an
emergency rate increase and forcing the utility to seek bankruptcy
protection two days later.
   A Wall Street utility analyst, Dan Scotto of L.F. Rothschild
Holdings Inc., said a takeover would make business sense for New
England Electric since aside from Seabrook, Public Service is a
profitable company.
   But ``this is not going to be clear sailing,'' Scotto said,
partly because of unresolved questions about ratemaking authority.
   Scotto also said the proposal indicates New England Electric is
showing a lack of confidence in Seabrook's prospects.
   Evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around Seabrook must be
approved before the plant can be licensed. Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, a Democratic presidential hopeful, has played a
key role in blocking the plant by refusing to submit plans for six
communities in his state within the zone.
   Seabrook has submitted its own plans for Massachusetts. No
hearings have been set on them yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
