<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-PlantExpansion     02-24 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Plant Expansion,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Says Help From Workers Key to Successful Livonia Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVONIA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said it was able to expand
its largest automatic transmission plant without interrupting
production and at less than half the cost of similar projects
because of worker participation.
   ``It truly was a team approach. Each plant area analyzed how the
expansion and quality improvements could be achieved. Issues were
discussed openly and plans were refined to reflect the suggestions
of each team,'' Henry Nickol, general manager of Ford's
transmission and chassis division, said Tuesday.
   The $50 million project added 100,000 units to the plant's
795,000 yearly transmission production while improving quality and
saving 190 jobs without interrupting the assembly line, Ford said.
   The expansion has helped ease a shortage of automatic
transmissions for rear-wheel-drive cars and trucks, particularly
Ford's popular F-series pickup, that use 4.9-liter, six-cylinder
engines and 5.0-liter V-8 engines.
   The F-series pickup was the best-selling vehicle in the United
States in 1986 and 1987, but Ford was forced to offer incentives to
boost sales of manual transmission trucks because it didn't have
enough automatic transmissions, company spokesman Rex Greenslade
said.
   Greenslade said a comparable transmission plant expansion would
have cost $100 million to $150 million.
   Nickol's remarks reflect what has become cliche at Ford, where
top executives never note a new profit, sales or quality
achievement without crediting hourly workers and their cooperation
with management.
   But the employees, hourly and salaried, who have worked together
on the project since September 1986 and who will live with its
results, say it proves that cooperative management is more than a
1980s buzzword.
   ``It's certainly the way we'll go from now on, on any new
program,'' said Jim O'Neill, the Livonia Transmission plant's
manufacturing manager.
   O'Neill said the expansion saved jobs that would have been cut
if efficiency had improved but total production did not.
</TEXT>
