<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0853EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-InsiderTrading     02-24 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Insider Trading,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finance Ministry Council Seeks Tighter Laws Against Insider
Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Finance Ministry committee Wednesday approved a
report calling for tougher laws against insider trading on Japan's
stock markets, where traders say information about companies
frequently is leaked to selected investors.
   The ministry's Securities and Exchange Council approved an
advisory panel's findings, including a recommendation that insider
trading be made a criminal rather than a civil offense. It proposed
that the offense carry a penalty of up to three years in prison and
a fine of up to 3 million yen, or $23,000, ministry officials said.
   The panel also called for a revision of Japan's current
securities and exchange law to specifically prohibit insider
trading, or the use of inside information about companies to profit
on stock markets.
   Other recommendations called for an expansion of the ministry's
investigation powers and a tightening of the definition of actions
falling under insider trading laws, the officials said.
   Ministry officials now will formulate legislation based on the
panel's recommendations to submit to Japan's parliament, probably
this spring.
   Large-scale insider trading is limited in Japan because of the
infrequency of corporate takeovers, analysts say. But leaks of
information about company developments to certain investors is
believed to be frequent, along with stock manipulation by some
large brokerages, financial sources say.
   Japan's markets are dominated by four large securities firms _
Nomura, Nikko, Daiwa and Yamaichi _ creating a climate favorable to
market manipulation.
   The advisory panel began forming its recommendations about two
months ago, after allegations of stock sales by officials at a
chemical company shortly before it announced bankruptcy, news
reports said.
   Implementation of the recommendations will make Japan the last
major industrialized country to adopt such regulations, the Japan
Broadcasting Corp. (NHK-TV) reported.
   The panel said insider trading restrictions should apply to
employees and others inside companies that issue stocks, to
underwriting securities firms, lawyers and certified public
accountants, and to reporters that have access to sensitive
information.
   The report also recommended that securities firms be required to
report the stock ownership of large stockholders.
   The changes are not likely to take effect before the summer of
1989 because of a one-year notice period necessary for the
strengthened criminal penalties, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
