<HEAD>IU Board Supports Dean Witter Offer; Neoax Ups Ante</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 1-2 to CORRECT spelling of company to Neoax; picks
up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, After that ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle for IU International Corp. has
intensified with the company's board of directors first endorsing a
$21.50-a-share buyout from a group backed by Dean Witter Capital
Corp., then Neoax Inc. raising its hostile bid.
   The board announced Tuesday that it had accepted a cash offer
totaling around $650 million from the Dean Witter Group, but
shortly after Neoax sweetened its bid to $22 a share.
   After that occurred, IU issued a statement saying it would
consider other alternatives.
   ``Shareholders will be advised of the board's recommendations
when the board has completed its review.'' said IU spokesman E.K.
Sheldon, refusing to elaborate.
   Neoax, a Stamford, Conn., manufacturing conglomerate, has been
trying since early January to take over Philadelphia-based IU,
which has interests in trucking, food services and waste management.
   Neoax started the bidding on Jan. 6 with an offer of $17.50 per
share, increased it to $19 on Jan. 17 and boosted it to $20 on Feb.
1.
   IU's board suggested shareholders ignore the $20 IU offer,
saying the board was exploring alternatives such as
recapitalization or a leveraged buyout.
   In the agreement between IU and the Dean Witter group, which
includes IU President William H. Waltrip and other IU executives,
Dean Witter would receive up to $15 million from IU if another
bidder acquires a majority of the outstanding shares.
   Neoax, which has acquired about 2.9 million of IU's 30.2 million
shares outstanding, has filed a motion in federal court in
Baltimore seeking to stop payment of that fee.
