<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-LoveCanal 1stLd-Writethru f0007 02-24 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Love Canal, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0007,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Love Canal Ruling Seen Strengthening Environmental Laws</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to explain that amount of liability still
to be determined; picks up 3rd graf, `The judge; INSERTS two grafs
after graf 7, ``The decision,'' with explanation of procedure,
picks up 8th graf, `About 1,300 ...; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's landmark ruling
that Occidental Chemical Corp. was liable for the cost of cleaning
up Love Canal strengthens anti-pollution laws nationwide, a federal
official says.
   After nine years' deliberations, Judge John Curtin ruled Tuesday
that Occidental was responsible because wastes generated by the
company's plant were stored in a way that would eventually result
in leakage.
   A trial expected to start in 1990 will determine the amount of
damages, but state and federal officials say $200 million has
already been spent on the cleanup and estimate that $50 million
more will be required.
   The judge ruled in a 1979 lawsuit filed by the federal
Environmental Protection Agency. In 1978, earlier, toxic chemicals
at Love Canal prompted state officials to evacuate children and
pregnant women, and eventually 728 families. Of those, 175 families
are still waiting to learn whether it is safe to return.
   Curtin's ruling upheld the federal Comprehensive Environmental
Response, Compensation and Liability Act of 1980. The judge said
that law was designed to compel the waste disposal industry ``to
correct its past mistakes and to provide a solution for the dangers
posed by inactive abandoned waste sites.''
   ``This will strengthen environmental laws throughout the
country,'' Roger J. Marzulla, head of the U.S. Justice Department's
Land and Natural Resources Division, said in Washington.
   Frank Ashley, a spokesman for Occidental's parent company,
Occidental Petroleum, based in Los Angeles, said the company did
not agree with the decision and would appeal.
   ``The decision which has just been issued on partial summary
judgment, without a trial and without any factual determination,
that Occidental had acted negligently or with fault contradicts the
resolution of these problems by amicable adjustments reached in
other actions involving Occidental Chemical Corp.,'' Ashley said.
   The law entitles a judge to determine the issue of liability,
and the next stage of the case is a trial to determine the amount
of damages, said Martin Littlefield, assistant U.S. attorney for
the Buffalo district.
   In its motions, Occidental had challenged that procedure.
   About 1,300 former residents of the Love Canal neighborhood
accepted a $20 million damage settlement with Occidental in 1984.
   The eventual amount Occidental pays will depend on costs proved
in court and assessed by the judge. U.S. Attorney Roger Williams'
staff said that $200 million has been spent so far and it is
estimated that there will be $50 million more in costs.
   Lois Gibbs, a former Love Canal resident who runs the Citizen's
Clearing House for Hazardous Wastes in Alexandria, Va., said she
hopes the company will be found liable for the full $250 million.
   ``That will at least make them blink,'' Gibbs said.
   The company said it was covered by insurance and that the
expenses would not adversely affect its finances.
   Occidental contended that it was not responsible for the
landfill because Hooker Chemicals and Plastics Co., which was later
acquired by Occidental in 1968, yielded ownership to the Niagara
Falls School Board in 1953. The board built a school on the grounds.
   Occidental said the construction project broke a clay seal on
the dump and allowed the chemicals to leach into the environment.
The company acknowledged that Hooker dumped 20,000 tons of chemical
wastes into the canal during the late 1940s and early '50s.
   Littlefield, assistant U.S. attorney for the Buffalo district,
said Tuesday's decision was ``a great victory for the state because
it means companies are indeed responsible for what they've done in
years past.''
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams said the decision was ``a
resounding defeat for Occidental's strenuous and expensive public
relations campaign to shift the entire blame for Love Canal.''
   Curtin's ruling does, however, allow Occidental to sue other
parties the chemical giant contends should share the
responsibility. The company is expected to countersue the state,
the city of Niagara Falls and its school board.
   Nunzio Loverdi, president of the Love Canal Environmental Action
Committee, said, ``I think Occidental should accept the decision
and not take action against the city and school board because if it
does we will all suffer. We want to get on with our lives and put
this behind us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
