<DOCNO> AP880224-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TakeoverLaw     02-24 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Takeover Law,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black & Decker Rebuffed In Delaware Law Challenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has rejected Black &
Decker Corp.'s request to block Delaware's new corporate
anti-takeover law, but did not rule on the constitutionality of the
statute.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph J. Longobardi on Tuesday rejected
Black & Decker's request for an injunction against the law, which
it contended was hindering its attempt to acquire American Standard
Corp.
   Black & Decker, a power tool and household appliance maker based
in Towson, Md., has a hostile $68 a share, or $2.12 billion, tender
offer outstanding for American Standard, which is based in New York
but incorporated in Delaware.
   American Standard had rejected two previous Black & Decker
offers, and proposed a defensive recapitalization that analysts
have valued at between $68 and $71 a share.
   American Standard rose 50 cents to $68.75 a share in early New
York Stock Exchange trading. Black & Decker dipped 50 cents to
$18.87{.
   Delaware's new anti-takeover law was enacted on Feb. 2, and
immediately was challenged as unconstitutional by Black & Decker..
   Black & Decker also claimed shareholders of American Standard,
an air-conditioning, plumbing and building products company, were
confused by the law and reluctant to tender their shares.
   But Longobardi rejected the request for an injunction. He ruled
Black & Decker hadn't shown it would suffer irreparable harm under
the law, and therefore would not rule on its constitutionality.
   ``Such a gratuitous discussion of the constitutionality of (the
statute) could be used to upset the balance between the parties in
the quest for their respective positions,'' Longobardi said of the
takeover battle.
   The court also noted that Black & Decker was attempting to take
control of the American Standard board, and if successful then
could exempt the company from the law.
   The boards of directors of Delaware corporations have 90 days
from the law's enactment to exempt their companies.
   Under the law, any shareholder who acquires more than 15 percent
of a company's stock is prohibited for three years from entering a
business combination that would allow the stockholder to acquire
the firm.
   If a takeover is launched before the law is triggered, the
bidder would have to acquire 85 percent of the outstanding shares
in a single transaction to complete the merger.
   John F. Geer, vice president of American Standard, said the
company was ``gratified'' by the decision. Richard L. Templeton,
Delaware's assistant secretary of state, said he was ``encouraged
by the decision.''
</TEXT>
