<1ST_LINE>u f PM-GMJobs     02-24 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Jobs,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM to Restore 1,900 Jobs at California Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said today it will
restore 1,900 jobs at its Van Nuys, Calif., plant on March 14 by
putting both shifts back to work six weeks earlier than expected.
   The announcement came as GM indicated it will be recalling about
8,600 workers nationwide to produce an extra 175,000 cars and
trucks annually.
   The night shift at the Van Nuys plant was elminated Feb. 15
because GM had too much unsold inventory of the Pontiac Firebirds
and Chevrolet Camaros assembled there.
   At the time, GM said it expected the plant would operate with
only one shift until at least May 2 or until the inventory was
reduced.
   In a unique experiment that had run into stiff resistance among
senior workers, all 3,800 of the plant's hourly workers were
affected, with half being off for two weeks at a time, then
returning to their jobs while the others were furloughed for two
weeks.
   The staggered-layoff system was to have continued at least until
May 2, or longer if necessary, GM said.
   Similar systems of staggered layoffs have been tested elsewhere
in the GM system, but at Van Nuys the plan had to be approved in a
vote by workers.
   The vote was required because when the workers agreed in 1986 to
adopt Japanese-style work rules to speed production and cut costs,
the company agreed to negotiate with the union to ease any impact
from changes in staffing levels.
   In an initial vote, the plan was defeated by eight votes, but
after some maneuvering the union agreed to hold a second vote and
to do it at the plant so more workers with less seniority could
cast ballots. The plan was approved on the second vote, despite
grumbling by older workers that making all workers take part in the
furloughs was an attack on seniority rights.
   The Camaros and Firebirds produced at the Van Nuys plant have
been plagued for some time with slow sales. When GM announced plans
for the layoffs earlier this year, the company's inventory of the
two cars was well in excess of 100 days, meaning it would take that
long at existing sales rates to dispose of already-assembled cars.
   Normally, GM operates with about a 60-day inventory on its
various models.
   With both shifts operating, the Van Nuys plant produces about
800 of the two car models daily.
</TEXT>
