<HEAD>New Alliance in Societe Generale Formed To Rival De Benedetti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of shareholders of Societe
Generale de Belgique SA said Wednesday it has formed an alliance
that holds a majority stake in Belgium's largest holding company
and wants to keep its focus in Belgium.
   The group, which includes representation from Belgium, France
and Luxembourg, said it controlled 52 percent of Societe Generale
stock.
   Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti, the president of Olivetti
SpA, whotrols 43 percent, wants to turn the company
into that controls enterprises throughout Europe.
   The shareholder alliance consists of several Belgian and
Lu has said he conxembourg firms led by Groupe AG, Belgium's biggest insurer.
The
group's French members are Compagnie Financiere de Suez, an
investment firm, Companie Generale d'Electricite and Societe
Financiere et Industrielle Gaz et Eaux.
   Suez alone controls 27 percent; Groupe AG and its allies, 16
percent; CGE, 5 percent and Gaz et Eaux, 4 percent, the group said
in a statement.
   On Wednesday, Societe Generale stock closed at a new high of
6,100 francs, or $174.20, up 14 percent from Tuesday's 5,350
francs, or $152.90.
   De Benedetti has offered 4,000 francs, or $114.28, a share for
an additional 15 percent stake in the company. His offer expires
March 4.
