<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Federated     02-24 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federated's Board To Consider Campeau Offer, Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc.'s board of
directors on Thursday will consider a restructuring plan and an
extended merger offer from Toronto developer Campeau Corp., a
spokesman said.
   However, Jim Sluzewski declined Wednesday to disclose the site
for the gathering, which he described as a regular monthly meeting.
   The Cincinnati-based retailer, which operates the Bloomingdale's
department store chain, said the board will review Campeau's
extended $5.85 billion offer for a friendly merger.
   The directors also will review options for a restructuring to
avoid a takeover, including selling its non-department store
assets. Federated said it has been negotiating with unidentified
third parties that have shown an interest in acquiring the company
or its non-department store divisions.
   Federated has resisted Campeau's attempts to acquire the company
in either a friendly merger or a hostile takeover.
   On Monday, Campeau extended its offer to pay $66 per share for
Federated, which has 88.5 million outstanding shares, if the
retailer agrees to a definitive, friendly merger by midnight Friday.
   Campeau said if no agreement is reached by the Friday deadline,
the offer reverts to a hostile, $61-per-share offer.
   Federated has twice rejected Campeau's $66-per-share offer,
saying it didn't think the Toronto-based corporation has the
financing to complete such a deal.
   Federated has about 650 stores nationwide, with sales exceeding
$11 billion last year. It's non-department store assets include
Columbus-based Gold Circle stores, Ralphs supermarkets based in Los
Angeles, and specialty stores including The Children's Place in
Pine Brook, N.J., Filene's Basement in Boston, and MainStreet in
Chicago.
</TEXT>
