<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed To Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed to
higher Wednesday in fairly light trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Corn futures were the most consistent performers, showing
strength throughout the trading session on rumors that the Soviet
Union had purchased as much as 2 million bushels of U.S. corn
overnight, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago for Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Soybean prices lagged for most of the day but ended mixed on a
late surge of buying led by C&D Commodities, a major player in
soybean trading, analysts said.
   Wheat futures ended slightly higher on talk of expected new
export sales to European countries, Gustafson said.
   Gains in wheat prices were limited by an increase in supplies of
wheat for near-term delivery, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.18 a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 2{ cents higher with March at $1.99 a bushel; oats were \ cent
to } cents lower with March at $1.90 a bushel; soybeans were 2}
cents lower to 3{ cents higher with March at $6.24{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
