<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     02-24 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Head Lower After Rally Bid Fizzles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices headed lower Wednesday after an early
attempt to rally fizzled.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
settled at $16.46 per 42-gallon barrel, down 14 cents from
Tuesday's close.
   Among March contracts for refined products, wholesale heating
oil settled at 46.40 cents a gallon, down 0.06 cent from Tuesday,
while wholesale unleaded gasoline closed 0.6 cent lower at 46.30
cents a gallon.
   Linda Simard, an analyst at the Drexel Burham Lambert Inc.
securities firm, said some traders were expecting prices to rise at
the start of the session in the wake of late Tuesday's weekly
report on weekly oil production and supplies.
   The report, issued by the Washington-based American Petroleum
Institute, a trade organization, showed a larger-than-expected
drawdown of heating oil inventories during the week ending last
Friday, but also a larger-than-expected increase in unleaded
gasoline supplies, she said.
   Crude inventories were also slightly lower, according to the
report.
   Ms. Simard said traders ``were looking to sell higher at the
start, but as disappointment set in, the sellers took over.''
   In the end, trading wound up being dominated by technical
factors more than anything else, she added.
</TEXT>
