<DOCNO> AP880224-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 2250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-UMW-OCAW     02-24 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UMW-OCAW,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Reject Proposed Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Mine Workers President Richard Trumka said
Wednesday he considers the union's failed merger with the Oil,
Chemical and Atomic Workers union ``a closed deal'' that won't be
reconsidered.
   OCAW's executive board on Tuesday voted 6-2 to reject a merger
that would have created the United Mine, Energy and Chemical
Workers of America from the two powerful unions. Trumka said the
OCAW board had left open the possibility of reconsidering the
merger, but the UMW's board voted Wednesday to rescind the approval
it gave on Sunday.
   ``I consider it a closed deal,'' Trumka told a news conference.
``Their board was willing to let it go to their constitutional
convention without a recommendation. I flatly rejected that.''
   OCAW spokesman Rod Rogers said the union's executive board was
still involved Wednesday in its regular meeting, and OCAW President
Joseph Misbrener was not immediately available for comment. Rogers
said the issue is not necessarily dead.
   ``It's always possible there could be a resurrection of the
idea,'' he said.
   ``There were compelling reasons why this merger was a good idea,
and those reasons haven't gone away,'' Rogers said. ``This
particular merger proposal is dead, yes, but we could take action
to re-initiate things.''
   Trumka said he was ready to move on, however.
   ``I'll come back at the next (UMW) board meeting and say, `That
didn't work; let's try something else,''' Trumka said. ``We're
going to pursue a policy of growth for our organization.''
   Trumka said the OCAW board rejected the merger agreement because
it ``wanted assurances there would be no dues increase in 1990,''
when the first constitutional convention of the combined union
would have taken place.
   ``There was no way possible I could guarantee that because
delegates at that convention determine what will happen,'' Trumka
said.
   The UMW president said he then convened a meeting of his union's
board, which rescinded its earlier approval of the merger
agreement, which contained no provisions for amendment.
   Trumka said both unions would continue to work together,
especially on negotiations with employers that the two unions have
in common.
   While he plans to look for other ways to expand the UMW's
influence, Trumka said, he does not consider it good policy ``to
merge just for the sake of merging.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880224-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 1655EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Stop&Shop Bjt   02-24 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stop & Shop, Bjt,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dart Vows To Continue Takeover Bid For Stop & Shop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stop & Shop-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. will continue its billion-dollar
hostile takeover bid for Stop & Shop Cos. Inc., which is
negotiating with several other potential buyers, a Dart spokesman
said Wednesday.
   Stop & Shop confirmed Wednesday it had begun talks with several
parties considering a buyout of the supermarket and discount store
chain, raising the possibility it might find a ``white knight''
friendly suitor to thwart Dart.
   Sandy Bouzoukis, a Stop & Shop spokeswoman, declined to name the
parties interested in the Braintree-based company.
   Dart spokesman Stanley Rubenstein said the Landover, Md.-based
retailing concern would continue its hostile $37 a share, $1.03
billion tender offer launched last month. Dart controls about 2.7
percent of Stop & Shop's 27.9 million common shares outstanding.
   ``Dart's position is unchanged. It is premature to respond to
(Stop & Shop) until we know the details of any alternative
proposal,'' said Rubenstein.
   Stop & Shop rose $2.37{ to $41.50 a share Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Boston businessman Thomas Lee reportedly is a possible suitor,
but neither Lee nor Stop & Shop officials would confirm they were
in negotiations.
   Stop & Shop directors rejected Dart's $37 a share offer earlier
this month and filed a federal court suit to block the bid,
claiming Dart did not fully disclose details of past takeover
attempts and had failed to register as an investment company with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Dart countersued, claiming Stop & Shop illegally withheld
corporate information.
   U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel ruled Tuesday that Dart must file
its claim in Norfolk Superior Court in Massachusetts, where eight
separate shareholder suits challenging Stop & Shop's anti-takeover
measures are awaiting a hearing.
   Dart has mounted several unsuccessful but profitable hostile
takeover attempts since selling its Washington-based drug store
chain in 1985.
   The bid for Stop & Shop was Dart's first since it abandoned a $6
billion takeover proposal for Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp.
following the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   Dart, which owns Crown Books and Trak Auto Parts stores
nationwide, also has made unsuccessful but profitable attempts to
gain control of Safeway Co. and Supermarkets General.
   Since 1986, Stop & Shop has sold several unprofitable divisions,
including Medi Mart drug stores and Almys department stores, and
laid off about 450 middle-level workers.
   The company operates 113 Stop & Shop supermarkets and 169
Bradlees discount department stores.
</TEXT>
