<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Honda     02-24 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Honda,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honda Earnings Rise 38.1 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda Motor Co. Ltd. posted a 38.1 percent rise in
profits in the latest three-month period, even though operating
income fell, the company said Tuesday.
   Net income rose to 23.68 billion Japanese yen, or about $193
million, from 17.1 billion yen in a corresponding reporting period
in 1986.
   Honda is shifting to a new fiscal year, so results for the three
months ended Dec. 31, 1987, were compared with results for the
period ended Nov. 30, 1986. Dollar equivalents were based on an
exchange rate of 123 yen to the dollar prevailing at the end of
1987.
   Revenue rose 20.5 percent to 789.5 billion yen, or about $6.42
billion, from 655.3 billion yen a year earlier.
   Honda's income from operations fell 31.4 percent to 32.4 billion
yen, or $263 million, in the quarter, mainly because of the falling
value of the dollar, which decreases the value of U.S. sales when
measured in yen.
   However, Honda's net profit rose because of successful
foreign-exchange trading and decreased income taxes, among other
factors, the company said.
</TEXT>
