<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market made little progress in a
churning session Wednesday, struggling to resume its recent rally
after a pause on Tuesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, off 1.17 on Tuesday,
edged up .83 to 2,039.95.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8 to 7 on the New
York Stock Exchange, 825 up, 715 down and 449 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 212.73 million shares, against 192.26
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index lost
.19 to 148.54.
   Analysts said confidence has slowly been recovering lately after
the market's historic drop last fall.
   The economy has so far shown no signs of suffering any drastic
harm from the crash, and interest rates have fallen since that time.
   But traders have been taking a gingerly approach, recalling how
gains built up over many months were wiped out in a few short days
in October.
   Many Wall Streeters are watching to see whether the Dow Jones
industrial average can surpass the 2,051.89 close it reached on
Jan. 7, which stands as its post-crash closing high.
   Most of the broader market indicators have already surpassed
their January best, betokening the recent superior performance of
many smaller, secondary issues compared with the blue chips that
make up the Dow.
   Navistar, by far the lowest-priced component of the industrial
average, jumped } to 5{ for a gain of 15.8 percent. Some Wall
Street analysts have been recommending the stock lately as a
participant in the recovery in the industrial sector of the U.S.
economy.
   USG jumped 4| to 37 on news of a $42-a-share takeover proposal
from a investment group known as Desert Partners L.P.
   Coastal Corp. was actively traded, down ~ at 29[. Underwriters
priced an offering of 10 million Coastal shares at $29.50.
   Stop & Shop rose 2] to 41{. The company, opposing a $37-a-share
takeover bid by Dart Group, said it is talking with several other
parties about a possible deal.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Eastman Kodak, up | at
41]; USX, up ~ at 32~; International Business Machines, up } at
116[, and Sears Roebuck, up \ at 36\. But Merck fell 2[ to 163\ and
American Telephone & Telegraph was down \ at 29].
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $0.08 billion, or 0.003
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 239.38 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials dropped .71 to
305.06, and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down .59 at 264.43.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 2.06 to 363.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 283.20, up .48.
