<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-88 0809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GlassMerger     02-24 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Glass Merger,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Seeks to Block Glass Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission asked a federal
appeals court Tuesday to stop the merger of two of the nation's
largest manufacturers of glass containers while it appeals a lower
court's refusal to halt the deal.
   The FTC asked the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for a
preliminary injunction to prevent Owens-Illinois Inc., the nation's
second-largest glass container manufacturer, from acquiring
Brockway Inc. for $750 million during the appeal.
   The FTC, which obtained a provisional stay from the appellate
court on Friday, contended that U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens
Green ``erred, both factually and legally, in holding that the
merger is not likely to have anticompetitive effects.''
   The FTC contends that the merger, which would create the
nation's largest glass container manufacturer, would reduce
competition and raise the price of bottles, jars and other
containers the companies make for food, soft drinks and liquor.
   Green, who last week denied the FTC's bid to stop the merger
pending administrative proceedings within the agency, accepted the
companies' argument that competition from plastic and paper
packaging would keep down the prices of glass containers.
   But the FTC said she ``disregarded extensive testimony by
customers accounting for more than $450 million in annual glass
container purchases that they will not or cannot economically
switch from glass containers to other package forms.''
   The agency said Green's opinion ``disregards, without
explanation, long-established legal standards for assessing the
potential anticompetitive effects of horizontal mergers, including
the significance of market concentration and entry barriers, as
well as extensive customer testimony that prices are likely to rise
as a result of the merger.''
   The FTC has stalled the merger since Owens-Illinois, based in
Toledo, Ohio, made its tender offer last September to buy Brockway
stock for $60 a share. Green had granted a temporary restraining
order halting the merger while she reviewed the case, but she
refused to grant a preliminary injunction.
   Owens-Illinois controls 22.7 percent of the market while
Brockway, based in Jacksonville, Fla., controls 15 percent of sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
