<HEAD>Greyhound Agrees To Buy Borax Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greyhound Corp. said Wednesday it has
reached an agreement in principle to purchase the household
products business and assets of the 20 Mule Team division of U.S.
Borax & Chemical Corp.
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
   Among the products made by the Los Angeles-based company are
Borateam dry bleach, Borax powdered hand soap and 20 Mule Team
Borax.
   The product line, which is sold in the United States and Canada,
has annual revenue of about $30 million, company officials said.
   The purchase was negotiated Wednesday by Dial Corp., Greyhound's
consumer products group.
   Dial, with sales of $866 million last year and net income of
$41.4 million, makes such products as Dial and Tone hand soaps,
Purex laundry and household goods and Armour Star canned foods.
   U.S. Borax & Chemical Corp. is a subsidiary of RTZ Corp. PLC of
Britain.
   Greyhound, based in Phoenix, is a diversified company with
revenue last year of $2.5 billion. Its principle operations are in
consumer products, services, transportation, manufacturing and
financial businesses.
