<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   02-24 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0521</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan says
the risk of a recession is as great as the risk of renewed
inflation, but he agrees with the Reagan administration that
neither appears imminent.
   Greenspan made his remarks Tuesday during the Fed's semi-annual
congressional testimony on its conduct of monetary policy.
   Greenspan also confirmed that the central bank had eased credit
slightly a few weeks ago in an effort to keep the economic
expansion alive.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket''
durable goods fell 2.8 percent in January, the biggest decline in a
year, according to the Commerce Department.
   Durable goods orders fell to a seasonally adjusted $112.23
billion last month, a drop of $3.28 billion from December,
reflecting sharp drops in demand for aircraft and primary metals,
the government said Tuesday.
   The steep decline followed a December advance of 4.1 percent,
which was the strongest rise since March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts electric holding company
has begun talks aimed at taking over ailing Public Service Company
of New Hampshire, except for its 36 percent share of the stalled
Seabrook nuclear plant.
   Public Service, the lead Seabrook owner, filed for federal
bankruptcy protection last month.
   New England Electric System, based in Westborough, Mass., said
Tuesday the potential takeover would let Public Service pay its
share of Seabrook preparation costs while its owners keep trying to
get an operating license.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp. has sweetened a hostile
bid for American Standard Inc. a second time, raising its offer to
$68 from $65 per share and promising court action to block the
target's recapitalization plan.
   The latest offer from Black & Decker on Tuesday _ worth about
$2.11 billion _ surprised some analysts who said the bidding was
becoming inflated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. has agreed to pay $1.25 billion to
the government to settle claims it overcharged customers for oil
during the 1973-81 period of price controls.
   The nation's third largest oil company said Tuesday it would
make a first installment of $400 million when the agreement was
closed and pay the rest over the following 5{ years.
   The White Plains, N.Y.-based oil giant is the latest in a series
of companies forced to pay billions to resolve charges they
violated pricing restrictions on crude oil and refined products
during the period of federal controls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled Occidental
Chemical Corp. is liable for the estimated $250 million cost of
cleaning up the Love Canal landfill that became synonymous with
environmental disaster.
   After nine years of deliberations, U.S. District Judge John
Curtin said Tuesday that Occidental produced the wastes that
created the disaster and stored them in a way that would eventually
result in toxic leakage.
   Occidental spokesman James Green said the company was
disappointed by the ruling but would not comment until its
attorneys had studied the decision.
</TEXT>
